{"title_page": "Hollywood marriage", "text_new": "A '''Hollywood marriage''' originally meant a glamorous high society [[marriage]] between [[celebrity|celebrities]] involved in the [[Cinema of the United States|U.S. film industry]]; the word \"[[Hollywood]]\" is often used to represent the US film industry. However, the term has grown to also have strong negative connotations of a marriage that is of short duration and quickly ends in [[Legal separation|separation]] or [[divorce]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D7EDAAAAMBAJ&q=marriage#v=snippet&q=marriage&f=false |title=Jet September 23, 1985 |date=1985-09-23 |accessdate=2011-02-21|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company }}</ref> The term developed the negative connotations fairly early; by the 1930s, a \"Hollywood marriage\" was a marriage both glamorous and short-lived.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gFFkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WnUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1387,4367247&dq=hollywood-marriage&hl=en |title=St. Joseph News-Press \u2013 July 31, 1938 |date=1938-07-31 |accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xRE_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=6k4MAAAAIBAJ&pg=2649,1205199&dq=hollywood-marriage&hl=en |title=The Border Cities Star \u2013 April 3, 1935 |date=1935-04-03 |accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref> This connotation may also have related, at times, to [[moral panic]]s over Hollywood's influence on the culture.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/817968732.html?dids=817968732:817968732&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+23%2C+1933&author=&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=Hollywood%27s+%27Big+Parade%27+To+The+Reno+Divorce+Mill+Result+of+Actors%27+Insatiable+Craving+for+Publicity&pqatl=google |title=\"Hollywood's 'Big Parade' To The Reno Divorce Mill Result of Actors' Insatiable Craving for Publicity\" from the Hartford Courant on July 23, 1933 |publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date=1933-07-23 |accessdate=2011-02-21 |first=J C |last=Moffitt}}</ref>\n\n== Issues ==\n\nSympathetic views of celebrities point out that in Hollywood, it is mostly the bad marriages that are documented by the media, giving a skewed perspective that might make \"Hollywood marriages\" appear to have a worse success rate than they have in reality. In 1972 Bob Thomas of the [[Associated Press]] remarked specifically about the tendency to ignore lasting celebrity marriages with the examples he gave including [[Bob Hope]]'s marriage to [[Dolores Hope]] and [[Rosalind Russell]]'s marriage to producer Frederick Brisson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pTkzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T7cFAAAAIBAJ&pg=931,4090555&dq=|title=AP via The Palm Beach Post \u2013 April 23, 1972}}</ref>\n\nNegative views of Hollywood marriages take the position that the divorce rates are indeed unusually high among celebrities and that this is caused by faults within Hollywood as a culture or by personal faults of the celebrities themselves. They point to the usage of weddings as [[publicity stunt]]s, the egotism or immaturity of celebrities or \"celebrity culture\", and high rates of infidelity or [[promiscuity]]. [[Bee Wilson]], in an article for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', critiqued \"Hollywood marriages\" for often being based on the unrealistic dreams of what she termed \"permanent children\", although she points to some [[Classical Hollywood cinema|classic Hollywood]] couples, like [[Lauren Bacall]] and [[Humphrey Bogart]] or [[Paul Newman]] and [[Joanne Woodward]], as exceptions to these criticisms.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson |first=Bee |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3663142/Movie-stars-plus-marriage-equals-disaster.html |title=\"Movie Stars plus marriage equals disaster\" Daily Telegraph: 11 February 2007 |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=2007-02-11 |accessdate=2011-02-21 |location=London}}</ref> While the introduction to the ''Cultural Sociology of Divorce: An Encyclopedia'' edited by [[Robert E. Emery]] specifically mentions Hollywood divorces as epitomizing a \"consumerist, [[Throw-away society|throw-away]]-marriage view found in the West.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wzJdSIfeeTQC&pg=PR27&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Cultural Sociology of Divorce: An Encyclopedia|first=Robert E.|last=Emery|date=February 21, 2013|publisher=SAGE|via=Google Books|isbn=978-1-4129-9958-8}}</ref>\n\nThe actors and entertainers themselves vary in perspective on the commonality or reason for divorce in Hollywood. In 1961 [[Anne Baxter]] stated Hollywood was \"the most difficult place in America for marriage\" due, in part, to the \"terrible extremes of success and failure\" both spouses may face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pEYyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=POkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3658,2332812&dq=|title=The Miami News \u2013 June 5, 1961}}</ref> In a 1964 interview [[Mitzi Gaynor]], who would remain married to the husband mentioned in the interview until his death (in 2006), took the more \"defensive\" position that \"Hollywood\" couples look different mostly because \"everything we do is magnified.\" Although she conceded they might be slightly different because \"you have to be a little off-center to get into this business in the first place.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LUcqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BE8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=7379,1030430&dq=|title=The Pittsburgh Press \u2013 Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref>\n\nBeyond anecdote or opinion the actual evidence on the matter is complicated by differing definitions of who qualifies as a \"celebrity\" or \"Hollywood.\" That stated a study from [[Radford University]] placed \"dancers and choreographers\" as the occupations having the highest percent currently divorced<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/16/AR2010091607509.html|title=Study breaks down divorce rates by occupation|first=Ellen|last=McCarthy|date=September 19, 2010|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> with \"Entertainers and performers, sports and related workers, all other\" still being above average at tenth. That placed them between \"Nursing, psychiatric, and home health aides\" at ninth and \"Baggage porters and concierges\" at eleventh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/highest-divorce-rates-by-profession-2010-9?op=1|title=The 15 Jobs Where You're Most Likely To Get Divorced \u2013 Business Insider}}</ref> In 1900 \"actors, professional showmen\" were listed as having the highest divorce rate of occupations, but as this predates even the incorporation of Hollywood it refers to the profession itself rather than \"Hollywood\" or \"celebrity culture\" as we know it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.overcomingbias.com/2010/09/low-divorce-jobs.html|title=Overcoming Bias : Low-Divorce Jobs|website=www.overcomingbias.com}}</ref> A [[Forbes]] article placed \"professional athletes and entertainers\" together and with a high divorce rate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://divorce.lovetoknow.com/Divorce_Rate_Statistics_by_Occupation|title=Divorce Rate Statistics by Occupation|first=Shannon|last=Johnson|website=LoveToKnow}}</ref>\n\n== Entertainers married a year or less ==\n\nThe idea that the term \"Hollywood marriage\" equates to something short-term is sometimes displayed by citing celebrities who had marriages that ended in divorce, separation, or annulment within approximately one year. The following examples of that are primarily restricted to marriages involving a notable actor, entertainer or director linked to \"Hollywood\" in some way. Note that the vast majority of the examples are from the 1970s onward; this is in part because [[no-fault divorce]] became legalized in that era, which increased the number of divorces overall.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! width=\"250px\" | Names\n! width=\"80px\" | Length\n! width=\"210px\" | Marriage\n! Notes\n! Source\n|-\n|[[Britney Spears]] and Jason Alexander\n|56 hours\n|January 2004\n|Annulled\n|<