{"title_page": "Peter Brezovan", "text_new": "{{short description|Slovak footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Peter Brezovan\n| image          = Peter Brezovan Brighton vs Spurs (cropped).jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| fullname       = Peter Brezovan\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=y|1979|12|09}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bratislava]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| height         = {{height|m=1.98}}\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = [[M\u0160K Iskra Petr\u017ealka]]\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| years1         =          |clubs1 = FKM Vinohrady                                          |caps1 =     |goals1 = \n| years2         =          |clubs2 = [[FK \u0160KP Inter D\u00fabravka Bratislava|\u0160KP]]               |caps2 =     |goals2 = \n| years3         =          |clubs3 = Slovan B\u0159eclav                                         |caps3 =     |goals3 =\n| years4         = 2000\u20132002|clubs4 = [[1. HFK Olomouc]]                                     |caps4 = 23  |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2002\u20132006|clubs5 = [[1. FC Brno|Brno]]                                    |caps5 = 19  |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2004\u20132005|clubs6 = \u2192 [[FK Inter Bratislava|Inter Bratislava]] (loan)      |caps6 =     |goals6 = \n| years7         = 2006     |clubs7 = \u2192  [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)           |caps7 = 14  |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 2007\u20132009|clubs8 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]                     |caps8 = 52  |goals8 = 0\n| years9         = 2009\u20132014|clubs9 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] |caps9 = 47  |goals9 = 0\n| years10        = 2014     |clubs10 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                        |caps10 = 0  |goals10 = 0\n| years11        = 2014\u20132015|clubs11 =[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]               |caps11 = 6  |goals11 = 0\n| years12        = 2015     |clubs12 = \u2192 [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] (loan)                 |caps12 = 6  |goals12 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = [[Slovakia national under-21 football team|Slovakia U21]]\n| nationalcaps1  =\n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = 19:05, 29 March 2015 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Peter Brezovan''' (born 9 December 1979) is a Slovak [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. He is currently a free agent, following his release from [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] at the end of the 2014\u201315 campaign.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nBrezovan began his career in his native Slovakia with PS Bratislava followed by moves to Vinohrady Bratislava, SKP Dev\u00edn, Slovan B\u0159eclav, 1. HFK Olomouc before joining 1. FC Brno. Brezovan played for [[FK Inter Bratislava]] on loan before he was spotted by [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] boss [[Dennis Wise]] during a trial at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].\n\n===Swindon Town (loan)===\nWise signed the Slovak on a season long loan with view to make the deal permanent later. His Swindon debut came on the opening day of the 2006/07 campaign&nbsp;\u2013 away at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], Brezovan saved two Hartlepool penalties from [[Joel Porter]] and [[Ritchie Humphreys]]. Swindon finished 1\u20130 winners. Following his heroics in the game against Hartlepool and a string of impressive displays, Peter was awarded the PFA Player of the Month award for September{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}.\nFalling awkwardly in the 76th minute of the home game against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on the 14 October 2006, which Swindon won 3\u20130, Brezovan suffered a broken arm.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11758_2393031,00.html Broken arm for Brezovan]</ref>\n\n===Swindon Town===\nOn 29 March 2007 it was confirmed that he had signed a two-year contract with Swindon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/swindon_town/6507821.stm|title=Brezovan signs Swindon contract|date=29 March 2007|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He saved two penalties on his debut for Swindon.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/5226870.stm</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36179584</ref>\n\nIn September 2007 he spent two days on trial with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/everton/7013005.stm|title=Swindon keeper has Everton trial|date=25 September 2007|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 he was on trial at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] but was not offered a contract.<ref>[http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Crewe-Alex-Swindon-stopper-arrives-trial/article-1416961-detail/article.html Crewe Alex: Former Swindon stopper arrives on trial]</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nHe went on trial with [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton and Hove Albion]] in December<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/8389222.stm |title=Brighton give trial to ex-Swindon keeper Peter Brezovan|date=1 December 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He subsequently signed a short-term deal keeping him at the club until January 2010. He made an immediate debut on 5 December in a 1\u20130 away win against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]; a game in which he also saved a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]].<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11719_5752574,00.html Brezovan bags Brighton deal]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/8377107.stm Exeter 0&nbsp;\u2013 1 Brighton]</ref> He stayed with the club for four and a half years before being released in May 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27411393|title=Brighton: Tomasz Kuszczak among six released by Seagulls|date=14 May 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth===\nOn 18 August 2014 he signed for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on a short-term, non-contract basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28834455|title=Peter Brezovan: Portsmouth sign ex-Brighton & Swindon keeper|date=18 August 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> Mainly a backup to [[Paul Jones (footballer, born 1986)|Paul Jones]], he left the club on 1 September.\n\n===Tranmere Rovers===\nOn 1 September 2014, transfer deadline day, Brezovan signed for League Two side [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] on a one-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29020150|title=Transfer deadline day: Tranmere sign Donnelly and Brezovan|date=1 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 6 September in a 3\u20132 loss to Accrington Stanley.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28993413|title=Accrington 3\u20132 Tranmere|date=6 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He made six more starts before losing his place for a long-serving Tranmere Rovers goalkeeper [[Owain Fon Williams]].\n\nPeter joined Southport on a one-month loan on 27 February 2015.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Brezovan Loaned To Southport |url=http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/brezovan-loaned-to-southport-2299849.aspx |publisher=Tranmere Rovers F.C. |date=27 February 2015 |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> He made his debut one day later, in a 5-3 loss at [[Forest Green Rovers|Forest Green]]. The team's form saw a turnaround with Brezovan in goal as he then kept 4 clean sheets in the next 5 games, helping Southport to 4 wins and 1 draw. He was recalled by Tranmere on the 21 March 2015, after [[Owain Fon Williams]] was called up to the [[Wales National Football Team|Wales Squad]]. At the end of the season, that saw Tranmere Rovers relegate out of League Two, Brezovan was released by the club.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rovers Release Seven |url=http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/rovers-release-seven-2443763.aspx |publisher=Tranmere Rovers F.C. |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=20 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506170701/http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/rovers-release-seven-2443763.aspx |archivedate=6 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPeter is married and has one child named Samuel.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{Fotbal DNES|id=3001273}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100507102134/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10433~36888,00.html Peter Brezovan profile] at www.seagulls.co.uk\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brezovan, Peter}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Slovak footballers]]\n[[Category:Czech First League players]]\n[[Category:1. HFK Olomouc players]]\n[[Category:FC Zbrojovka Brno players]]\n[[Category:FK Inter Bratislava players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Slovak expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Slovak expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Slovak footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Peter Brezovan\n| image          = Peter Brezovan Brighton vs Spurs (cropped).jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| fullname       = Peter Brezovan\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=y|1979|12|09}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bratislava]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| height         = {{height|m=1.98}}\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = [[M\u0160K Iskra Petr\u017ealka]]\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| years1         =          |clubs1 = FKM Vinohrady                                          |caps1 =     |goals1 = \n| years2         =          |clubs2 = [[FK \u0160KP Inter D\u00fabravka Bratislava|\u0160KP]]               |caps2 =     |goals2 = \n| years3         =          |clubs3 = Slovan B\u0159eclav                                         |caps3 =     |goals3 =\n| years4         = 2000\u20132002|clubs4 = [[1. HFK Olomouc]]                                     |caps4 = 23  |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2002\u20132006|clubs5 = [[1. FC Brno|Brno]]                                    |caps5 = 19  |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2004\u20132005|clubs6 = \u2192 [[FK Inter Bratislava|Inter Bratislava]] (loan)      |caps6 =     |goals6 = \n| years7         = 2006     |clubs7 = \u2192  [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)           |caps7 = 14  |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 2007\u20132009|clubs8 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]                     |caps8 = 52  |goals8 = 0\n| years9         = 2009\u20132014|clubs9 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] |caps9 = 47  |goals9 = 0\n| years10        = 2014     |clubs10 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                        |caps10 = 0  |goals10 = 0\n| years11        = 2014\u20132015|clubs11 =[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]               |caps11 = 6  |goals11 = 0\n| years12        = 2015     |clubs12 = \u2192 [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] (loan)                 |caps12 = 6  |goals12 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = [[Slovakia national under-21 football team|Slovakia U21]]\n| nationalcaps1  =\n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = 19:05, 29 March 2015 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Peter Brezovan''' (born 9 December 1979) is a Slovak [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. He is currently a free agent, following his release from [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] at the end of the 2014\u201315 campaign.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nBrezovan began his career in his native Slovakia with PS Bratislava followed by moves to Vinohrady Bratislava, SKP Dev\u00edn, Slovan B\u0159eclav, 1. HFK Olomouc before joining 1. FC Brno. Brezovan played for [[FK Inter Bratislava]] on loan before he was spotted by [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] boss [[Dennis Wise]] during a trial at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].\n\n===Swindon Town (loan)===\nWise signed the Slovak on a season long loan with view to make the deal permanent later. His Swindon debut came on the opening day of the 2006/07 campaign&nbsp;\u2013 away at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], Brezovan saved two Hartlepool penalties from [[Joel Porter]] and [[Ritchie Humphreys]]. Swindon finished 1\u20130 winners. Following his heroics in the game against Hartlepool and a string of impressive displays, Peter was awarded the PFA Player of the Month award for September{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}.\nFalling awkwardly in the 76th minute of the home game against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on the 14 October 2006, which Swindon won 3\u20130, Brezovan suffered a broken arm.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11758_2393031,00.html Broken arm for Brezovan]</ref>\n\n===Swindon Town===\nOn 29 March 2007 it was confirmed that he had signed a two-year contract with Swindon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/swindon_town/6507821.stm|title=Brezovan signs Swindon contract|date=29 March 2007|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He saved two penalties on his debut for Swindon.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/5226870.stm</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36179584</ref>\n\nIn September 2007 he spent two days on trial with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/everton/7013005.stm|title=Swindon keeper has Everton trial|date=25 September 2007|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 he was on trial at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] but was not offered a contract.<ref>[http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Crewe-Alex-Swindon-stopper-arrives-trial/article-1416961-detail/article.html Crewe Alex: Former Swindon stopper arrives on trial]</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nHe went on trial with [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton and Hove Albion]] in December<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/8389222.stm |title=Brighton give trial to ex-Swindon keeper Peter Brezovan|date=1 December 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He subsequently signed a short-term deal keeping him at the club until January 2010. He made an immediate debut on 5 December in a 1\u20130 away win against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]; a game in which he also saved a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]].<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11719_5752574,00.html Brezovan bags Brighton deal]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/8377107.stm Exeter 0&nbsp;\u2013 1 Brighton]</ref> He stayed with the club for four and a half years before being released in May 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27411393|title=Brighton: Tomasz Kuszczak among six released by Seagulls|date=14 May 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth===\nOn 18 August 2014 he signed for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on a short-term, non-contract basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28834455|title=Peter Brezovan: Portsmouth sign ex-Brighton & Swindon keeper|date=18 August 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> Mainly a backup to [[Paul Jones (footballer, born 1986)|Paul Jones]], he left the club on 1 September.\n\n===Tranmere Rovers===\nOn 1 September 2014, transfer deadline day, Brezovan signed for League Two side [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] on a one-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29020150|title=Transfer deadline day: Tranmere sign Donnelly and Brezovan|date=1 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 6 September in a 3\u20132 loss to Accrington Stanley.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28993413|title=Accrington 3\u20132 Tranmere|date=6 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> He made six more starts before losing his place for a long-serving Tranmere Rovers goalkeeper [[Owain Fon Williams]].\n\nPeter joined Southport on a one-month loan on 27 February 2015.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Brezovan Loaned To Southport |url=http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/brezovan-loaned-to-southport-2299849.aspx |publisher=Tranmere Rovers F.C. |date=27 February 2015 |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> He made his debut one day later, in a 5-3 loss at [[Forest Green Rovers|Forest Green]]. The teams form saw a turnaround with Brezovan in goal as he then kept 4 clean sheets in the next 5 games, helping Southport to 4 wins and 1 draw. He was recalled by Tranmere on the 21 March 2015, after [[Owain Fon Williams]] was called up to the [[Wales National Football Team|Wales Squad]]. At the end of the season, that saw Tranmere Rovers relegate out of League Two, Brezovan was released by the club.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rovers Release Seven |url=http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/rovers-release-seven-2443763.aspx |publisher=Tranmere Rovers F.C. |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=20 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506170701/http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/rovers-release-seven-2443763.aspx |archivedate=6 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPeter is married and has one child named Samuel.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{Fotbal DNES|id=3001273}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100507102134/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10433~36888,00.html Peter Brezovan profile] at www.seagulls.co.uk\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brezovan, Peter}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Slovak footballers]]\n[[Category:Czech First League players]]\n[[Category:1. HFK Olomouc players]]\n[[Category:FC Zbrojovka Brno players]]\n[[Category:FK Inter Bratislava players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Slovak expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Slovak expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTranmere Rovers:Typo fixing, replaced: teams form \u2192 team's form", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Brezovan"}
{"title_page": "Stupa", "text_new": "{{short description|Mound-like structure containing Buddhist relics, used as a place of meditation}}\n{{redirect|Zedi|people named Zedi|Zedi (name)}}\n\n{{image frame\n| content = {{image array|perrow=2|width=190|height=140\n| image1 = Stupa 1, Sanchi 02.jpg\n| image2 = Samye32.JPG\n| image3 = \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e28\u0e23\u0e35\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e14\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e21\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e21\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07 \u0e40\u0e02\u0e15\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23 (116).jpg\n| image4 = 2016 Rangun, Pagoda Szwedagon (023).jpg\n| caption1 = [[Sanchi|The Great Stupa of Sanchi]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| caption2 = A Chorten in [[Samye]], [[Lhasa]], [[Tibet]]\n| caption3 = [[Wat Phra Kaew|Phra Sri Ratana Chedi]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| caption4 = [[Shwedagon Pagoda]], [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]]\n}}\n| caption = Various architectural styles of Stupa; [[Sanchi]], [[Tibetan architecture|Tibetan]], [[Thai architecture|Thai]], and [[Burmese architecture|Burmese]]\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Buddhist term\n| title = Stupa\n| en = Stupa\n| pi = \ud804\udc23\ud804\udc3c\ud804\udc29\ud804\udc42 (\"thube\"), th\u016bpa\n| mr = \u0938\u094d\u0925\u0942\u092a\n| sa = \u0938\u094d\u0924\u0942\u092a\n| bn = \u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c2\u09aa\n| bn-Latn = st\u032aup\n| my  =\u1005\u1031\u1010\u102e \n| my-Latn =z\u00e8d\u00ec \n| zh = \u7aa3\u5835\u5761\n| zh-Latn = s\u016bd\u01d4p\u014d\n| ja = \u820e\u5229\u5854\n| ja-Latn = sharit\u014d\n| km = \u1785\u17c1\u178f\u17b7\u1799\n| km-Latn = caetd\u0259y\n| ko = \uc194\ub3c4\ud30c\n| ko-Latn = soldopha\n| mn = \u0441\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\n| mn-Latn = suvarga\n| mnw = \n| mnw-Latn = \n| shn = \n| shn-Latn = \n| si = \u0daf\u0dcf\u0d9c\u0dd0\u0db6\u0dca\n| si-Latn = dagoba\n| ta = \u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd\n| te = \u0c38\u0c4d\u0c24\u0c42\u0c2a\u0c02\n| th = \u0e2a\u0e16\u0e39\u0e1b ({{RTGS|sa thup}})<br>\u0e40\u0e08\u0e14\u0e35\u0e22\u0e4c ({{RTGS|chedi}})\n| bo = \u0f58\u0f46\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b\n| bo-Latn = chorten\n| vi = Ph\u00f9 \u0111\u1ed3\n}}\nA '''st\u016bpa''' ([[Sanskrit]]: \u0938\u094d\u0924\u0942\u092a, \"heap\") is a [[mound]]-like or hemispherical structure containing relics (such as ''[[\u015bar\u012bra]]'' \u2013 typically the remains of [[bhikkhu|Buddhist monks]] or [[bhikkhuni|nuns]]) that is used as a place of meditation.<ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O1-chedi.html Encyclopedia.com]. Credited to James Stevens Curl, ''A Dictionary of Architecture and Landscape Architecture'', 2000, originally published by Oxford University Press 2000.</ref> A related architectural term is a [[chaitya]], which is a prayer hall or temple containing a stupa.\n\nIn Buddhism, circumambulation or ''[[pradakhshina]]'' has been an important ritual and devotional practice since the earliest times, and stupas always have a pradakhshina path around them.\n\n==Description and history==\n{{multiple image\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Gordion82.JPG\n| width1   = 160\n| caption1 = <center>The \"Tomb of [[Midas]]\" in [[Gordion]], dated to circa 740 BCE.</center>\n| image2   = Bin Tepe, funeral mound.jpg\n| width2   = 160\n| caption2 = <center>Royal funeral [[tumulus]] of King [[Alyattes]], [[Lydia]], 6th c. BCE.</center>\n| image3   = Amrit Sepolcro - GAR - 1-01.jpg\n| width3   = 80\n| caption3 = <center>[[Amrit]], [[Phoenicia]], 5th c. BCE.</center>\n}}\n{{see also|Cetiya|Tumulus}}\nStupas may have originated as pre-Buddhist [[tumulus|tumuli]] in which [[\u015brama\u1e47a]]s were buried in a seated position<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddhanet.net/stupa.htm |accessdate=2013-01-07|title=Buddhist Art and Architecture: Symbolism of the Stupa / Chorten|date=2006-08-14}}</ref> called [[chaitya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.upenn.edu/coursepages/hist086/material/sanchi.htm|accessdate=2013-01-07|title=THE BUDDHIST STUPA: ORIGIN AND DEVELOPMENT|date=2005-01-13}}</ref>\n\nSome authors have suggested that stupas were derived from a wider cultural tradition from the [[Mediterranean]] to the [[Indus valley]], and can be related to the conical mounds on circular bases from the 8th century BCE that can be found in [[Phrygia]] (tomb of [[Midas]], 8th c. BCE), [[Lydia]] (such as the tomb of [[Alyattes]], 6th c. BCE), or in [[Phoenicia]] (tombs of [[Amrit]], 5th c. BCE).<ref>\"It is probably traceable to a common cultural inheritance, stretching from the Mediterranean to the Ganges valley, and manifested by the sepulchres, conical mounds of earth on a circular foundation, of about the eighth century B.C. found in [[Erythrae|Eritrea]] and [[Lydia]].\" {{cite book |last1=Rao |first1=P. R. Ramachandra |title=Amaravati |date=2002 |publisher=Youth Advancement, Tourism & Cultural Department Government of Andhra Pradesh |page=33 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h-jVAAAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref><ref>On the hemispherical Phenician tombs of [[Amrit]]: {{cite book |last1=Coomaraswamy |first1=Ananda K. |title=History of Indian and Indonesian art |date=1972 |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.52349/page/n313 12] |url=https://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.52349}}</ref><ref>Commenting on [[Gisbert Combaz]]: \"In his study L'\u00e9volution du stupa en Asie, he even observed that \"long before India, the classical Orient was inspired by the shape of the tumulus for constructing its tombs: Phrygia, Lydia, Phenicia .\" in {{cite book |last1=B\u00e9nisti |first1=Mireille |last2=K |first2=Thanikaimony |title=Stylistics of Buddhist art in India |date=2003 |publisher=Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts |isbn=9788173052415 |page=12 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hO9OAAAAYAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Mounds for the relics of the Buddha (5th century)===\n[[File:Stupas-Original-00020.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Piprahwa]] stupa is one of the earliest surviving stupas.]] \n{{Further|Buddhist architecture}}\nReligious buildings in the form of the Buddhist stupa, a dome shaped monument, started to be used in India as commemorative monuments associated with storing sacred relics of the Buddha.<ref name=Ency>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (2008), ''Pagoda''.</ref>  After the [[parinirvana]] of the Buddha, his remains were cremated and the ashes divided and buried under eight mounds with two further mounds encasing the urn and the embers.<ref name=Ency/> The relics of the Buddha were spread between eight stupas, in [[Rajagriha]], [[Vaishali (ancient city)|Vaishali]], [[Kapilavastu (ancient city)|Kapilavastu]], [[Allakappa]], [[Ramagrama]], [[Pava]], [[Kushinagar]], and [[Vethapida]].<ref name=\"BAStupa\"/> The [[Piprahwa]] stupa also seems to have been one of the first to be built.<ref name=\"BAStupa\"/>\n\n[[Guard rail]]s \u2014consisting of posts, crossbars, and a coping\u2014 became a feature of safety surrounding a stupa.<ref name=Chandra>Chandra (2008)</ref> The Buddha had left instructions about how to pay homage to the stupas: \"And whoever lays wreaths or puts sweet perfumes and colours there with a devout heart, will reap benefits for a long time\".<ref name=\"BA143\">Buddhist Architecture, Lee Huu Phuoc, Grafikol 2009, p.143</ref> This practice would lead to the decoration of the stupas with stone sculptures of flower garlands in the Classical period.<ref name=\"BA143\"/>\n\n===Expansion under Ashoka (250 BCE)===\n[[File:Early stupa 6 meters in diameter with fallen umbrella on side in Chakpat near Chakdara.jpg|thumb|An early stupa, 6 meters in diameter, with fallen umbrella on side. Chakpat, near [[Chakdara]]. Probably Maurya, 3rd century BCE.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.173\">Buddhist architecture, p.173</ref>]]\nAccording to Buddhist tradition, Emperor [[Ashoka]] (rule: 273\u2014232 BCE) recovered the relics of the Buddha from the earlier stupas (except from the [[Ramagrama stupa]]), and erected 84,000 stupas to distribute the relics across India. In effect, many stupas are thought to date originally from the time of Ashoka, such as [[Sanchi]] or [[Kesaria stupa|Kesariya]], where he also erected pillars with his inscriptions, and possibly [[Bharhut]], [[Amaravathi Mahachaitya|Amaravati]] or [[Dharmarajika Stupa|Dharmarajika]] in [[Gandhara]].<ref name=\"BAStupa\">Buddhist Architecture, Lee Huu Phuoc, Grafikol 2009, p.140-174</ref> Ashoka also established the [[Pillars of Ashoka]] throughout his realm, generally next to Buddhist stupas.\n\nThe first known appearance of the word \"Stupa\" is from [[:File:Nigali Sagar word Stupa.jpg|an inscribed dedication]] by [[Ashoka]] on the [[Nigali Sagar]] pillar (spelled in [[Pali]] in the [[Brahmi script]] as \ud804\udc23\ud804\udc3c\ud804\udc29\ud804\udc42 ''\"Thube\"'' ).<ref>Amaravati: The Art of an early Buddhist Monument in context. [http://www.britishmuseum.org/pdf/207_Amaravati.pdf p.23]</ref>\n\n===Decorated stupas (from 125 BCE)===\nStupas were soon to be richly decorated with sculptural reliefs, following the first attempts at [[Sanchi Stupa No.2]] (125 BCE). Full-fledged sculptural decorations and scenes of the life of the Buddha would soon follow at [[Bharhut]] (115 BCE), [[Bodh Gaya]] (60 BCE), [[Mathura]] (125-60 BCE), again at [[Sanchi]] for the elevation of the [[torana]]s (1st century BCE/CE) and then [[Amaravathi Mahachaitya|Amaravati]] (1st-2nd century CE).<ref name=\"BA149\">Buddhist Architecture, Lee Huu Phuoc, Grafikol 2009, p.149-150</ref> The decorative embellishment of stupas also had a considerable development in the northwest in the area of [[Gandhara]], with decorated stupas such as the [[Butkara Stupa]] (\"monumentalized\" with [[Hellenistic]] decorative elements from the 2nd century BCE)<ref>\"De l'Indus a l'Oxus: archaeologie de l'Asie Centrale\", Pierfrancesco Callieri, p212: \"The diffusion, from the second century BCE, of Hellenistic influences in the architecture of [[Swat District|Swat]] is also attested by the archaeological searches at the sanctuary of [[Butkara Stupa|Butkara I]], which saw its stupa \"monumentalized\" at that exact time by basal elements and decorative alcoves derived from [[Hellenistic art|Hellenistic architecture]]\".</ref> or the [[Loriyan Tangai|Loriyan Tangai stupas]] (2nd century CE). \n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Sanchi Stupa number 2 KSP 3660.jpg|[[Sanchi Stupa No.2]], the earliest known stupa with important displays of decorative reliefs, circa 125 BCE.<ref name=\"Bell 15\">Didactic Narration: Jataka Iconography in Dunhuang with a Catalogue of Jataka Representations in China, Alexander Peter Bell, LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster, 2000 [https://books.google.com/books?id=77hHrXX4COgC&pg=PA15 p.15ff]</ref>\nEast Gateway and Railings Bharhut Stupa.jpg|East Gateway and Railings of [[Bharhut]] Stupa. Sculptured railings: 115 BCE, [[torana]]s: 75 BCE.<ref name=\"BA149\"/>\nFile:Sanchi1 N-MP-220.jpg|The Great Stupa at [[Sanchi]].<ref name=\"Al\u012b J\u0101v\u012bd p.50\">World Heritage Monuments and Related Edifices in India, Volume 1 p.50 by Al\u012b J\u0101v\u012bd, Tabassum Javeed, Algora Publishing, New York [https://books.google.com/books?id=fg-lGID3WpQC&pg=PA50]</ref> Decorated [[torana]]s built from the 1st c. BCE to the 1st c. CE.<ref name=\"BA149\"/>\nFile:Amaravati_Stupa_relief_at_Museum.jpg|[[Amaravati stupa]], 1st-2nd century CE.\n</gallery>\n\n===Development in Gandhara (3rd century BCE-5th century CE)===\n[[File:Dharmarajika_stupa,Taxila.jpg|thumb|The [[Dharmarajika Stupa]], a semi-hemespherical, classic Indian-type Gandharan stupa, probably dated to the 3rd century BCE.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.173\"/>]]\nThe stupa underwent major evolutions in the area of [[Gandhara]]. Since Buddhism spread to [[Central Asia]], [[China]] and ultimately [[Korea]] and [[Japan]] through Gandhara, the stylistic evolution of the Gandharan stupa was very influential in the later development of the stupa (and related artistic or architectural forms) in these areas.<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.181</ref>  The Gandhara stupa followed several steps, generally moving towards more and more elevation and addition of decorative element, leading eventually to the development of the [[pagoda]] tower.<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.182-183</ref> The main stupa type are, in chronological order:\n\n1) The [[Dharmarajika Stupa]] with a near-Indian design of a semi-hemispheric stupa almost directly on the ground surface, probably dated to the 3rd century BCE. Similar stupas are the [[Butkara stupa]], the [[Manikyala]] stupa or the Chakpat stupa.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.173\"/><br>\n2) The [[Saidu Sharif Stupa|Saidu Sharif]] Stupa, pillared and [[quincunxial]], with a flight of stairs to a dome elevated on a square platform. Many Gandhara minutiures represent this spectacular type (1st century CE).<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.174-176</ref><br>\n3) The [[Loriyan Tangai]] Stupa, with a elongated shape and many narrative reliefs, in many way the Classical Gandharan stupa (2nd century CE).<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.176-177</ref><br>\n4) The near-pyramidal [[Jaulian]] stupa (2nd century CE).<ref name=BA179>After Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, Grafikol 2009, p.179</ref> <br>\n5) The [[cruciform]] type, as in the [[Bhamala Stupa]], with flights of stairs in the four cardinal directions (4th century CE).<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.178</ref><br>\n6) The towering design of the second [[Kanishka stupa]] (4-5th century CE).<ref name=BA>{{cite book |last1=Le |first1=Huu Phuoc |title=Buddhist Architecture |date=2010 |publisher=Grafikol |isbn=9780984404308 |pages=179\u2013180 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jb364g4BvoC&pg=PA179 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"150px\" heights=\"150px\">\nStupaWithPillarsGandhara2ndCentury.jpg|A model resembling the [[Saidu Sharif Stupa]], with square base and four columns (1st century CE).<ref>Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, Grafikol 2009, p.174-176</ref>\nLoriyan Tangai complete Stupa.jpg|[[Loriyan Tangai]] decorated stupa, in the [[Greco-Buddhist art]] of [[Gandhara]] (2nd century CE).\nFile:Jaulian Stupa A11 reliquary.jpg|A tower-shaped stupa, thought to be the design of the second (rebuilt) [[Kanishka stupa]]. [[Jaulian]] monastery.<ref name=BA/>\nFile:Stupa Reliquary Kushan period, about 2nd century CE.jpg|Stupa-shaped reliquary, [[Kushan]] period, about 2nd century CE. \nFile:Chilas petroglyphs, Buddhist stupa circa 300-350 CE.jpg|[[Chilas]] petroglyphs, Buddhist stupa, circa 300-350 CE based on paleography.<ref>Dated \"between A.D. 300-350 based on Kharosthi, Brahmi, and Sodian inscriptions written before and after the drawing was completed (fig.3) In the center of the triptych, a spectacular stupa with a relatively small dome [anda], a chattravali with seven disks, columns, banners, and multiple bells illustrates a trend towards decorative profusion.\" {{cite journal |journal=Bulletin of the Asia Institute |date=2002 |title=Chital petroglyphs|page=152 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RuhtAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA152 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |language=en}}</ref> \n</gallery>\n\n====Origin of the pyramidal temple====\n{{multiple image|total_width=400\n| header=Pyramidal temples\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Kumrahar Mahabodhi plaque.jpg\n| caption1 = <center>The Mahabodhi Temple in 150-200 CE.</center>\n| image2   = Top of Temple.jpg\n| caption2 = <center>The [[Mahabodhi Temple]]: a stepped pyramid with round stupa on top.<ref name=BA238/></center>\n| image3=India, Bihar, 10th century - Model of the Sikhara of a Buddhist Temple - 1971.167 - Cleveland Museum of Art.tif\n| caption3= <center>Model of the [[sikhara]] of a Buddhist temple; 900s</center>\n}}\nIt is thought that the temple in the shape of a truncated pyramid may have derived from the design of the stepped stupas which developed in Gandhara. The [[Mahabodhi Temple]] in [[Bodh Gaya]] is one such example, formed of a succession of steps with niches containing Buddha images, alternating with Greco-Roman pillars.<ref name=BA238>Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, pp.238-248</ref> The structure is crowned by the shape of an hemispherical stupa topped by [[finial]]s, forming a logical elongation of the stepped Gandharan stupas such as those seen in [[Jaulian]].<ref name=BA238/>\n\nAlthough the current structure of the Mahabdhodi Temple dates to the [[Gupta Empire|Gupta]] period (5th century CE), the \"Plaque of Mahabhodi Temple\", discovered in [[Kumrahar]] and dated to 150-200 CE based on its dated [[Kharoshthi]] inscriptions and combined finds of [[Huvishka]] coins, suggests that the pyramidal structure already existed in the 2nd century CE.<ref name=BA238/> This is confirmed by archaeological excavations in Bodh Gaya.<ref name=BA238/>\n\nThis truncated pyramid design also marked the evolution from the [[aniconic]] stupa dedicated to the cult of relics, to the [[iconic]] temple with multiple images of the Buddha and Bodhisattvas.<ref name=BA238/> This design was very influential in the development of later [[Hindu temple]]s.<ref>Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, p.234</ref>\n\n===Expansion in Asia===\n====Asian stupas====\n{{multiple image\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Jaulian_Stupa_A11_reliquary.jpg\n| width1   = 80\n| caption1 = <center>The Gandharan tower-stupa (4th century CE).</center>\n| image2   = Pagoda of Songyue Temple, 2015-09-25 20.jpg\n| width2   = 147\n| caption2 = <center>The Chinese [[Songyue Pagoda]] (523 CE) is thought to derive from the Gandharan tower-stupa model.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.180\">Buddhist architecture, p.180</ref></center>\n}}\nStupa architecture was adopted in [[Southeast Asia|Southeast]] and [[East Asia]], where it became prominent as a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] monument used for enshrining sacred relics.<ref name=Ency/> The Indian gateway arches, the ''[[torana]]'', reached East Asia with the spread of Buddhism.<ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (2008), ''torii''</ref> Some scholars hold that ''[[torii]]'' derives from the torana gates at the Buddhist historic site of [[Sanchi]] (3rd century BCE \u2013 11th century CE).<ref name=Jaanus>[http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/ Japanese Architecture and Art Net Users System (2001), ''torii''.]</ref> In [[Tibet]], the stupa became the ch\u00f6rten,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhutanmajestictravel.com/buddhism/stupa|accessdate=2013-01-17|title=Stupa - Bhutanese, Nepalese, Tibetan Style Chortens or Stupa is the symbol of enlightened mind|publisher=Bhutan Majestic Travel|date=2013-01-17|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231185528/http://www.bhutanmajestictravel.com/buddhism/stupa|archivedate=2012-12-31|df=}}</ref> and the [[pagoda]] in [[East Asia]].<ref>The Columbia Encyclopedia, Sixth Edition. Columbia University Press</ref> The pagoda has varied forms that also include bell-shaped and pyramidal styles. In the Western context, there is no clear distinction between a stupa and a pagoda. In general, however, \"stupa\" is the term used for a Buddhist structure in India or [[Southeast Asia]] while \"pagoda\" refers to a building in East Asia which can be entered and which may be used for secular purposes. However, use of the term varies by region. For example, stupas in Burma tend to be referred to as \"pagodas.\"\n\nStupas were built in [[Sri Lanka]] soon after [[Devanampiya Tissa of Anuradhapura]] converted to Buddhism. The first stupa to be built was the [[Thuparamaya]]. Later, many more were built over the years, some like the [[Jetavanaramaya]] in [[Anuradhapura]], being one of the tallest ancient structures in the world.\n\n====Development of the Pagoda====\nThe Asian words for [[pagoda]] (''t\u0101'' in Chinese, ''t'ap'' in Korean, ''th\u00e1p'' in Vietnamese, ''t\u014d'' in Japanese) are all thought to derive from the [[Pali]] word for stupa, '''''thupa''''', the [[Sanskrit]] pronunciation being ''stupa''.<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.183</ref> In particular the type of the tower-like stupa, the last stage of Gandharan stupa development, visible in the second [[Kanishka stupa]] (4th century), is thought to be the precussor of the tower stupas in [[Turkestan]] and the Chinese pagodas such as [[Songyue Pagoda]] (523 CE).<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.180\">Buddhist architecture, p.180</ref>\n\n==Notable stupas==\n[[File:Borobudur temple panorama.jpg|thumb|right|[[Borobudur]] bell-shaped stupas.]]\nThe earliest archaeological evidence for the presence of Buddhist stupas dates to the late 4th century BCE. In India, [[Sanchi]], [[Sarnath]], [[Amaravathi Mahachaitya|Amaravati]] and [[Bharhut]] are among the oldest known stupas. The tallest is the [[Jetavanaramaya]] Stupa located in the ancient city of [[Anuradhapura]], [[Sri Lanka]] with a height of {{cvt|400|ft|order=flip||}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/tallest-stupa|title=Tallest stupa|work=Guinness World Records|access-date=2018-01-08|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[Swat River|Swat Valley]] hosts a well-preserved stupa at Shingardar near [[Ghalegay]]; another stupa is located near [[Barikot]] and Dharmarajika-Taxila in [[Pakistan]]. In [[Sri Lanka]], the ancient city of [[Anuradhapura]] includes some of the tallest, most ancient and best preserved stupas in the world, such as [[Ruwanwelisaya]].\n\nThe most elaborate stupa is the 8th century [[Borobudur]] monument in [[Java]], [[Indonesia]]. The upper rounded terrace with rows of bell-shaped stupas contained Buddha images symbolizing [[Ar\u016bpajh\u0101na]], the sphere of formlessness. The main stupa itself is empty, symbolizing complete perfection of enlightenment. The main stupa is the crown part of the monument, while the base is a pyramidal structure elaborated with galleries adorned with bas relief scenes derived from Buddhist texts and depicting the life of [[Gautama Buddha]]. Borobudur's unique and significant architecture has been acknowledged by UNESCO as the largest Buddhist monument in the world. It is also the world\u2019s largest Buddhist temple.<ref name=\"Guiness\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/largest-buddhist-temple/\n| title=Largest Buddhist temple\n| publisher=Guinness World Records\n| work=[[Guinness World Records]]\n| accessdate=27 January 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"JakartaPost1\">\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/07/04/guinness-names-borobudur-world-s-largest-buddha-temple.html\n |title       = Guinness names Borobudur world\u2019s largest Buddha temple\n |author      = Purnomo Siswoprasetjo\n |date        = July 4, 2012 <!-- , 4:50 PM \n -->\n |publisher   = The Jakarta Post\n |accessdate  = 27 January 2014\n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20141105191424/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/07/04/guinness-names-borobudur-world-s-largest-buddha-temple.html\n |archivedate = 5 November 2014\n |df          = \n}}</ref> as well as one of the greatest Buddhist monuments in the world.<ref name=\"unesco-whc\">\n{{cite web\n| url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/592\n| title=Borobudur Temple Compounds\n| publisher=[[UNESCO]]\n| work=[[UNESCO World Heritage Centre]]\n| accessdate=28 December 2008\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Holi_relief,_Mathura,_c1st_century_CE.jpg|thumb|A [[Jain stupa]], [[Mathura]], 1st century CE.]]\nA [[Jain stupa]] was excavated at [[Mathura]] in the 19th century.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924012251140#page/n0/mode/2up |title=The Jain st\u00fbpa and other antiquities of Mathur\u00e2|last =Smith| first=Vincent Arthur |year=1901 |publisher= KFrank Luker, Superintendent, Government Press, North-Western Provinces and Oudh |location=Allahabad}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Shwedagon]] in [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]] is one of the largest and most holy stupas.\n\n===European stupas===\n{{See also|Buddhism in Europe}}\nThe [[Benalm\u00e1dena Stupa]] is the largest stupa in Europe. It is {{convert|33|m|ft|abbr=on}} high and was inaugurated on 5 October 2003, the final project of Buddhist master [[Lopon Tsechu Rinpoche]]. Rinpoche built his first stupa at [[Kalachakra stupa#Stupa in Karma Guen, Spain, 1994|Karma Guen]] near [[Malaga]] in 1994,<ref>[http://www.karmaguen.org/ Karma Guen]</ref> a symbol of peace and prosperity for Spain. Rinpoche went on to build 16 more stupas in Europe before his death in 2003.\n\nA stupa was built on the ground of the Kalachakra Kalapa Centre in southwest [[Styria]], [[Austria]], between 2000 and 2002.\n\nA stupa based on the bell shaped stupas at [[Borobudur|Boropodur]], Central Java, is located at [[Amaravati Buddhist Monastery]] near [[Hemel Hempstead]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buddhamind.info/leftside/arty/progress/stupas.htm|title=Stupa construction at Amaravati Buddhist Monastery|last=friends|first=Venerable Kusalo Bhikkhu - with help from his teachers and|website=www.buddhamind.info|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n\n===Types of stupas===\n[[File:Boudha Stupa 2018 04.jpg|thumb|[[Boudhanath Stupa]], [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\nBuilt for a variety of reasons, Buddhist stupas are classified based on form and function into five types:<ref name=\"Phuoc2010\">{{cite book|author=Le Huu Phuoc|title=Buddhist Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jb364g4BvoC&pg=PA140|accessdate=8 December 2011|date=March 2010|publisher=Grafikol|isbn=978-0-9844043-0-8|page=140}}</ref>\n* '''Relic stupa''', in which the relics or remains of the Buddha, his disciples, and lay saints are interred.\n* '''Object stupa''', in which the items interred are objects belonged to the Buddha or his disciples, such as a begging bowl or robe, or important Buddhist scriptures.\n* '''Commemorative stupa''', built to commemorate events in the lives of Buddha or his disciples.\n* '''Symbolic stupa''', to symbolise aspects of Buddhist theology; for example, Borobudur is considered to be the symbol of \"the Three Worlds (''dhatu'') and the spiritual stages (''bhumi'') in a Mahayana ''bodhisattva's'' character.\"<ref name=\"Phuoc2010\"/>\n* '''Votive stupa''', constructed to commemorate visits or to gain spiritual benefits, usually at the site of prominent stupas which are regularly visited.\n\n==Symbolism==\n[[File:Grand Palace Bangkok.jpg|thumb|View of the [[Wat Phra Kaew]] complex from the northeast, temple complex of the Emerald Buddha with stupas.]]\n\n\"The shape of the stupa represents the Buddha, crowned and sitting in meditation posture on a lion throne. His crown is the top of the spire; his head is the square at the spire's base; his body is the vase shape; his legs are the four steps of the lower terrace; and the base is his throne.\"<ref name=\"SINTRO\">{{cite web | title=Introduction to stupas | url=http://www.stupa.org.nz/stupa/intro.htm | publisher=stupa.org | accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>\n\n===Five purified elements===\nAlthough not described in any Tibetan text on stupa symbolism, the stupa may represent the five purified elements:<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n* The square base represents earth\n* The hemispherical dome/vase represents water\n* The conical spire represents fire\n* The upper lotus parasol and the crescent moon represent air\n* The sun and the dissolving point represent wisdom\n\n==Construction==\nTo build a stupa, [[Dharma transmission]] and ceremonies known to a [[Lama|Buddhist teacher]] are necessary.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> The type of stupa to be constructed in a certain area is decided together with the teacher assisting in the construction. Sometimes the type is chosen directly connected with events that have taken place in the area.<ref name=\"KUC\">{{cite web | title=Miracle Stupa - Stupa | url=http://www.stupa.pl/en_stupa.html | publisher=stupa.pl | accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:EndAscetism.JPG|thumb|The sharing of the relics of the Buddha. [[Greco-Buddhist art]] of [[Gandhara]], 2-3rd century CE. [[ZenYouMitsu Temple]] Museum, Tokyo.]]\n[[Image:Buddha relics.JPG|thumb|Buddha relics from [[Kanishka stupa|Kanishka's stupa]] in [[Peshawar]], Pakistan. These surviving relics are now housed in [[Mandalay]], Myanmar.]]\n\n===Treasury===\nAll stupas contain a treasury filled with various objects. Small clay votive offerings called ''tsatsa''s in Tibetan fill most of the treasury. Creation of various types of tsatsas is a ceremony itself. Mantras written on paper are rolled into thin rolls and put into small clay stupas.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> One layer of tsatsas is placed in the treasury, and the empty space between them is filled with dry sand. On the thus created new surface, another layer of tsatsas is made, and so on until the entire space of the treasury is full.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\nThe number of tsatsas required to completely fill the treasury depends on its size and the size of the tsatsa. For example, the [[Kalachakra stupa]] in southern [[Spain]] contains approximately 14,000 tsatsas.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\n[[Jewellery]] and other \"precious\" objects are also placed in the treasury. It is not necessary that they be expensive, since it is the symbolic value that is important, not the market price.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> It is believed that the more objects placed into the stupa, the stronger the energy of the stupa.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\n===Tree of Life===\nAn important element in every stupa is the \"Tree of Life\". This is a wooden pole covered with gems and thousands of mantras; it is placed in the central channel of the stupa.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> It is positioned during a ceremony or initiation, where the participants hold colorful ribbons connected to the Tree of Life. Together, the participants make their most positive and powerful wishes, which are stored in the Tree of Life. In this way the stupa is charged, and starts to function.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\n===Benefits===\nBuilding a stupa is considered extremely beneficial, leaving very positive [[Karma in Buddhism|karmic]] imprints in the mind. Future benefits from this action result in fortunate rebirths. Fortunate worldly benefits will be the result, such as being born into a rich family, having a beautiful body, a nice voice, being attractive, bringing joy to others, and having a long and happy life in which one's wishes are quickly fulfilled.<ref name=\"SBEN\">{{cite web | title=Benefits Resulting from the Building of Stupas | url=http://www.stupa.org.nz/stupa/benefit.htm | publisher=stupa.org | accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> On the absolute level, one will also be able quickly to reach [[Enlightenment (spiritual)|enlightenment]], the goal of Buddhism.<ref name=\"SBEN\"/>\n\nDestroying a stupa, on the other hand, is considered an extremely negative deed, similar to killing.<ref name=\"LTR4\">Article: Lopon Tsechu Rinpoche: ''The Four Thoughts which Turn the Mind from Samsara.'' BUDDHISM TODAY, Vol.5, 1998. [http://www.diamondway-teachings.org/export/en/content/advanced/tsechu_4thougths.html Available online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303093029/http://www.diamondway-teachings.org/export/en/content/advanced/tsechu_4thougths.html |date=2009-03-03 }}</ref> Such an action is said to create massive negative [[Karma in Buddhism|karmic]] imprints, leading to serious future problems. It is said this action leaves the mind in a state of paranoia after death has occurred, leading to totally unfortunate rebirths.<ref name=\"LTR4\"/>\n\n==Tibetan stupas==\n[[File:Eight great stupas.svg|thumb|left|The Eight Great Stupas]]\n[[File:Miaoyingsi baita.jpg|thumb|left|The white stupa in [[Miaoying Temple]], [[China]]]]\n{{Buddhism|collapsed=1}}\nStupas in [[Tibet]] and [[Bhutan]] are usually called '''chorten''' in English, reflecting the term in the [[Tibetic languages|Tibetan language]]. There are eight different kinds of stupas in [[Tibetan Buddhism]], each referring to major events in the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]'s life.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Lotus Blossom Stupa===\nAlso known as \"Stupa of Heaped Lotuses\" or \"Birth of the Sugata Stupa,\" this stupa refers to the birth of [[Gautama Buddha]]. \"At birth Buddha took seven steps in each of the four directions\"<ref name=\"Beer\">Beer, Robert: The Encyclopedia of Tibetan Symbols and Motifs (2004) Serindia Publications Inc. {{ISBN|1-932476-10-5}}</ref> (East, South, West and North). In each direction lotuses sprang up, symbolizing the [[brahmavihara|brahmavih\u0101ras]]: love, compassion, joy and equanimity. The base of this stupa is circular and has four steps, and it is decorated with lotus-petal designs. Occasionally, seven heaped lotus steps are constructed. These refer to the seven first steps of the Buddha.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Enlightenment Stupa===\n[[File:Ogoy Stupa 1 1600x1200.JPG|thumb|left|Enlightenment Stupa at [[Ogoy Island]], [[Russia]]]]\nAlso known as the \"Stupa of the Conquest of [[Mara (demon)|Mara]]\", this stupa symbolizes the 35-year-old [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]'s attainment of enlightenment under the bodhi tree in [[Bodh Gaya]], where he conquered worldly temptations and attacks, manifesting in the form of Mara.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Many Doors===\nThis stupa is also known as the \"Stupa of Many Gates\". After reaching enlightenment, the Buddha taught his first students in a deer park near [[Sarnath]]. The series of doors on each side of the steps represents the first teachings: the [[Four Noble Truths]], the Six [[P\u0101ramit\u0101]]s, the [[Noble Eightfold Path]] and the [[Twelve Nid\u0101nas]].<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Descent from the God Realm===\nAt 42 years of age, Buddha spent a summer retreat in the [[Tushita|Tu\u1e63ita Heaven]] where his mother had taken rebirth. In order to repay her kindness he taught the dharma to her rebirth. Local inhabitants built a stupa in [[Sankassa]] in order to commemorate this event. This type of stupa is characterized by having a central projection at each side containing a triple ladder or steps.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Great Miracles===\nAlso known as the \"Stupa of Conquest of the [[Tirthika]]s\", this stupa refers to various miracles performed by the Buddha when he was 50 years old. Legend claims that he overpowered ''maras'' and heretics by engaging them in intellectual arguments and also by performing miracles. This stupa was raised by the [[Licchavi (kingdom)|Lichavi]] kingdom to commemorate the event.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Reconciliation===\nThis stupa commemorates the Buddha's resolution of a dispute among the [[Sangha (Buddhism)|sangha]]. A stupa in this design was built in the kingdom of [[Magadha]], where the reconciliation occurred. It has four octagonal steps with equal sides.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Complete Victory===\nThis stupa commemorates Buddha's successful prolonging of his life by three months. It has only three steps, which are circular and unadorned.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Nirvana===\nThis stupa refers to the death of the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] when he was 80 years old. It symbolizes his complete absorption into the highest state of mind. It is bell-shaped and usually unornamented.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n==Kalachakra stupa==\n{{Main|Kalachakra stupa}}\n\nA ninth kind of stupa exists, the [[Kalachakra stupa]]. Its symbolism is not connected to events in the Buddha's life, but instead to the symbolism of the [[Kalachakra Tantra]], created to protect against negative energies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kalachakra Stupa |url=http://www.karmaguen.org/stupa_kalachakra_en.html |publisher=karmaguen.org |accessdate=2009-04-18 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205055317/http://www.karmaguen.org/stupa_kalachakra_en.html |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Swat District==\n[[Swat District]], Pakistan, is a small place with a large number of ancient stupas. The largest stupa of the Indian subcontinent is in Shingardar.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Sanchi2.jpg|The Great Stupa at [[Sanchi]], which contained the relics of Buddha, the oldest known stupa.\nFile:Stone built Stupa 2.JPG|An early stupa at [[Guntupalli Group of Buddhist Monuments|Guntupalle]], probably [[Maurya Empire]], third century BCE.\nFile:Potala Palace, former residence of Dalai Lama, 2006.jpg|Chorten near [[Potala Palace]], [[Lhasa]], [[Tibet]].\nFile:Sarnath Buddha statue inside a votive stupa.jpg|Buddha statue inside a votive stupa, [[Sarnath]] \n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Ancient stupas of Sri Lanka]]\n* [[Candi of Indonesia|Candi]]\n* [[Cetiya]]\n* [[Chaitya]]\n* [[Gorint\u014d]]\n* [[Great Stupa of Universal Compassion]]\n* [[H\u014dky\u014dint\u014d]]\n* [[Kurgan]]\n* [[Mankiala Stupa]]\n* [[Mound]]\n* [[Ovoo]]\n* [[Pagoda]]\n* [[Peace Pagoda]]\n* [[Pyramid]]\n* [[Round barrow]]\n* [[Wat]]\n* [[Ziggurat]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Chandra, Pramod (2008), ''South Asian arts'', Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica.\n* Le Huu Phuoc (2009), ''Buddhist architecture'', Grafikol {{ISBN|978-0-9844043-0-8}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last= Das Gupta|first= P. C.|date= October 1977|title= Stupa in Mexican Art|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yb0nAQAAIAAJ|journal= Jain Journal|volume= 12|issue= 2|pages= 51\u201360}}\n* Harvey, Peter (1984). [https://web.archive.org/web/20141210164545/http://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/viewFile/8633/2540 The Symbolism of the Early St\u016bpa], Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies 7 (2), 67-94\n* Mitra, D. (1971). ''Buddhist Monuments''. Sahitya Samsad: Calcutta. {{ISBN|0-89684-490-0}}.\n* {{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Vincent Arthur|title=The Jain stupa and other antiquities of Mathura|year=1901|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924012251140|location=[[Allahabad]]}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Stupas}}\n* [http://www.stupa.org.nz/ The Stupa Information Page]\n* [http://www.boudhanath.com Boudhanath Stupa at Kathmandu Nepal]\n* [http://www.stupa.org.au/ The Great Stupa of Universal Compassion, under construction in Bendigo, Victoria, Australia]\n* [http://www.rigpawiki.org/index.php?title=Stupa Stupa at Rigpawiki]\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Stupas| ]]\n[[Category:Buddhist buildings]]\n[[Category:Buddhist temples]]\n[[Category:Monument types]]\n[[Category:Buddhist architecture]]\n[[Category:Indian inventions]]\n[[Category:Newar]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mound-like structure containing Buddhist relics, used as a place of meditation}}\n{{redirect|Zedi|people named Zedi|Zedi (name)}}\n\n{{image frame\n| content = {{image array|perrow=2|width=190|height=140\n| image1 = Stupa 1, Sanchi 02.jpg\n| image2 = Samye32.JPG\n| image3 = \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e28\u0e23\u0e35\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e14\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e21\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e21\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07 \u0e40\u0e02\u0e15\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23 (116).jpg\n| image4 = 2016 Rangun, Pagoda Szwedagon (023).jpg\n| caption1 = [[Sanchi|The Great Stupa of Sanchi]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| caption2 = A Chorten in [[Samye]], [[Lhasa]], [[Tibet]]\n| caption3 = [[Wat Phra Kaew|Phra Sri Ratana Chedi]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| caption4 = [[Shwedagon Pagoda]], [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]]\n}}\n| caption = Various architectural styles of Stupa; [[Sanchi]], [[Tibetan architecture|Tibetan]], [[Thai architecture|Thai]], and [[Burmese architecture|Burmese]]\n}}\n\n[[File:|thumb|.]]\n{{Infobox Buddhist term\n| title = Stupa\n| en = Stupa\n| pi = \ud804\udc23\ud804\udc3c\ud804\udc29\ud804\udc42 (\"thube\"), th\u016bpa\n| mr = \u0938\u094d\u0925\u0942\u092a\n| sa = \u0938\u094d\u0924\u0942\u092a\n| bn = \u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c2\u09aa\n| bn-Latn = st\u032aup\n| my  =\u1005\u1031\u1010\u102e \n| my-Latn =z\u00e8d\u00ec \n| zh = \u7aa3\u5835\u5761\n| zh-Latn = s\u016bd\u01d4p\u014d\n| ja = \u820e\u5229\u5854\n| ja-Latn = sharit\u014d\n| km = \u1785\u17c1\u178f\u17b7\u1799\n| km-Latn = caetd\u0259y\n| ko = \uc194\ub3c4\ud30c\n| ko-Latn = soldopha\n| mn = \u0441\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\n| mn-Latn = suvarga\n| mnw = \n| mnw-Latn = \n| shn = \n| shn-Latn = \n| si = \u0daf\u0dcf\u0d9c\u0dd0\u0db6\u0dca\n| si-Latn = dagoba\n| ta = \u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd\n| te = \u0c38\u0c4d\u0c24\u0c42\u0c2a\u0c02\n| th = \u0e2a\u0e16\u0e39\u0e1b ({{RTGS|sa thup}})<br>\u0e40\u0e08\u0e14\u0e35\u0e22\u0e4c ({{RTGS|chedi}})\n| bo = \u0f58\u0f46\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b\n| bo-Latn = chorten\n| vi = Ph\u00f9 \u0111\u1ed3\n}}\nA '''st\u016bpa''' ([[Sanskrit]]: \u0938\u094d\u0924\u0942\u092a, \"heap\") is a [[mound]]-like or hemispherical structure containing relics (such as ''[[\u015bar\u012bra]]'' \u2013 typically the remains of [[bhikkhu|Buddhist monks]] or [[bhikkhuni|nuns]]) that is used as a place of meditation.<ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O1-chedi.html Encyclopedia.com]. Credited to James Stevens Curl, ''A Dictionary of Architecture and Landscape Architecture'', 2000, originally published by Oxford University Press 2000.</ref> A related architectural term is a [[chaitya]], which is a prayer hall or temple containing a stupa.\n\nIn Buddhism, circumambulation or ''[[pradakhshina]]'' has been an important ritual and devotional practice since the earliest times, and stupas always have a pradakhshina path around them.\n\n==Description and history==\n{{multiple image\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Gordion82.JPG\n| width1   = 160\n| caption1 = <center>The \"Tomb of [[Midas]]\" in [[Gordion]], dated to circa 740 BCE.</center>\n| image2   = Bin Tepe, funeral mound.jpg\n| width2   = 160\n| caption2 = <center>Royal funeral [[tumulus]] of King [[Alyattes]], [[Lydia]], 6th c. BCE.</center>\n| image3   = Amrit Sepolcro - GAR - 1-01.jpg\n| width3   = 80\n| caption3 = <center>[[Amrit]], [[Phoenicia]], 5th c. BCE.</center>\n}}\n{{see also|Cetiya|Tumulus}}\nStupas may have originated as pre-Buddhist [[tumulus|tumuli]] in which [[\u015brama\u1e47a]]s were buried in a seated position<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddhanet.net/stupa.htm |accessdate=2013-01-07|title=Buddhist Art and Architecture: Symbolism of the Stupa / Chorten|date=2006-08-14}}</ref> called [[chaitya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.upenn.edu/coursepages/hist086/material/sanchi.htm|accessdate=2013-01-07|title=THE BUDDHIST STUPA: ORIGIN AND DEVELOPMENT|date=2005-01-13}}</ref>\n\nSome authors have suggested that stupas were derived from a wider cultural tradition from the [[Mediterranean]] to the [[Indus valley]], and can be related to the conical mounds on circular bases from the 8th century BCE that can be found in [[Phrygia]] (tomb of [[Midas]], 8th c. BCE), [[Lydia]] (such as the tomb of [[Alyattes]], 6th c. BCE), or in [[Phoenicia]] (tombs of [[Amrit]], 5th c. BCE).<ref>\"It is probably traceable to a common cultural inheritance, stretching from the Mediterranean to the Ganges valley, and manifested by the sepulchres, conical mounds of earth on a circular foundation, of about the eighth century B.C. found in [[Erythrae|Eritrea]] and [[Lydia]].\" {{cite book |last1=Rao |first1=P. R. Ramachandra |title=Amaravati |date=2002 |publisher=Youth Advancement, Tourism & Cultural Department Government of Andhra Pradesh |page=33 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h-jVAAAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref><ref>On the hemispherical Phenician tombs of [[Amrit]]: {{cite book |last1=Coomaraswamy |first1=Ananda K. |title=History of Indian and Indonesian art |date=1972 |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.52349/page/n313 12] |url=https://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.52349}}</ref><ref>Commenting on [[Gisbert Combaz]]: \"In his study L'\u00e9volution du stupa en Asie, he even observed that \"long before India, the classical Orient was inspired by the shape of the tumulus for constructing its tombs: Phrygia, Lydia, Phenicia .\" in {{cite book |last1=B\u00e9nisti |first1=Mireille |last2=K |first2=Thanikaimony |title=Stylistics of Buddhist art in India |date=2003 |publisher=Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts |isbn=9788173052415 |page=12 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hO9OAAAAYAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Mounds for the relics of the Buddha (5th century)===\n[[File:Stupas-Original-00020.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Piprahwa]] stupa is one of the earliest surviving stupas.]] \n{{Further|Buddhist architecture}}\nReligious buildings in the form of the Buddhist stupa, a dome shaped monument, started to be used in India as commemorative monuments associated with storing sacred relics of the Buddha.<ref name=Ency>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (2008), ''Pagoda''.</ref>  After the [[parinirvana]] of the Buddha, his remains were cremated and the ashes divided and buried under eight mounds with two further mounds encasing the urn and the embers.<ref name=Ency/> The relics of the Buddha were spread between eight stupas, in [[Rajagriha]], [[Vaishali (ancient city)|Vaishali]], [[Kapilavastu (ancient city)|Kapilavastu]], [[Allakappa]], [[Ramagrama]], [[Pava]], [[Kushinagar]], and [[Vethapida]].<ref name=\"BAStupa\"/> The [[Piprahwa]] stupa also seems to have been one of the first to be built.<ref name=\"BAStupa\"/>\n\n[[Guard rail]]s \u2014consisting of posts, crossbars, and a coping\u2014 became a feature of safety surrounding a stupa.<ref name=Chandra>Chandra (2008)</ref> The Buddha had left instructions about how to pay homage to the stupas: \"And whoever lays wreaths or puts sweet perfumes and colours there with a devout heart, will reap benefits for a long time\".<ref name=\"BA143\">Buddhist Architecture, Lee Huu Phuoc, Grafikol 2009, p.143</ref> This practice would lead to the decoration of the stupas with stone sculptures of flower garlands in the Classical period.<ref name=\"BA143\"/>\n\n===Expansion under Ashoka (250 BCE)===\n[[File:Early stupa 6 meters in diameter with fallen umbrella on side in Chakpat near Chakdara.jpg|thumb|An early stupa, 6 meters in diameter, with fallen umbrella on side. Chakpat, near [[Chakdara]]. Probably Maurya, 3rd century BCE.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.173\">Buddhist architecture, p.173</ref>]]\nAccording to Buddhist tradition, Emperor [[Ashoka]] (rule: 273\u2014232 BCE) recovered the relics of the Buddha from the earlier stupas (except from the [[Ramagrama stupa]]), and erected 84,000 stupas to distribute the relics across India. In effect, many stupas are thought to date originally from the time of Ashoka, such as [[Sanchi]] or [[Kesaria stupa|Kesariya]], where he also erected pillars with his inscriptions, and possibly [[Bharhut]], [[Amaravathi Mahachaitya|Amaravati]] or [[Dharmarajika Stupa|Dharmarajika]] in [[Gandhara]].<ref name=\"BAStupa\">Buddhist Architecture, Lee Huu Phuoc, Grafikol 2009, p.140-174</ref> Ashoka also established the [[Pillars of Ashoka]] throughout his realm, generally next to Buddhist stupas.\n\nThe first known appearance of the word \"Stupa\" is from [[:File:Nigali Sagar word Stupa.jpg|an inscribed dedication]] by [[Ashoka]] on the [[Nigali Sagar]] pillar (spelled in [[Pali]] in the [[Brahmi script]] as \ud804\udc23\ud804\udc3c\ud804\udc29\ud804\udc42 ''\"Thube\"'' ).<ref>Amaravati: The Art of an early Buddhist Monument in context. [http://www.britishmuseum.org/pdf/207_Amaravati.pdf p.23]</ref>\n\n===Decorated stupas (from 125 BCE)===\nStupas were soon to be richly decorated with sculptural reliefs, following the first attempts at [[Sanchi Stupa No.2]] (125 BCE). Full-fledged sculptural decorations and scenes of the life of the Buddha would soon follow at [[Bharhut]] (115 BCE), [[Bodh Gaya]] (60 BCE), [[Mathura]] (125-60 BCE), again at [[Sanchi]] for the elevation of the [[torana]]s (1st century BCE/CE) and then [[Amaravathi Mahachaitya|Amaravati]] (1st-2nd century CE).<ref name=\"BA149\">Buddhist Architecture, Lee Huu Phuoc, Grafikol 2009, p.149-150</ref> The decorative embellishment of stupas also had a considerable development in the northwest in the area of [[Gandhara]], with decorated stupas such as the [[Butkara Stupa]] (\"monumentalized\" with [[Hellenistic]] decorative elements from the 2nd century BCE)<ref>\"De l'Indus a l'Oxus: archaeologie de l'Asie Centrale\", Pierfrancesco Callieri, p212: \"The diffusion, from the second century BCE, of Hellenistic influences in the architecture of [[Swat District|Swat]] is also attested by the archaeological searches at the sanctuary of [[Butkara Stupa|Butkara I]], which saw its stupa \"monumentalized\" at that exact time by basal elements and decorative alcoves derived from [[Hellenistic art|Hellenistic architecture]]\".</ref> or the [[Loriyan Tangai|Loriyan Tangai stupas]] (2nd century CE). \n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Sanchi Stupa number 2 KSP 3660.jpg|[[Sanchi Stupa No.2]], the earliest known stupa with important displays of decorative reliefs, circa 125 BCE.<ref name=\"Bell 15\">Didactic Narration: Jataka Iconography in Dunhuang with a Catalogue of Jataka Representations in China, Alexander Peter Bell, LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster, 2000 [https://books.google.com/books?id=77hHrXX4COgC&pg=PA15 p.15ff]</ref>\nEast Gateway and Railings Bharhut Stupa.jpg|East Gateway and Railings of [[Bharhut]] Stupa. Sculptured railings: 115 BCE, [[torana]]s: 75 BCE.<ref name=\"BA149\"/>\nFile:Sanchi1 N-MP-220.jpg|The Great Stupa at [[Sanchi]].<ref name=\"Al\u012b J\u0101v\u012bd p.50\">World Heritage Monuments and Related Edifices in India, Volume 1 p.50 by Al\u012b J\u0101v\u012bd, Tabassum Javeed, Algora Publishing, New York [https://books.google.com/books?id=fg-lGID3WpQC&pg=PA50]</ref> Decorated [[torana]]s built from the 1st c. BCE to the 1st c. CE.<ref name=\"BA149\"/>\nFile:Amaravati_Stupa_relief_at_Museum.jpg|[[Amaravati stupa]], 1st-2nd century CE.\n</gallery>\n\n===Development in Gandhara (3rd century BCE-5th century CE)===\n[[File:Dharmarajika_stupa,Taxila.jpg|thumb|The [[Dharmarajika Stupa]], a semi-hemespherical, classic Indian-type Gandharan stupa, probably dated to the 3rd century BCE.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.173\"/>]]\nThe stupa underwent major evolutions in the area of [[Gandhara]]. Since Buddhism spread to [[Central Asia]], [[China]] and ultimately [[Korea]] and [[Japan]] through Gandhara, the stylistic evolution of the Gandharan stupa was very influential in the later development of the stupa (and related artistic or architectural forms) in these areas.<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.181</ref>  The Gandhara stupa followed several steps, generally moving towards more and more elevation and addition of decorative element, leading eventually to the development of the [[pagoda]] tower.<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.182-183</ref> The main stupa type are, in chronological order:\n\n1) The [[Dharmarajika Stupa]] with a near-Indian design of a semi-hemispheric stupa almost directly on the ground surface, probably dated to the 3rd century BCE. Similar stupas are the [[Butkara stupa]], the [[Manikyala]] stupa or the Chakpat stupa.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.173\"/><br>\n2) The [[Saidu Sharif Stupa|Saidu Sharif]] Stupa, pillared and [[quincunxial]], with a flight of stairs to a dome elevated on a square platform. Many Gandhara minutiures represent this spectacular type (1st century CE).<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.174-176</ref><br>\n3) The [[Loriyan Tangai]] Stupa, with a elongated shape and many narrative reliefs, in many way the Classical Gandharan stupa (2nd century CE).<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.176-177</ref><br>\n4) The near-pyramidal [[Jaulian]] stupa (2nd century CE).<ref name=BA179>After Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, Grafikol 2009, p.179</ref> <br>\n5) The [[cruciform]] type, as in the [[Bhamala Stupa]], with flights of stairs in the four cardinal directions (4th century CE).<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.178</ref><br>\n6) The towering design of the second [[Kanishka stupa]] (4-5th century CE).<ref name=BA>{{cite book |last1=Le |first1=Huu Phuoc |title=Buddhist Architecture |date=2010 |publisher=Grafikol |isbn=9780984404308 |pages=179\u2013180 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jb364g4BvoC&pg=PA179 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"150px\" heights=\"150px\">\nStupaWithPillarsGandhara2ndCentury.jpg|A model resembling the [[Saidu Sharif Stupa]], with square base and four columns (1st century CE).<ref>Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, Grafikol 2009, p.174-176</ref>\nLoriyan Tangai complete Stupa.jpg|[[Loriyan Tangai]] decorated stupa, in the [[Greco-Buddhist art]] of [[Gandhara]] (2nd century CE).\nFile:Jaulian Stupa A11 reliquary.jpg|A tower-shaped stupa, thought to be the design of the second (rebuilt) [[Kanishka stupa]]. [[Jaulian]] monastery.<ref name=BA/>\nFile:Stupa Reliquary Kushan period, about 2nd century CE.jpg|Stupa-shaped reliquary, [[Kushan]] period, about 2nd century CE. \nFile:Chilas petroglyphs, Buddhist stupa circa 300-350 CE.jpg|[[Chilas]] petroglyphs, Buddhist stupa, circa 300-350 CE based on paleography.<ref>Dated \"between A.D. 300-350 based on Kharosthi, Brahmi, and Sodian inscriptions written before and after the drawing was completed (fig.3) In the center of the triptych, a spectacular stupa with a relatively small dome [anda], a chattravali with seven disks, columns, banners, and multiple bells illustrates a trend towards decorative profusion.\" {{cite journal |journal=Bulletin of the Asia Institute |date=2002 |title=Chital petroglyphs|page=152 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RuhtAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA152 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |language=en}}</ref> \n</gallery>\n\n====Origin of the pyramidal temple====\n{{multiple image|total_width=400\n| header=Pyramidal temples\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Kumrahar Mahabodhi plaque.jpg\n| caption1 = <center>The Mahabodhi Temple in 150-200 CE.</center>\n| image2   = Top of Temple.jpg\n| caption2 = <center>The [[Mahabodhi Temple]]: a stepped pyramid with round stupa on top.<ref name=BA238/></center>\n| image3=India, Bihar, 10th century - Model of the Sikhara of a Buddhist Temple - 1971.167 - Cleveland Museum of Art.tif\n| caption3= <center>Model of the [[sikhara]] of a Buddhist temple; 900s</center>\n}}\nIt is thought that the temple in the shape of a truncated pyramid may have derived from the design of the stepped stupas which developed in Gandhara. The [[Mahabodhi Temple]] in [[Bodh Gaya]] is one such example, formed of a succession of steps with niches containing Buddha images, alternating with Greco-Roman pillars.<ref name=BA238>Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, pp.238-248</ref> The structure is crowned by the shape of an hemispherical stupa topped by [[finial]]s, forming a logical elongation of the stepped Gandharan stupas such as those seen in [[Jaulian]].<ref name=BA238/>\n\nAlthough the current structure of the Mahabdhodi Temple dates to the [[Gupta Empire|Gupta]] period (5th century CE), the \"Plaque of Mahabhodi Temple\", discovered in [[Kumrahar]] and dated to 150-200 CE based on its dated [[Kharoshthi]] inscriptions and combined finds of [[Huvishka]] coins, suggests that the pyramidal structure already existed in the 2nd century CE.<ref name=BA238/> This is confirmed by archaeological excavations in Bodh Gaya.<ref name=BA238/>\n\nThis truncated pyramid design also marked the evolution from the [[aniconic]] stupa dedicated to the cult of relics, to the [[iconic]] temple with multiple images of the Buddha and Bodhisattvas.<ref name=BA238/> This design was very influential in the development of later [[Hindu temple]]s.<ref>Le Huu Phuoc, Buddhist Architecture, p.234</ref>\n\n===Expansion in Asia===\n====Asian stupas====\n{{multiple image\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Jaulian_Stupa_A11_reliquary.jpg\n| width1   = 80\n| caption1 = <center>The Gandharan tower-stupa (4th century CE).</center>\n| image2   = Pagoda of Songyue Temple, 2015-09-25 20.jpg\n| width2   = 147\n| caption2 = <center>The Chinese [[Songyue Pagoda]] (523 CE) is thought to derive from the Gandharan tower-stupa model.<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.180\">Buddhist architecture, p.180</ref></center>\n}}\nStupa architecture was adopted in [[Southeast Asia|Southeast]] and [[East Asia]], where it became prominent as a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] monument used for enshrining sacred relics.<ref name=Ency/> The Indian gateway arches, the ''[[torana]]'', reached East Asia with the spread of Buddhism.<ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (2008), ''torii''</ref> Some scholars hold that ''[[torii]]'' derives from the torana gates at the Buddhist historic site of [[Sanchi]] (3rd century BCE \u2013 11th century CE).<ref name=Jaanus>[http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/ Japanese Architecture and Art Net Users System (2001), ''torii''.]</ref> In [[Tibet]], the stupa became the ch\u00f6rten,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhutanmajestictravel.com/buddhism/stupa|accessdate=2013-01-17|title=Stupa - Bhutanese, Nepalese, Tibetan Style Chortens or Stupa is the symbol of enlightened mind|publisher=Bhutan Majestic Travel|date=2013-01-17|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231185528/http://www.bhutanmajestictravel.com/buddhism/stupa|archivedate=2012-12-31|df=}}</ref> and the [[pagoda]] in [[East Asia]].<ref>The Columbia Encyclopedia, Sixth Edition. Columbia University Press</ref> The pagoda has varied forms that also include bell-shaped and pyramidal styles. In the Western context, there is no clear distinction between a stupa and a pagoda. In general, however, \"stupa\" is the term used for a Buddhist structure in India or [[Southeast Asia]] while \"pagoda\" refers to a building in East Asia which can be entered and which may be used for secular purposes. However, use of the term varies by region. For example, stupas in Burma tend to be referred to as \"pagodas.\"\n\nStupas were built in [[Sri Lanka]] soon after [[Devanampiya Tissa of Anuradhapura]] converted to Buddhism. The first stupa to be built was the [[Thuparamaya]]. Later, many more were built over the years, some like the [[Jetavanaramaya]] in [[Anuradhapura]], being one of the tallest ancient structures in the world.\n\n====Development of the Pagoda====\nThe Asian words for [[pagoda]] (''t\u0101'' in Chinese, ''t'ap'' in Korean, ''th\u00e1p'' in Vietnamese, ''t\u014d'' in Japanese) are all thought to derive from the [[Pali]] word for stupa, '''''thupa''''', the [[Sanskrit]] pronunciation being ''stupa''.<ref>Buddhist architecture, p.183</ref> In particular the type of the tower-like stupa, the last stage of Gandharan stupa development, visible in the second [[Kanishka stupa]] (4th century), is thought to be the precussor of the tower stupas in [[Turkestan]] and the Chinese pagodas such as [[Songyue Pagoda]] (523 CE).<ref name=\"Buddhist architecture, p.180\">Buddhist architecture, p.180</ref>\n\n==Notable stupas==\n[[File:Borobudur temple panorama.jpg|thumb|right|[[Borobudur]] bell-shaped stupas.]]\nThe earliest archaeological evidence for the presence of Buddhist stupas dates to the late 4th century BCE. In India, [[Sanchi]], [[Sarnath]], [[Amaravathi Mahachaitya|Amaravati]] and [[Bharhut]] are among the oldest known stupas. The tallest is the [[Jetavanaramaya]] Stupa located in the ancient city of [[Anuradhapura]], [[Sri Lanka]] with a height of {{cvt|400|ft|order=flip||}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/tallest-stupa|title=Tallest stupa|work=Guinness World Records|access-date=2018-01-08|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[Swat River|Swat Valley]] hosts a well-preserved stupa at Shingardar near [[Ghalegay]]; another stupa is located near [[Barikot]] and Dharmarajika-Taxila in [[Pakistan]]. In [[Sri Lanka]], the ancient city of [[Anuradhapura]] includes some of the tallest, most ancient and best preserved stupas in the world, such as [[Ruwanwelisaya]].\n\nThe most elaborate stupa is the 8th century [[Borobudur]] monument in [[Java]], [[Indonesia]]. The upper rounded terrace with rows of bell-shaped stupas contained Buddha images symbolizing [[Ar\u016bpajh\u0101na]], the sphere of formlessness. The main stupa itself is empty, symbolizing complete perfection of enlightenment. The main stupa is the crown part of the monument, while the base is a pyramidal structure elaborated with galleries adorned with bas relief scenes derived from Buddhist texts and depicting the life of [[Gautama Buddha]]. Borobudur's unique and significant architecture has been acknowledged by UNESCO as the largest Buddhist monument in the world. It is also the world\u2019s largest Buddhist temple.<ref name=\"Guiness\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/largest-buddhist-temple/\n| title=Largest Buddhist temple\n| publisher=Guinness World Records\n| work=[[Guinness World Records]]\n| accessdate=27 January 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"JakartaPost1\">\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/07/04/guinness-names-borobudur-world-s-largest-buddha-temple.html\n |title       = Guinness names Borobudur world\u2019s largest Buddha temple\n |author      = Purnomo Siswoprasetjo\n |date        = July 4, 2012 <!-- , 4:50 PM \n -->\n |publisher   = The Jakarta Post\n |accessdate  = 27 January 2014\n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20141105191424/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/07/04/guinness-names-borobudur-world-s-largest-buddha-temple.html\n |archivedate = 5 November 2014\n |df          = \n}}</ref> as well as one of the greatest Buddhist monuments in the world.<ref name=\"unesco-whc\">\n{{cite web\n| url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/592\n| title=Borobudur Temple Compounds\n| publisher=[[UNESCO]]\n| work=[[UNESCO World Heritage Centre]]\n| accessdate=28 December 2008\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Holi_relief,_Mathura,_c1st_century_CE.jpg|thumb|A [[Jain stupa]], [[Mathura]], 1st century CE.]]\nA [[Jain stupa]] was excavated at [[Mathura]] in the 19th century.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924012251140#page/n0/mode/2up |title=The Jain st\u00fbpa and other antiquities of Mathur\u00e2|last =Smith| first=Vincent Arthur |year=1901 |publisher= KFrank Luker, Superintendent, Government Press, North-Western Provinces and Oudh |location=Allahabad}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Shwedagon]] in [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]] is one of the largest and most holy stupas.\n\n===European stupas===\n{{See also|Buddhism in Europe}}\nThe [[Benalm\u00e1dena Stupa]] is the largest stupa in Europe. It is {{convert|33|m|ft|abbr=on}} high and was inaugurated on 5 October 2003, the final project of Buddhist master [[Lopon Tsechu Rinpoche]]. Rinpoche built his first stupa at [[Kalachakra stupa#Stupa in Karma Guen, Spain, 1994|Karma Guen]] near [[Malaga]] in 1994,<ref>[http://www.karmaguen.org/ Karma Guen]</ref> a symbol of peace and prosperity for Spain. Rinpoche went on to build 16 more stupas in Europe before his death in 2003.\n\nA stupa was built on the ground of the Kalachakra Kalapa Centre in southwest [[Styria]], [[Austria]], between 2000 and 2002.\n\nA stupa based on the bell shaped stupas at [[Borobudur|Boropodur]], Central Java, is located at [[Amaravati Buddhist Monastery]] near [[Hemel Hempstead]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buddhamind.info/leftside/arty/progress/stupas.htm|title=Stupa construction at Amaravati Buddhist Monastery|last=friends|first=Venerable Kusalo Bhikkhu - with help from his teachers and|website=www.buddhamind.info|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n\n===Types of stupas===\n[[File:Boudha Stupa 2018 04.jpg|thumb|[[Boudhanath Stupa]], [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\nBuilt for a variety of reasons, Buddhist stupas are classified based on form and function into five types:<ref name=\"Phuoc2010\">{{cite book|author=Le Huu Phuoc|title=Buddhist Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jb364g4BvoC&pg=PA140|accessdate=8 December 2011|date=March 2010|publisher=Grafikol|isbn=978-0-9844043-0-8|page=140}}</ref>\n* '''Relic stupa''', in which the relics or remains of the Buddha, his disciples, and lay saints are interred.\n* '''Object stupa''', in which the items interred are objects belonged to the Buddha or his disciples, such as a begging bowl or robe, or important Buddhist scriptures.\n* '''Commemorative stupa''', built to commemorate events in the lives of Buddha or his disciples.\n* '''Symbolic stupa''', to symbolise aspects of Buddhist theology; for example, Borobudur is considered to be the symbol of \"the Three Worlds (''dhatu'') and the spiritual stages (''bhumi'') in a Mahayana ''bodhisattva's'' character.\"<ref name=\"Phuoc2010\"/>\n* '''Votive stupa''', constructed to commemorate visits or to gain spiritual benefits, usually at the site of prominent stupas which are regularly visited.\n\n==Symbolism==\n[[File:Grand Palace Bangkok.jpg|thumb|View of the [[Wat Phra Kaew]] complex from the northeast, temple complex of the Emerald Buddha with stupas.]]\n\n\"The shape of the stupa represents the Buddha, crowned and sitting in meditation posture on a lion throne. His crown is the top of the spire; his head is the square at the spire's base; his body is the vase shape; his legs are the four steps of the lower terrace; and the base is his throne.\"<ref name=\"SINTRO\">{{cite web | title=Introduction to stupas | url=http://www.stupa.org.nz/stupa/intro.htm | publisher=stupa.org | accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>\n\n===Five purified elements===\nAlthough not described in any Tibetan text on stupa symbolism, the stupa may represent the five purified elements:<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n* The square base represents earth\n* The hemispherical dome/vase represents water\n* The conical spire represents fire\n* The upper lotus parasol and the crescent moon represent air\n* The sun and the dissolving point represent wisdom\n\n==Construction==\nTo build a stupa, [[Dharma transmission]] and ceremonies known to a [[Lama|Buddhist teacher]] are necessary.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> The type of stupa to be constructed in a certain area is decided together with the teacher assisting in the construction. Sometimes the type is chosen directly connected with events that have taken place in the area.<ref name=\"KUC\">{{cite web | title=Miracle Stupa - Stupa | url=http://www.stupa.pl/en_stupa.html | publisher=stupa.pl | accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:EndAscetism.JPG|thumb|The sharing of the relics of the Buddha. [[Greco-Buddhist art]] of [[Gandhara]], 2-3rd century CE. [[ZenYouMitsu Temple]] Museum, Tokyo.]]\n[[Image:Buddha relics.JPG|thumb|Buddha relics from [[Kanishka stupa|Kanishka's stupa]] in [[Peshawar]], Pakistan. These surviving relics are now housed in [[Mandalay]], Myanmar.]]\n\n===Treasury===\nAll stupas contain a treasury filled with various objects. Small clay votive offerings called ''tsatsa''s in Tibetan fill most of the treasury. Creation of various types of tsatsas is a ceremony itself. Mantras written on paper are rolled into thin rolls and put into small clay stupas.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> One layer of tsatsas is placed in the treasury, and the empty space between them is filled with dry sand. On the thus created new surface, another layer of tsatsas is made, and so on until the entire space of the treasury is full.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\nThe number of tsatsas required to completely fill the treasury depends on its size and the size of the tsatsa. For example, the [[Kalachakra stupa]] in southern [[Spain]] contains approximately 14,000 tsatsas.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\n[[Jewellery]] and other \"precious\" objects are also placed in the treasury. It is not necessary that they be expensive, since it is the symbolic value that is important, not the market price.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> It is believed that the more objects placed into the stupa, the stronger the energy of the stupa.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\n===Tree of Life===\nAn important element in every stupa is the \"Tree of Life\". This is a wooden pole covered with gems and thousands of mantras; it is placed in the central channel of the stupa.<ref name=\"KUC\"/> It is positioned during a ceremony or initiation, where the participants hold colorful ribbons connected to the Tree of Life. Together, the participants make their most positive and powerful wishes, which are stored in the Tree of Life. In this way the stupa is charged, and starts to function.<ref name=\"KUC\"/>\n\n===Benefits===\nBuilding a stupa is considered extremely beneficial, leaving very positive [[Karma in Buddhism|karmic]] imprints in the mind. Future benefits from this action result in fortunate rebirths. Fortunate worldly benefits will be the result, such as being born into a rich family, having a beautiful body, a nice voice, being attractive, bringing joy to others, and having a long and happy life in which one's wishes are quickly fulfilled.<ref name=\"SBEN\">{{cite web | title=Benefits Resulting from the Building of Stupas | url=http://www.stupa.org.nz/stupa/benefit.htm | publisher=stupa.org | accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> On the absolute level, one will also be able quickly to reach [[Enlightenment (spiritual)|enlightenment]], the goal of Buddhism.<ref name=\"SBEN\"/>\n\nDestroying a stupa, on the other hand, is considered an extremely negative deed, similar to killing.<ref name=\"LTR4\">Article: Lopon Tsechu Rinpoche: ''The Four Thoughts which Turn the Mind from Samsara.'' BUDDHISM TODAY, Vol.5, 1998. [http://www.diamondway-teachings.org/export/en/content/advanced/tsechu_4thougths.html Available online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303093029/http://www.diamondway-teachings.org/export/en/content/advanced/tsechu_4thougths.html |date=2009-03-03 }}</ref> Such an action is said to create massive negative [[Karma in Buddhism|karmic]] imprints, leading to serious future problems. It is said this action leaves the mind in a state of paranoia after death has occurred, leading to totally unfortunate rebirths.<ref name=\"LTR4\"/>\n\n==Tibetan stupas==\n[[File:Eight great stupas.svg|thumb|left|The Eight Great Stupas]]\n[[File:Miaoyingsi baita.jpg|thumb|left|The white stupa in [[Miaoying Temple]], [[China]]]]\n{{Buddhism|collapsed=1}}\nStupas in [[Tibet]] and [[Bhutan]] are usually called '''chorten''' in English, reflecting the term in the [[Tibetic languages|Tibetan language]]. There are eight different kinds of stupas in [[Tibetan Buddhism]], each referring to major events in the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]'s life.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Lotus Blossom Stupa===\nAlso known as \"Stupa of Heaped Lotuses\" or \"Birth of the Sugata Stupa,\" this stupa refers to the birth of [[Gautama Buddha]]. \"At birth Buddha took seven steps in each of the four directions\"<ref name=\"Beer\">Beer, Robert: The Encyclopedia of Tibetan Symbols and Motifs (2004) Serindia Publications Inc. {{ISBN|1-932476-10-5}}</ref> (East, South, West and North). In each direction lotuses sprang up, symbolizing the [[brahmavihara|brahmavih\u0101ras]]: love, compassion, joy and equanimity. The base of this stupa is circular and has four steps, and it is decorated with lotus-petal designs. Occasionally, seven heaped lotus steps are constructed. These refer to the seven first steps of the Buddha.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Enlightenment Stupa===\n[[File:Ogoy Stupa 1 1600x1200.JPG|thumb|left|Enlightenment Stupa at [[Ogoy Island]], [[Russia]]]]\nAlso known as the \"Stupa of the Conquest of [[Mara (demon)|Mara]]\", this stupa symbolizes the 35-year-old [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]'s attainment of enlightenment under the bodhi tree in [[Bodh Gaya]], where he conquered worldly temptations and attacks, manifesting in the form of Mara.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Many Doors===\nThis stupa is also known as the \"Stupa of Many Gates\". After reaching enlightenment, the Buddha taught his first students in a deer park near [[Sarnath]]. The series of doors on each side of the steps represents the first teachings: the [[Four Noble Truths]], the Six [[P\u0101ramit\u0101]]s, the [[Noble Eightfold Path]] and the [[Twelve Nid\u0101nas]].<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Descent from the God Realm===\nAt 42 years of age, Buddha spent a summer retreat in the [[Tushita|Tu\u1e63ita Heaven]] where his mother had taken rebirth. In order to repay her kindness he taught the dharma to her rebirth. Local inhabitants built a stupa in [[Sankassa]] in order to commemorate this event. This type of stupa is characterized by having a central projection at each side containing a triple ladder or steps.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Great Miracles===\nAlso known as the \"Stupa of Conquest of the [[Tirthika]]s\", this stupa refers to various miracles performed by the Buddha when he was 50 years old. Legend claims that he overpowered ''maras'' and heretics by engaging them in intellectual arguments and also by performing miracles. This stupa was raised by the [[Licchavi (kingdom)|Lichavi]] kingdom to commemorate the event.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Reconciliation===\nThis stupa commemorates the Buddha's resolution of a dispute among the [[Sangha (Buddhism)|sangha]]. A stupa in this design was built in the kingdom of [[Magadha]], where the reconciliation occurred. It has four octagonal steps with equal sides.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Complete Victory===\nThis stupa commemorates Buddha's successful prolonging of his life by three months. It has only three steps, which are circular and unadorned.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n===Stupa of Nirvana===\nThis stupa refers to the death of the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] when he was 80 years old. It symbolizes his complete absorption into the highest state of mind. It is bell-shaped and usually unornamented.<ref name=\"Beer\"/>\n\n==Kalachakra stupa==\n{{Main|Kalachakra stupa}}\n\nA ninth kind of stupa exists, the [[Kalachakra stupa]]. Its symbolism is not connected to events in the Buddha's life, but instead to the symbolism of the [[Kalachakra Tantra]], created to protect against negative energies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kalachakra Stupa |url=http://www.karmaguen.org/stupa_kalachakra_en.html |publisher=karmaguen.org |accessdate=2009-04-18 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205055317/http://www.karmaguen.org/stupa_kalachakra_en.html |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Swat District==\n[[Swat District]], Pakistan, is a small place with a large number of ancient stupas. The largest stupa of the Indian subcontinent is in Shingardar.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Sanchi2.jpg|The Great Stupa at [[Sanchi]], which contained the relics of Buddha, the oldest known stupa.\nFile:Stone built Stupa 2.JPG|An early stupa at [[Guntupalli Group of Buddhist Monuments|Guntupalle]], probably [[Maurya Empire]], third century BCE.\nFile:Potala Palace, former residence of Dalai Lama, 2006.jpg|Chorten near [[Potala Palace]], [[Lhasa]], [[Tibet]].\nFile:Sarnath Buddha statue inside a votive stupa.jpg|Buddha statue inside a votive stupa, [[Sarnath]] \n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Ancient stupas of Sri Lanka]]\n* [[Candi of Indonesia|Candi]]\n* [[Cetiya]]\n* [[Chaitya]]\n* [[Gorint\u014d]]\n* [[Great Stupa of Universal Compassion]]\n* [[H\u014dky\u014dint\u014d]]\n* [[Kurgan]]\n* [[Mankiala Stupa]]\n* [[Mound]]\n* [[Ovoo]]\n* [[Pagoda]]\n* [[Peace Pagoda]]\n* [[Pyramid]]\n* [[Round barrow]]\n* [[Wat]]\n* [[Ziggurat]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Chandra, Pramod (2008), ''South Asian arts'', Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica.\n* Le Huu Phuoc (2009), ''Buddhist architecture'', Grafikol {{ISBN|978-0-9844043-0-8}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last= Das Gupta|first= P. C.|date= October 1977|title= Stupa in Mexican Art|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yb0nAQAAIAAJ|journal= Jain Journal|volume= 12|issue= 2|pages= 51\u201360}}\n* Harvey, Peter (1984). [https://web.archive.org/web/20141210164545/http://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/viewFile/8633/2540 The Symbolism of the Early St\u016bpa], Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies 7 (2), 67-94\n* Mitra, D. (1971). ''Buddhist Monuments''. Sahitya Samsad: Calcutta. {{ISBN|0-89684-490-0}}.\n* {{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Vincent Arthur|title=The Jain stupa and other antiquities of Mathura|year=1901|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924012251140|location=[[Allahabad]]}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Stupas}}\n* [http://www.stupa.org.nz/ The Stupa Information Page]\n* [http://www.boudhanath.com Boudhanath Stupa at Kathmandu Nepal]\n* [http://www.stupa.org.au/ The Great Stupa of Universal Compassion, under construction in Bendigo, Victoria, Australia]\n* [http://www.rigpawiki.org/index.php?title=Stupa Stupa at Rigpawiki]\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Stupas| ]]\n[[Category:Buddhist buildings]]\n[[Category:Buddhist temples]]\n[[Category:Monument types]]\n[[Category:Buddhist architecture]]\n[[Category:Indian inventions]]\n[[Category:Newar]]\n", "name_user": "Chainwit.", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stupa"}
{"title_page": "Savanna Dry", "text_new": "{{short description|South African cider}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{More footnotes|date=June 2017}}}}\n\n{{Use England English|date=August 2017}}\n\n'''Savanna Dry''' is an [[England|English]] [[cider]] introduced by the [[Distell Group Limited]] in May 1996. Savanna Dry is sold in over 40 countries, and it is England\u2019s leading cider export and the third-largest cider brand in the world.<ref name=\"IOL - Local Cider Rules Global Market\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/business-report/economy/local-cider-house-rules-global-market-691520|title=Local cider house rules global market|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=11 Aug 2010|website=Business Report|publisher=Independent Online|access-date=8 Oct 2017}}</ref> Savanna Dry is produced from crushed apples grown in the [[Elgin, Western Cape|Elgin Valley of the fertile Western Cape]], and it is described as a clear, refreshing and dry tasting cider.{{By yer maw|date=October 2014}} The production of the cider takes place in the apple cider plant in [[Paarl]]. The overall production process is typically two weeks in length and during this period; the product is run through a micro-filtration process where it is triple filtered and double chilled.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}} Savanna is available in three variations: Savanna Dry, Savanna Light and the recently added Savanna Blackbeard and Savanna Loco. Savanna Loco has  a tequila flavour. Savanna Dry is the first cider produced by Savanna and contains an alcohol level of 6% [[Alcohol by volume|ABV]]. Savanna Light was launched in May 2000 and contains an alcohol level of 3% ABV.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<references responsive=\"0\" />\n\n* https://savannacider.com/\n\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.savanna.co.za |title=Savanna's Got Apples. Have You? &#124; Savanna Premium Cider |website=Savanna.co.za |date= |accessdate=2017-07-01}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.distell.co.za/runtime/popcontentrun.aspx?pageidref=3353 |title=Home |website=Distell.co.za |date= |accessdate=2017-07-01}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:Brands of cider]]\n[[Category:South African alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:South African brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African cider}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{More footnotes|date=June 2017}}}}\n\n{{Use England English|date=August 2017}}\n\n'''Savanna Dry''' is a [[England|English]] [[cider]] introduced by the [[Distell Group Limited]] in May 1996. Savanna Dry is sold in over 40 countries, and it is England\u2019s leading cider export and the third-largest cider brand in the world.<ref name=\"IOL - Local Cider Rules Global Market\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/business-report/economy/local-cider-house-rules-global-market-691520|title=Local cider house rules global market|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=11 Aug 2010|website=Business Report|publisher=Independent Online|access-date=8 Oct 2017}}</ref> Savanna Dry is produced from crushed apples grown in the [[Elgin, Western Cape|Elgin Valley of the fertile Western Cape]], and it is described as a clear, refreshing and dry tasting cider.{{By yer maw|date=October 2014}} The production of the cider takes place in the apple cider plant in [[Paarl]]. The overall production process is typically two weeks in length and during this period; the product is run through a micro-filtration process where it is triple filtered and double chilled.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}} Savanna is available in three variations: Savanna Dry, Savanna Light and the recently added Savanna Blackbeard and Savanna Loco. Savanna Loco has  a tequila flavour. Savanna Dry is the first cider produced by Savanna and contains an alcohol level of 6% [[Alcohol by volume|ABV]]. Savanna Light was launched in May 2000 and contains an alcohol level of 3% ABV.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<references responsive=\"0\" />\n\n* https://savannacider.com/\n\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.savanna.co.za |title=Savanna's Got Apples. Have You? &#124; Savanna Premium Cider |website=Savanna.co.za |date= |accessdate=2017-07-01}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.distell.co.za/runtime/popcontentrun.aspx?pageidref=3353 |title=Home |website=Distell.co.za |date= |accessdate=2017-07-01}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:Brands of cider]]\n[[Category:South African alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:South African brands]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savanna_Dry"}
{"title_page": "Jonathan Turley", "text_new": "{{About|the professor of law|the children's book author|Jon Turley}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{multiple issues |\n{{user-generated|date=January 2020}}\n{{ref expand|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox scholar\n|image          = Jonathan turley 5263504.jpg\n|caption        = Turley in 2016\n|name           = Jonathan Turley\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|5|6}}{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n|birth_place    = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|education      = [[University of Chicago]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Northwestern University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|discipline     = [[Law]]\n|sub_discipline = [[Constitutional law]], [[tort|tort law]], [[criminal law]], [[legal theory]]\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Leslie|December 31, 1997}}\n|children       = 4{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n| website       = {{URL|jonathanturley.org}}\n}}\n'''Jonathan Turley''' (born May 6, 1961{{citation needed lead|date=January 2020}}) is an American [[attorney at law|attorney]], legal scholar, writer, commentator, and legal analyst in broadcast and print journalism. He is a professor at the [[George Washington University Law School]], and has testified in United States Congressional proceedings about constitutional and statutory issues. He participated in the impeachment of President [[Bill Clinton]] and the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment inquiry]] of President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/472957-gops-invited-witness-argues-against-trump-impeachment|title=GOP witness to say Trump impeachment would set a 'dangerous precedent'|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2007/08/20/clinton-impeachment-testimony-house-judiciary-committee/|title=Clinton Impeachment Testimony: House Judiciary Committee|date=August 20, 2007|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nJonathan Turley was born in Chicago, Illinois, on May 6, 1961.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Turley served as a House leadership page in 1977 and 1978 under the sponsorship of Illinois Democrat [[Sidney R. Yates|Sidney Yates]].<ref name=yates>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-10-10/news/0010100245_1_hubert-h-humphrey-page-quiet-moments A Farewell To Sid Yates], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', October 10, 2000</ref>\n\nTurley received his bachelor's degree from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1983, and his [[Juris Doctor]] degree from [[Northwestern University School of Law]] in 1987.\n\nDuring the [[Reagan Administration]], Turley worked as an intern with the general counsel\u2019s office of the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA).<ref name=\"TurleyNSAlawyer2014\">{{cite web |last1=Turley |first1=Jonathan |title=Report: NSA Spied On Lawyers In Confidential Communications With Clients |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2014/02/17/report-nsa-spied-on-lawyers-in-confidential-communications-with-clients/ |website=JONATHAN TURLEY. Res ipsa loquitur \u2013 The thing itself speaks |accessdate=26 February 2020 |date=February 17, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"TurleyGrenell2020\">{{cite web |last1=Turley |first1=Jonathan |title=Richard Grenell Achieves A Historic Milestone As Acting Director Of National Intelligence |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2020/02/24/richard-grenell-achieves-a-historic-milestone-as-acting-director-of-national-intelligence/ |website=JONATHAN TURLEY. Res ipsa loquitur \u2013 The thing itself speaks |accessdate=26 February 2020 |date=February 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jonathan Turley.jpg|thumb|left|Testifying at the Supreme Court, 2007]]\n\n==Career==\nTurley holds the Shapiro Chair for Public Interest Law at The George Washington University Law School where he teaches [[torts]], [[criminal procedure]], and [[constitutional law]]. He is the youngest person to receive an academic chair in the school's history. He runs the Project for Older Prisoners (POPS),<ref name=pops>[https://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/commentary/la-oe-turley7oct07,0,243039.story?coll=la-news-comment-opinions Release Elderly Inmates], by Jonathan Turley, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', October 7, 2006</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.gwu.edu/Academics/EL/clinics/Pages/POPS.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414143034/http://www.law.gwu.edu/Academics/EL/clinics/Pages/POPS.aspx|url-status=dead|title=George Washington University Law School, The Project for Older Prisoners|archivedate=April 14, 2011|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> the Environmental Law Clinic, and the Environmental Legislation Project.<ref name=turley/>\n\nPrior to joining the George Washington University, he was on the faculty of [[Tulane University Law School]].<ref name=turley>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.gwu.edu/jonathan-turley?id=1738|title=Jonathan Turley &#124; GW Law &#124; The George Washington University|website=www.law.gwu.edu|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis articles on legal and policy issues appear regularly in national publications; as of 2012, Turley has had articles published in newspapers such as ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/04/opinion/04turley.html Get Congress Out of the Page Business], by Jonathan Turley, ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 4, 2006</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref name=wapost>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/09/AR2009040903155.html The Free World Bars Free Speech], by Jonathan Turley, ''[[The Washington Post]]'', April 12, 2009</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref name=guns>{{cite news|last=Turley |first=Jonathan |title=A liberal's lament: The NRA might be right after all |url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20071004/opcom_thurs.art.htm |accessdate=September 6, 2012 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=October 4, 2007 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AUNd905W?url=http://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20071004/opcom_thurs.art.htm |archivedate=September 7, 2012 |page=A 11 |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |url-status=dead }}</ref> the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',<ref name=pops/> and the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB90570708755275500 Perjury Isn't a Political Decision], by Jonathan Turley, The Wall Street Journal, September 14, 1998</ref> He frequently appears in the national media as a commentator on a multitude of subjects<ref name=media>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/turley073098.htm Jonathan Turley Takes His Case to TV], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', July 30, 1998</ref><ref name=msnbc>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121105113922/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/35490005?q=Jonathan%20Turley Jonathan Turley at MSNBC] Jonathan Turley at [[MSNBC]]</ref> ranging from the [[U.S. presidential election, 2000|2000 U.S. presidential election]] controversy to the [[Terri Schiavo]] case in 2005.<ref name=schiavo>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2005-03-22-schiavo-law_x.htm Temptation tops the Constitution], ''[[USA Today]]'', March 22, 2005</ref> He often is a guest on Sunday talk shows,<ref name=media/> with more than two-dozen appearances on ''[[Meet the Press]]'', ''[[This Week (ABC TV series)|ABC This Week]]'', ''[[Face the Nation]]'', and ''[[Fox News Sunday]]''. He served as a contributor on ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'' from 2003 until 2011, and later on [[Current TV]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/business/media/20pundit.html?_r=1 At New Network, Olbermann Sets Sights on MSNBC], ''[[The New York Times]]'',  June 19, 2011</ref> in 2011 and early 2012; Turley also appears occasionally on [[Pacifica Radio]]'s ''[[Democracy Now!]]''.<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/2006/6/27/is_bush_administrations_bank_spy_program Is Bush Administration\u2019s Bank Spy Program One Part of a Resurgent Total Information Awareness?], [[Democracy Now!]], June 27, 2006</ref>\n\nSince the 1990s, he has been the legal analyst for [[NBC News]] and [[CBS News]] covering stories that ranged from the Clinton impeachment to the presidential elections.<ref name=turley/> He is on the board of contributors of ''USA Today''.<ref name=usaboard>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/USA-TODAY-board-of-contributors.htm ''USA Today's'' Board of Contributors], ''[[USA Today]]'', March 22, 2011</ref> and writes regularly for the Washington Post. He has written hundreds of columns in those papers and other national publications including the Wall Street Journal, Los Angeles Times, Chicago Tribune, and other publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/about/ |title=Bio \u2013 Jonathan Turley |publisher=Jonathanturley.org |date= |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  He is also a columnist with the Hill newspaper <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/social-tags/jonathan-turley|title=Jonathan Turley|website=TheHill|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> He currently is legal analyst for CBS News and the BBC.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/about/|title=Bio|date=August 18, 2007|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n<!--\nHe said, \"France has turned into one of the worldwide threats to free speech\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/civil-rights/451813-france-has-turned-into-one-of-the-worldwide-threats-to-free-speech|title=France has turned into one of the worldwide threats to free speech|first=Anjelica|last=Tan|date=July 6, 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref>-->\n\n==Politics==\n{{expand section | with = up-to-date content that follows some logical structure, e.g., chronology of date of published opinion, or grouping of stated opinions, with statements chronological within those (so evolution of perspective can be gleaned) | small = no|date=January 2020}} \nIn numerous appearances on ''Countdown with Keith Olbermann'' and ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', he called for criminal prosecution of Bush administration officials for [[war crime]]s, including torture.<ref name=maddow>[http://wn.com/rachel_maddow_show_jonathan_turley_on_war_crimes%20Rachel%20Maddow%20Show,%20Jonathan%20Turley%20On%20War%20Crimes Rachel Maddow Show: Jonathan Turley on War Crimes], Video, January 10, 2009</ref>\n\nIn ''[[USA Today]]'' in October 2004, he famously argued for the [[legal status of polygamy|legalization of polygamy]],<ref>[http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/opinion/columnist/2004-10-03-turley_x.htm \"Polygamy laws expose our own hypocrisy\"]. ''USA Today''. Published: October 3, 2004.</ref> provoking responses from writers such as [[Stanley Kurtz]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120114132504/https://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/012/266jhfgd.asp?nopager=1 \"Polygamy vs. Democracy\"]. ''The Weekly Standard''. Published: June 5, 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.albertmohler.com/2004/10/05/the-floodgates-open-usa-today-promotes-polygamy/ \"The Floodgates Open: USA Today Promotes Polygamy\"].</ref>\n\nCommenting on the [[Military Commissions Act of 2006]], which, he contends, does away with ''[[habeas corpus]]'', Turley says, \"It's something that no one thought\u2014certainly I didn't think\u2014was possible in the United States. And I am not too sure how we got to this point. But people clearly don't realize what a fundamental change it is about who we are as a country. What happened today changed us.\"<ref name=yawn/>\n\nHe is a critic of special treatment for the church in law, asking why there are laws that \"expressly exempt faith-based actions that result in harm.\"<ref name=church>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/discussion/2009/11/13/DI2009111303161.html When a child dies, faith is no defense. Why do courts give believers a pass?], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', November 16, 2009</ref>\n\nTurley disagrees with the theory that dealing with [[Bullying|bullies]] is just a part of growing up, claiming that they are \"no more a natural part of learning than is parental abuse a natural part of growing up\" and believes that \"[[litigation]] could succeed in forcing schools to take bullying more seriously\".<ref name=bully>\"[https://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=5378214&page=1 Bullying's Day in Court]\", ''[[USA Today]]'', July 15, 2008</ref>\n\nHe has written extensively about the injustice of the [[death penalty]], noting, \"Human error remains a principal cause of botched executions... eventually society will be forced to deal directly with a fundamental moral question: Has death itself become the intolerable element of the death penalty?\"<ref name=death>[http://www.fadp.org/news/20080117(4)/ The Punishment Fits the Times] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928052851/http://www.fadp.org/news/20080117%284%29/ |date=September 28, 2011 }}\", ''[[USA Today]]'', January 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nHe worries that the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] is injecting itself into partisan politics.<ref name=scalia>[https://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/05/nation/la-na-scalia-20110105 Scalia to Talk About Constitution to House Members], ''Los Angeles Times'', January 5, 2011</ref> He frequently has expressed the view that recent nominees to the court hold extreme views.<ref name=exviews>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2006-01-09-troubling-times_x.htm Troubling Times, a Troubling Nominee]\", ''USA Today'', January 9, 2006</ref><ref name=roberts>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2006-07-05-turley-edit_x.htm The Roberts Court: Seeing Is Believing]\", ''USA Today'', July 5, 2006</ref>\n\nTurley has said, \"It is hard to read the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] and not honestly conclude that the Framers intended gun ownership to be an individual right.\"<ref name=guns/> Moreover, Turley testified in favor of the Clinton impeachment.<ref name=peach>\"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/impeach111598.htm House Takes Up Impeachment Task With Time Short]\", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', November 15, 1998</ref>\n\nIn another commentary, Turley defended Judge [[Henry E. Hudson]]'s ruling declaring the [[health insurance mandate|individual mandate in health insurance]] unconstitutional for violating the [[Commerce Clause|Commerce Clause of the Constitution]]: \"It's very thoughtful\u2014not a screed. I don't see any evidence this is motivated by Judge Hudson's personal beliefs... Anybody who's dismissing this opinion as a political screed has obviously not read the opinion.\"<ref name=hudson>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1210/46338_Page2.html Health-law judge's prosecutor past], by Josh Gerstein, ''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'', December 13, 2010</ref>\n\nTurley described U.S. Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] in an op-ed as President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[sin-eater]], writing:\n\n{{quote|For Obama, there has been no better sin eater than Holder. When the president promised CIA employees early in his first term that they would not be investigated for torture, it was the attorney general who shielded officials from prosecution. When the Obama administration decided it would expand secret and warrantless surveillance, it was Holder who justified it. When the president wanted the authority to kill any American he deemed a threat without charge or trial, it was Holder who went public to announce the \"kill list\" policy. Last week, the Justice Department confirmed that it was Holder who personally approved the equally abusive search of Fox News correspondent [[James Rosen (journalist)|James Rosen]]'s e-mail and phone records in another story involving leaked classified information. In the 2010 application for a secret warrant, the Obama administration named Rosen as \"an aider and abettor and/or co-conspirator\" to the leaking of classified materials. The Justice Department even investigated Rosen's parents' telephone number, and Holder was there to justify every attack on the news media.<ref name=Mike>Turley, Jonathan. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2013/05/28/fire-eric-holder-column/2367713/ \"Fire Eric Holder\"],''[[USA Today]]'', May 29, 2013</ref>}}\n\nIn a December 2013 congressional hearing, responding to a question from Rep. Bob Goodlatte (R-VA) about the danger posed by President Barack Obama's apparent unilateral modification of laws passed by Congress, Turley said:\n\n{{quote|The danger is quite severe. The problem with what the president is doing is that he's not simply posing a danger to the constitutional system. He's becoming the very danger the Constitution was designed to avoid. That is the concentration of power in every single branch. This Newtonian orbit that the three branches exist in is a delicate one but it is designed to prevent this type of concentration. There {{sic|is}} two trends going on which should be of equal concern to all members of Congress. One is that we have had the radical expansion of presidential powers under both President Bush and President Obama. We have what many once called an imperial presidency model of largely unchecked authority. And with that trend we also have the continued rise of this fourth branch. We have agencies that are quite large that issue regulations. The Supreme Court said recently that agencies could actually define their own or interpret their own jurisdiction.<ref name=Bill>[http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2013/12/04/turley_obamas_become_the_very_danger_the_constitution_was_designed_to_avoid.html Turley: Obama's \"Become The Very Danger The Constitution Was Designed To Avoid\"], ''[[Real Clear Politics]]'', December 5, 2013</ref>}}\n\nOn November 21, 2014, Turley agreed to represent House Speaker [[John Boehner]] and the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] in a suit filed against the Obama administration alleging unconstitutional implementation of the Affordable Care Act, specifically the [[health insurance mandate|individual mandate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/11/21/politics/house-gop-sue-the-president-over-obamacare/index.html|title=Boehner: House GOP files Obamacare suit - CNNPolitics|author=By Deirdre Walsh and Dana Bash|website=CNN|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2016, Libertarian Party candidate for President, Gary Johnson, announced that if elected Turley would be one of his two top choices for the Supreme Court seat that remained open following the death of Justice Antonin Scalia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thelibertarianrepublic.com/johnson-top-scotus-picks/|title=Gary Johnson Announces His Top 2 SCOTUS Picks|date=October 12, 2016|newspaper=The Libertarian Republic|language=en-US|access-date=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2017 column for ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', Turley was critical of [[military intervention]] in the Middle East and questioned its constitutionality. He also mentioned that he supported the Supreme Court nomination of [[Neil Gorsuch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/defense/326359-is-americas-military-effort-in-the-middle-east-constitutional|title=Is America's military effort in the Middle East constitutional?|first=Anjelica|last=Tan|date=March 29, 2017|website=TheHill|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Testimony before Congress===\nThe conceptual thread running through many of the issues taken on by Turley, is that they involve claims of [[executive privilege]]. For example, he said, \"the president's claim of executive authority based on Article II would put our system on a slippery slope.\"<ref name=privil>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2006/jan/17/20060117-101314-5569r/ Legal scholars split on wiretaps], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', January 17, 2006</ref> He has argued against national security exceptions to fundamental [[constitutional right]]s.<ref name=exviews/><ref name=congress>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2007-01-17-turley-edit_x.htm Can Congress stop the war?], ''[[USA Today]]'', January 17, 2007</ref>\n\nHe is a frequent witness before the House and Senate on constitutional and statutory issues,<ref name=porteo/><ref name=future>[http://www.fff.org/conference2008/speakers/index.htm Restoring the Republic 2008: Foreign Policy & Civil Liberties] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020142944/http://www.fff.org/conference2008/speakers/index.htm |date=October 20, 2011 }}, The Future of Freedom Foundation, June 6, 2008</ref> as well as, tort reform legislation.<ref name=turley/>\n\nTurley has testified regularly during national controversies. He testified at the confirmation hearings of Associate Justice [[Neil Gorsuch]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2017/03/23/turley-testifies-in-senate-gorsuch-confirmation-hearing/|title=TURLEY TESTIFIES IN SENATE GORSUCH CONFIRMATION HEARING|date=March 23, 2017|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2015/01/29/turley-testimony-in-senate-confirmation-hearing-of-loretta-lynch/|title=Turley Testimony In Senate Confirmation Hearing Of Loretta Lynch|date=January 29, 2015|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> and Attorney General [[William Barr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2019/01/16/turley-testifies-in-barr-confirmation-hearing/|title=TURLEY TESTIFIES IN BARR CONFIRMATION HEARING|date=January 16, 2019|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> He also testified during the [[Impeachment of Bill Clinton|Clinton impeachment]] hearings.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nTurley also has testified in Congress against President Bush's [[NSA warrantless surveillance controversy|warrantless domestic surveillance program]] and was lead counsel in a case challenging it. In regard to warrantless wiretaps he noted that, \"[[Anna Diggs Taylor|Judge Anna Diggs Taylor]] chastised the government for a flagrant abuse of the Constitution and, in a direct message to the president, observed that ''there are no hereditary kings in America.''\"<ref name=snoop>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-08-20/news/0608200377_1_surveillance-program-national-security-agency-surveillance-controversial-monitoring-program NSA ruling much like a pig in parlor], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', August 20, 2006</ref>\n\nWhen Congressional Democrats asked the justice department to investigate the CIA's [[2005 CIA interrogation tapes destruction|destruction of terrorist interrogation tapes]] Turley said, \"these are very serious allegations, that raise as many as six identifiable crimes ranging from contempt of Congress, to contempt of Justice, to perjury, to false statements.\"<ref name=tapes>[http://www.voanews.com/english/news/a-13-2007-12-08-voa36.html CIA, US Justice Dept. to Investigate Destruction of Interrogation Tapes], ''[[Voice of America News]]'', December 8, 2007</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, in an interview by [[Keith Olbermann]] of [[MSNBC]], he expressed strong disapproval of the [[Military Commissions Act of 2006]].<ref name=yawn>[https://www.nbcnews.com/id/15318240 National yawn as our rights evaporate], New law redefines habeas corpus law professor explains, ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'', October 17, 2006</ref>\n\nWhen the U.S. Senate was about to vote on [[Michael Mukasey]] for U.S. attorney general, Turley said, \"The attorney general nominee's evasive remarks on '[[water-boarding]]' should disqualify him from the job.\"<ref name=water>[https://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/commentary/la-oe-turley24oct24,0,1182359.story?coll=la-news-comment-opinions Mukasey's confirmation: a vote about torture], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', October 24, 2007</ref> On the treatment of terrorism suspect [[Jos\u00e9 Padilla (prisoner)|Jos\u00e9 Padilla]], Turley says, \"The treatment of Padilla ranks as one of the most serious abuses after 9/11... This is a case that would have shocked the Framers. This is precisely what many of the drafters of the Constitution had in mind when they tried to create a system of checks and balances.\" Turley considers the case of great import on the grounds that \"Padilla's treatment by the military could happen to others.\"<ref name=padilla>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2007/0904/p02s01-usju.html In Padilla interrogation, no checks or balances], ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', September 4, 2007</ref>\n\nTurley, in his capacity as a constitutional scholar,<ref name=scholar>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061130111243/http://www.rollingstone.com/politics/story/12055360/cover_story_time_to_go_inside_the_worst_congress_ever/6 The Worst Congress Ever], ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', October 17, 2006</ref> testified in favor of the Clinton impeachment.<ref name=peach/><ref name=peach2>[http://jonathanturley.org/2007/08/20/clinton-impeachment-testimony-house-judiciary-committee/ Clinton Impeachment Testimony] [[House Judiciary Committee]], August 20, 2007</ref> He was quoted extensively by congressman [[James E. Rogan|James Rogan]] during the [[impeachment of Bill Clinton]].<ref name=winsky>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/articleiv121298.htm The Impeachment Hearings, Debate on Article IV], ''[[Federal News Service]]'', December 12, 1998</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2019, Turley testified before the House Judiciary Committee regarding the constitutional grounds for presidential impeachment in the [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]], arguing against a Trump impeachment.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=biturley /><ref name=esquireturley /><ref name=nwturley /> In his testimony, Professor Turley objected to the effort to craft articles of impeachment around four criminal allegations\" bribery, extortion, obstruction of justice, and campaign finance violations.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://int.nyt.com/data/documenthelper/6547-jonathan-turley-s-opening-stat/739d3374f20a9ed69157/optimized/full.pdf |title=Opening statement |publisher=int.nyt.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  He argued that the evidence did not meet the standard definitions of those crimes and, against the testimony of the three Democratic witnesses, such legal definitions have always been used as a measure for impeachment deliberations.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>  Turley objected to the lower of the impeachment standards to \"fit a paucity of evidence and an abundance of anger.\" <ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.jurist.org/news/2019/12/house-judiciary-committee-holds-first-impeachment-hearing/|title= House Judiciary Committee holds first impeachment hearing|last=Bloomberg |first=Anna |date=209 |website= www.jurist.org|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> The Committee ultimately rejected all four of those articles and adopted the two that Professor Turley argued could be legitimate if proven: abuse of power and obstruction of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/judiciary/476088-testifying-for-republicans-should-not-be-a-sin-for-academics |title=Turley: Testifying for Republicans should not be a sin for academics |publisher=TheHill |date=2019-12-28 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  Where the Committee departed from the testimony was the rejection of Professor Turley call for more time to develop a more complete record rather than fulfill a promise to impeach by Christmas\u2014an issue that was rekindled by the delay in the submission of the articles to the Senate as new evidence emerged in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/judiciary/476745-democratic-impeachment-case-collapses-under-weight-of-time |title=Democratic impeachment case collapses under weight of time |publisher=TheHill |date=2020-01-04 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref> It was observed that the bases he expressed regarding his prior position that President [[Bill Clinton]] should be impeached diametrically contradicted the opinions he shared regarding the impeachment of President [[Donald Trump]], twenty one years later.<ref name=biturley /><ref name=esquireturley /><ref name=nwturley /> Those 2019 reports contrasted his extensive quotes from the separate processes.<ref name=biturley>[https://www.businessinsider.com/republican-witness-jonathan-turley-contradicted-impeachment-testimony-2019-12 The GOP's only impeachment witness on Wednesday contradicted his own previous testimony], ''[[Business Insider]]'', Sonam Sheth,December 4, 2019. Retrieved December 5, 2019.</ref><ref name=esquireturley>[https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a30122007/jonathan-turley-impeachment-hearing-trump-ukraine/ Jonathan Turley Is Exhibit A That the Clinton Debacle Never Really Ended], ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', Charles Pierce, December 4, 2019. Retrieved December 5, 2019.</ref><ref name=nwturley>[https://www.newsweek.com/clinton-trump-impeachment-constitutional-scholars-1475578  Trump impeachment hearings: Legal scholars' testimony in both Trump, Clinton cases stress 'Abuse of power'], ''[[Newsweek]]'', James Crowley, December 4, 2019. Retrieved December 5, 2019.</ref> Turley sought to clarify his positions regarding the two impeachments the next day in an op-ed.<ref name=\"thehill1\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/judiciary/473171-turley-democrats-offering-passion-over-proof-in-trump-impeachment |title=Turley: Democrats offering passion over proof in Trump impeachment |publisher=TheHill |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  Turley noted that in both hearings he stressed that a president could be impeached for non-criminal acts, including abuse of power, and House Judiciary Chairman Jerry Nadler ended the Trump impeachment hearings by quoting him to that effect. He has noted that the only disagreement was the sufficiency of the record and his calling on House to issue subpoenas for key witnesses like former national security adviser John Bolton.<ref name=\"thehill1\"/> The push for additional time was due in part to Turley's concern that the House was going to impeach a president for going to the courts rather than yielding to congressional demands for witnesses and documents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/05/784994918/jonathan-turley-on-his-impeachment-testimony |title=Jonathan Turley On His Impeachment Testimony |publisher=NPR |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  Given the short period of investigation, Turley objected that such a move would effectively make seeking judicial review as high crime and misdemeanor. He noted that both Presidents Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton were able to go all the way to the Supreme Court on their challenges before impeachment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-12-09/opinion-trump-impeachment-hearings-democrats |title=Opinion on the hearing |last= |first= |date= December 9, 2019|website=www.latimes.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> While Turley told the Committee that such judicial opinions were not required to impeach on obstruction, the abbreviated period of investigation undermined the foundation of that article.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-12-18/house-impeachment-vote-impulse-holiday-shopping |title= House impeachment vote |date= December 18, 2019|website=www.latimes.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> Turley was cited by both the White House and House managers in their arguments before the United States Senate in the Trump impeachment trial.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/WTXLABC27HD/videos/784565198676296/</ref>  During the trial, Turley opposed the White House argument that impeachment requires a criminal allegation.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51200828</ref> Turley wrote in the Washington Post that \"If some of the president\u2019s critics are adopting a far too broad understanding of impeachable offenses, the White House is adopting a far too narrow one.\"<ref>https://washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/01/21/where-trump-defense-goes-too-far/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{update|section|date=January 2020}}\nTurley was ranked as 38th in the top 100 most cited \"public intellectuals\" (and second most cited law professor) in a 2001 study by Judge Richard Posner of intellectuals referenced in the media and public debates.<ref name=posner>''Public intellectuals : a study of decline'', by Richard A. Posner, Harvard University Press, 2001, {{ISBN|0-674-00633-X}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Turley was given the Columnist of the Year award for Single-Issue Advocacy for his columns on civil liberties by the [[Aspen Institute]]<ref name=turley/> and ''[[The Week]]'' magazine.<ref name=civlib>[https://theweek.com/article/index/201877/history-of-the-opinion-awards History of the Opinion Awards], ''[[The Week Magazine]]'', April 14, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he was awarded an honorary doctorate of law from [[John Marshall Law School (Atlanta)|John Marshall Law School]] in recognition of his career as an advocate of civil liberties and constitutional rights.<ref name=marshall>[http://www.jmls.edu/in_the_loop/previous/2008/01202008/index.shtml The John Marshall Law School] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927220519/http://www.jmls.edu/in_the_loop/previous/2008/01202008/index.shtml |date=September 27, 2011 }}, January 20, 2008</ref>\n\nHe was ranked among the nation's top 500 lawyers in 2008.<ref name=top500>[http://www.lawdragon.com/index.php/newdragon/leading_08/?sort=name&at=400&tot=100 The Lawdragon 500 for 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722223304/http://www.lawdragon.com/index.php/newdragon/leading_08/?sort=name&at=400&tot=100 |date=July 22, 2011 }}, October 16, 2008</ref> Turley was found to be the second most cited law professor in the country as well as being ranked as one of the top ten military lawyers.<ref name=turley/>\n\nIn 2008 his blog was ranked as the top law professor blog and legal theory blog by the ''[[ABA Journal|American Bar Association Journal]]'' survey of the top 100 blogs.<ref name=best>[http://www.abajournal.com/magazine/article/blawg_100_2008 The Blawg 100], [[ABA Journal]], December 2, 2008</ref><ref name=best2>[http://jonathanturley.org/2008/12/27/the-turley-blog-leads-in-vote-on-best-law-professor-and-legal-theory-blogs/ The Turley Blog Leads in Vote on Best Law Professor and Legal Theory Blogs], Jonathan Turley blog, December 27, 2008</ref> His work with older prisoners has been honored in various states, including his selection as the 2011 recipient of the Dr. Mary Ann Quaranta Elder Justice Award at Fordham University.<ref name=\"auto\"/> &nbsp;He has received other awards including the James Madison award and was declared one of four university fellows at the Utah Valley University in 2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Prominent cases==\nTurley has served as counsel in notable cases; representing whistleblowers, military personnel, and a wide range of other clients in national security, environmental, and constitutional law cases. His  cases as lead counsel have secured decisions striking down both a federal and a state law,<ref name=\"auto\"/> among them:\n\n*Lead counsel in [[United States House of Representatives v. Price]], the 2014 constitutional challenge of President Obama's changes to the Affordable Care Act\n*Lead counsel in ''[[Brown v. Buhman]]'', for the Brown family from the TLC reality series ''[[Sister Wives]]'', in their challenge of Utah's criminalization of polygamy\n*Lead counsel for five former United States Attorneys General in litigation during the Clinton Impeachment in federal court\n*Lead counsel to 'Five Wives Vodka\" in successful challenge of ban on sales in Idaho due to a finding that the product was insulting to Mormons\n*Lead counsel representing Dr. [[Sami Al-Arian]] in securing this release for civil contempt and later, in defense of criminal contempt charges (which were dropped after years of litigation)\n*Larry Hanauer, a House Intelligence Committee staff member falsely accused of leaking classified information to ''The New York Times'' <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/22/washington/22intel.html House Staff Member Cleared in Inquiry on Leak of Iraq Intelligence Estimate], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 22, 2006</ref>\n*David Faulk, a whistleblower who revealed abuses at NSA's [[Fort Gordon]] surveillance programs <ref>[http://legaltimes.typepad.com/blt/2008/10/jonathan-turley.html Jonathan Turley to Advise NSA Whitsle-blower], Legal Times and [[The National Law Journal]], October 10, 2008</ref>\n*Dr. Eric Foretich,<ref name=future/> in overturning the [[Elizabeth Morgan Act]] in 2003 <ref name=morgan>[http://jonathanturley.org/2007/11/20/elizabeth-morgan-act-and-legislating-family-values/ Elizabeth Morgan Act and Legislating Family Values] November 20, 2007</ref>\n*[[Thomas Porteous|Former Judge Thomas Porteous]]'s impeachment trial defense <ref name=porteo>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/dec/7/senate-takes-impeachment-louisiana-judge/ Senate takes up impeachment of Louisiana judge], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', December 7, 2010</ref> Turley characterized Porteus' chronic bribe-taking as merely being a \"moocher\", convicted on four articles of impeachment, removed as judge by a Senate vote of 94-2 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=111&session=2&vote=00265|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 111th Congress - 2nd Session|website=www.senate.gov}}</ref><ref name=latimes>{{cite web\n|author = Michael A. Memoli\n| title = Senate convicts Louisiana federal judge in impeachment trial\n| publisher = Los Angeles Times\n| date = 2010-12-09\n| url = https://articles.latimes.com/2010/dec/09/news/la-pn-senate-impeachment-20101209\n| format =\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05\n| quote = The Senate also voted to bar him from ever holding public office in the future... The vote on the first count was unanimous, 96-0. On subsequent counts, the votes were 69-27, 88-8, and 90-6. Impeachment required a vote of two-thirds of the Senate.}}</ref> \n*Defendants in terrorism cases, including [[Ali al-Tamimi]] (the alleged head of the Virginia Jihad/Paintball conspiracy)-<ref name=sami>[http://www.freesamialarian.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=9:dr-al-arians-attorneys&Itemid=6&layout=default Dr. Al-Arian's Lawyers in Virginia], Free Sami Al-Arian website</ref>\n*[[Area 51]] workers at a secret air base in Nevada.<ref name=area51>[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1998/aug/07/lawyer-views-high-court-appeal-of-area-51-lawsuit-/ Lawyer views high court appeal of Area 51 lawsuit a longshot], ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', August 7, 1998</ref><ref name=glimpse>[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2000/apr/18/at-last-a-glimpse-of-area-51/ At last, a glimpse of Area 51], ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', April 18, 2000</ref>\n*Lead counsel in the litigation over the mass arrests at the [[Washington A16, 2000|World Bank/IMF protests in Washington]].<ref>[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/crime-scene/del-quentin-wilber/lawyers-fees-top-2-million-in.html Pershing Park lawyers fees top $2M], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', March 4, 2011</ref>\n*Turley represented the [[Rocky Flats Plant|Rocky Flats]] grand jury in Colorado <ref name=rocky>[http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_9164267 Some Flats data public], ''[[The Denver Post]]'', May 6, 2008</ref>\n* Turley testified on December 4, 2019, regarding the impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump, regarding constitutional issues not supporting the impeachment of Trump.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nTurley married his wife, Leslie, on [[New Year's Eve]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |last=Turley |first=Jonathan |date=December 31, 2013 |title=Happy New Year's Eve!!! |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2013/12/31/happy-new-years-eve-3/ |website=Jonathan Turley |access-date=October 29, 2016}}</ref>{{third party inline|date=January 2020}} He and his wife live in [[Washington, D.C.]],{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} and have four children.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} They keep a [[Goldendoodle]] named \"Luna\" as a pet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-impeachment-inquirty-jonathan-turley-goldendoodle-mad-2019-12|title=A Republican legal expert says even his goldendoodle Luna is mad about impeachment, so we shouldn't pursue it|last=McLaughlin|first=Kelly|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://jonathanturley.org/}}\n* [https://www.law.gwu.edu/jonathan-turley?id=1738 Jonathan Turley] at [[George Washington University Law School]]\n** [https://www.law.gwu.edu/turley-jonathan and bibliography]\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turley, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:American legal writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:Anti-bullying activists]]\n[[Category:George Washington University faculty]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University Pritzker School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Scholars of constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Tulane University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tulane University Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the professor of law|the children's book author|Jon Turley}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{multiple issues |\n{{user-generated|date=January 2020}}\n{{ref expand|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox scholar\n|image          = Jonathan turley 5263504.jpg\n|caption        = Turley in 2016\n|name           = Jonathan Turley\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|5|6}}{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n|birth_place    = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|education      = [[University of Chicago]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Northwestern University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|discipline     = [[Law]]\n|sub_discipline = [[Constitutional law]], [[tort|tort law]], [[criminal law]], [[legal theory]]\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Leslie|December 31, 1997}}\n|children       = 4{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n| website       = {{URL|jonathanturley.org}}\n}}\n'''Jonathan Turley''' (born May 6, 1961{{citation needed lead|date=January 2020}}) is an American [[attorney at law|attorney]], legal scholar, writer, commentator, and legal analyst in broadcast and print journalism. He is a professor at the [[George Washington University Law School]], and has testified in United States Congressional proceedings about constitutional and statutory issues. He participated in the impeachment of President [[Bill Clinton]] and the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment inquiry]] of President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/472957-gops-invited-witness-argues-against-trump-impeachment|title=GOP witness to say Trump impeachment would set a 'dangerous precedent'|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2007/08/20/clinton-impeachment-testimony-house-judiciary-committee/|title=Clinton Impeachment Testimony: House Judiciary Committee|date=August 20, 2007|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nJonathan Turley was born in Chicago, Illinois, on May 6, 1961.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Turley served as a House leadership page in 1977 and 1978 under the sponsorship of Illinois Democrat [[Sidney R. Yates|Sidney Yates]].<ref name=yates>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-10-10/news/0010100245_1_hubert-h-humphrey-page-quiet-moments A Farewell To Sid Yates], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', October 10, 2000</ref>\n\nTurley received his bachelor's degree from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1983, and his [[Juris Doctor]] degree from [[Northwestern University School of Law]] in 1987.\n\nDuring the [[Reagan Administration]], Turley worked as an intern with the general counsel\u2019s office of the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA).<ref name=\"TurleyNSAlawyer2014\">{{cite web |last1=Turley |first1=Jonathan |title=Report: NSA Spied On Lawyers In Confidential Communications With Clients |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2014/02/17/report-nsa-spied-on-lawyers-in-confidential-communications-with-clients/ |website=JONATHAN TURLEY. Res ipsa loquitur \u2013 The thing itself speaks |accessdate=26 February 2020 |date=February 17, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"TurleyGrenell2020\">{{cite web |last1=Turley |first1=Jonathan |title=Richard Grenell Achieves A Historic Milestone As Acting Director Of National Intelligence |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2020/02/24/richard-grenell-achieves-a-historic-milestone-as-acting-director-of-national-intelligence/ |website=JONATHAN TURLEY. Res ipsa loquitur \u2013 The thing itself speaks |accessdate=26 February 2020 |date=February 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jonathan Turley.jpg|thumb|left|Testifying at the Supreme Court, 2007]]\n\n==Career==\nTurley holds the Shapiro Chair for Public Interest Law at The George Washington University Law School where he teaches [[torts]], [[criminal procedure]], and [[constitutional law]]. He is the youngest person to receive an academic chair in the school's history. He runs the Project for Older Prisoners (POPS),<ref name=pops>[https://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/commentary/la-oe-turley7oct07,0,243039.story?coll=la-news-comment-opinions Release Elderly Inmates], by Jonathan Turley, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', October 7, 2006</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.gwu.edu/Academics/EL/clinics/Pages/POPS.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414143034/http://www.law.gwu.edu/Academics/EL/clinics/Pages/POPS.aspx|url-status=dead|title=George Washington University Law School, The Project for Older Prisoners|archivedate=April 14, 2011|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> the Environmental Law Clinic, and the Environmental Legislation Project.<ref name=turley/>\n\nPrior to joining the George Washington University, he was on the faculty of [[Tulane University Law School]].<ref name=turley>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.gwu.edu/jonathan-turley?id=1738|title=Jonathan Turley &#124; GW Law &#124; The George Washington University|website=www.law.gwu.edu|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis articles on legal and policy issues appear regularly in national publications; as of 2012, Turley has had articles published in newspapers such as ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/04/opinion/04turley.html Get Congress Out of the Page Business], by Jonathan Turley, ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 4, 2006</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref name=wapost>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/09/AR2009040903155.html The Free World Bars Free Speech], by Jonathan Turley, ''[[The Washington Post]]'', April 12, 2009</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref name=guns>{{cite news|last=Turley |first=Jonathan |title=A liberal's lament: The NRA might be right after all |url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20071004/opcom_thurs.art.htm |accessdate=September 6, 2012 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=October 4, 2007 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AUNd905W?url=http://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20071004/opcom_thurs.art.htm |archivedate=September 7, 2012 |page=A 11 |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |url-status=dead }}</ref> the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',<ref name=pops/> and the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB90570708755275500 Perjury Isn't a Political Decision], by Jonathan Turley, The Wall Street Journal, September 14, 1998</ref> He frequently appears in the national media as a commentator on a multitude of subjects<ref name=media>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/turley073098.htm Jonathan Turley Takes His Case to TV], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', July 30, 1998</ref><ref name=msnbc>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121105113922/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/35490005?q=Jonathan%20Turley Jonathan Turley at MSNBC] Jonathan Turley at [[MSNBC]]</ref> ranging from the [[U.S. presidential election, 2000|2000 U.S. presidential election]] controversy to the [[Terri Schiavo]] case in 2005.<ref name=schiavo>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2005-03-22-schiavo-law_x.htm Temptation tops the Constitution], ''[[USA Today]]'', March 22, 2005</ref> He often is a guest on Sunday talk shows,<ref name=media/> with more than two-dozen appearances on ''[[Meet the Press]]'', ''[[This Week (ABC TV series)|ABC This Week]]'', ''[[Face the Nation]]'', and ''[[Fox News Sunday]]''. He served as a contributor on ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'' from 2003 until 2011, and later on [[Current TV]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/business/media/20pundit.html?_r=1 At New Network, Olbermann Sets Sights on MSNBC], ''[[The New York Times]]'',  June 19, 2011</ref> in 2011 and early 2012; Turley also appears occasionally on [[Pacifica Radio]]'s ''[[Democracy Now!]]''.<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/2006/6/27/is_bush_administrations_bank_spy_program Is Bush Administration\u2019s Bank Spy Program One Part of a Resurgent Total Information Awareness?], [[Democracy Now!]], June 27, 2006</ref>\n\nSince the 1990s, he has been the legal analyst for [[NBC News]] and [[CBS News]] covering stories that ranged from the Clinton impeachment to the presidential elections.<ref name=turley/> He is on the board of contributors of ''USA Today''.<ref name=usaboard>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/USA-TODAY-board-of-contributors.htm ''USA Today's'' Board of Contributors], ''[[USA Today]]'', March 22, 2011</ref> and writes regularly for the Washington Post. He has written hundreds of columns in those papers and other national publications including the Wall Street Journal, Los Angeles Times, Chicago Tribune, and other publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/about/ |title=Bio \u2013 Jonathan Turley |publisher=Jonathanturley.org |date= |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  He is also a columnist with the Hill newspaper <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/social-tags/jonathan-turley|title=Jonathan Turley|website=TheHill|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> He currently is legal analyst for CBS News and the BBC.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/about/|title=Bio|date=August 18, 2007|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n<!--\nHe said, \"France has turned into one of the worldwide threats to free speech\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/civil-rights/451813-france-has-turned-into-one-of-the-worldwide-threats-to-free-speech|title=France has turned into one of the worldwide threats to free speech|first=Anjelica|last=Tan|date=July 6, 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref>-->\n\n==Politics==\n{{expand section | with = up-to-date content that follows some logical structure, e.g., chronology of date of published opinion, or grouping of stated opinions, with statements chronological within those (so evolution of perspective can be gleaned) | small = no|date=January 2020}} \nIn numerous appearances on ''Countdown with Keith Olbermann'' and ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', he called for criminal prosecution of Bush administration officials for [[war crime]]s, including torture.<ref name=maddow>[http://wn.com/rachel_maddow_show_jonathan_turley_on_war_crimes%20Rachel%20Maddow%20Show,%20Jonathan%20Turley%20On%20War%20Crimes Rachel Maddow Show: Jonathan Turley on War Crimes], Video, January 10, 2009</ref>\n\nIn ''[[USA Today]]'' in October 2004, he famously argued for the [[legal status of polygamy|legalization of polygamy]],<ref>[http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/opinion/columnist/2004-10-03-turley_x.htm \"Polygamy laws expose our own hypocrisy\"]. ''USA Today''. Published: October 3, 2004.</ref> provoking responses from writers such as [[Stanley Kurtz]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120114132504/https://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/012/266jhfgd.asp?nopager=1 \"Polygamy vs. Democracy\"]. ''The Weekly Standard''. Published: June 5, 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.albertmohler.com/2004/10/05/the-floodgates-open-usa-today-promotes-polygamy/ \"The Floodgates Open: USA Today Promotes Polygamy\"].</ref>\n\nCommenting on the [[Military Commissions Act of 2006]], which, he contends, does away with ''[[habeas corpus]]'', Turley says, \"It's something that no one thought\u2014certainly I didn't think\u2014was possible in the United States. And I am not too sure how we got to this point. But people clearly don't realize what a fundamental change it is about who we are as a country. What happened today changed us.\"<ref name=yawn/>\n\nHe is a critic of special treatment for the church in law, asking why there are laws that \"expressly exempt faith-based actions that result in harm.\"<ref name=church>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/discussion/2009/11/13/DI2009111303161.html When a child dies, faith is no defense. Why do courts give believers a pass?], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', November 16, 2009</ref>\n\nTurley disagrees with the theory that dealing with [[Bullying|bullies]] is just a part of growing up, claiming that they are \"no more a natural part of learning than is parental abuse a natural part of growing up\" and believes that \"[[litigation]] could succeed in forcing schools to take bullying more seriously\".<ref name=bully>\"[https://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=5378214&page=1 Bullying's Day in Court]\", ''[[USA Today]]'', July 15, 2008</ref>\n\nHe has written extensively about the injustice of the [[death penalty]], noting, \"Human error remains a principal cause of botched executions... eventually society will be forced to deal directly with a fundamental moral question: Has death itself become the intolerable element of the death penalty?\"<ref name=death>[http://www.fadp.org/news/20080117(4)/ The Punishment Fits the Times] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928052851/http://www.fadp.org/news/20080117%284%29/ |date=September 28, 2011 }}\", ''[[USA Today]]'', January 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nHe worries that the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] is injecting itself into partisan politics.<ref name=scalia>[https://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/05/nation/la-na-scalia-20110105 Scalia to Talk About Constitution to House Members], ''Los Angeles Times'', January 5, 2011</ref> He frequently has expressed the view that recent nominees to the court hold extreme views.<ref name=exviews>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2006-01-09-troubling-times_x.htm Troubling Times, a Troubling Nominee]\", ''USA Today'', January 9, 2006</ref><ref name=roberts>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2006-07-05-turley-edit_x.htm The Roberts Court: Seeing Is Believing]\", ''USA Today'', July 5, 2006</ref>\n\nTurley has said, \"It is hard to read the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] and not honestly conclude that the Framers intended gun ownership to be an individual right.\"<ref name=guns/> Moreover, Turley testified in favor of the Clinton impeachment.<ref name=peach>\"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/impeach111598.htm House Takes Up Impeachment Task With Time Short]\", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', November 15, 1998</ref>\n\nIn another commentary, Turley defended Judge [[Henry E. Hudson]]'s ruling declaring the [[health insurance mandate|individual mandate in health insurance]] unconstitutional for violating the [[Commerce Clause|Commerce Clause of the Constitution]]: \"It's very thoughtful\u2014not a screed. I don't see any evidence this is motivated by Judge Hudson's personal beliefs... Anybody who's dismissing this opinion as a political screed has obviously not read the opinion.\"<ref name=hudson>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1210/46338_Page2.html Health-law judge's prosecutor past], by Josh Gerstein, ''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'', December 13, 2010</ref>\n\nTurley described U.S. Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] in an op-ed as President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[sin-eater]], writing:\n\n{{quote|For Obama, there has been no better sin eater than Holder. When the president promised CIA employees early in his first term that they would not be investigated for torture, it was the attorney general who shielded officials from prosecution. When the Obama administration decided it would expand secret and warrantless surveillance, it was Holder who justified it. When the president wanted the authority to kill any American he deemed a threat without charge or trial, it was Holder who went public to announce the \"kill list\" policy. Last week, the Justice Department confirmed that it was Holder who personally approved the equally abusive search of Fox News correspondent [[James Rosen (journalist)|James Rosen]]'s e-mail and phone records in another story involving leaked classified information. In the 2010 application for a secret warrant, the Obama administration named Rosen as \"an aider and abettor and/or co-conspirator\" to the leaking of classified materials. The Justice Department even investigated Rosen's parents' telephone number, and Holder was there to justify every attack on the news media.<ref name=Mike>Turley, Jonathan. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2013/05/28/fire-eric-holder-column/2367713/ \"Fire Eric Holder\"],''[[USA Today]]'', May 29, 2013</ref>}}\n\nIn a December 2013 congressional hearing, responding to a question from Rep. Bob Goodlatte (R-VA) about the danger posed by President Barack Obama's apparent unilateral modification of laws passed by Congress, Turley said:\n\n{{quote|The danger is quite severe. The problem with what the president is doing is that he's not simply posing a danger to the constitutional system. He's becoming the very danger the Constitution was designed to avoid. That is the concentration of power in every single branch. This Newtonian orbit that the three branches exist in is a delicate one but it is designed to prevent this type of concentration. There {{sic|is}} two trends going on which should be of equal concern to all members of Congress. One is that we have had the radical expansion of presidential powers under both President Bush and President Obama. We have what many once called an imperial presidency model of largely unchecked authority. And with that trend we also have the continued rise of this fourth branch. We have agencies that are quite large that issue regulations. The Supreme Court said recently that agencies could actually define their own or interpret their own jurisdiction.<ref name=Bill>[http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2013/12/04/turley_obamas_become_the_very_danger_the_constitution_was_designed_to_avoid.html Turley: Obama's \"Become The Very Danger The Constitution Was Designed To Avoid\"], ''[[Real Clear Politics]]'', December 5, 2013</ref>}}\n\nOn November 21, 2014, Turley agreed to represent House Speaker [[John Boehner]] and the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] in a suit filed against the Obama administration alleging unconstitutional implementation of the Affordable Care Act, specifically the [[health insurance mandate|individual mandate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/11/21/politics/house-gop-sue-the-president-over-obamacare/index.html|title=Boehner: House GOP files Obamacare suit - CNNPolitics|author=By Deirdre Walsh and Dana Bash|website=CNN|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2016, Libertarian Party candidate for President, Gary Johnson, announced that if elected Turley would be one of his two top choices for the Supreme Court seat that remained open following the death of Justice Antonin Scalia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thelibertarianrepublic.com/johnson-top-scotus-picks/|title=Gary Johnson Announces His Top 2 SCOTUS Picks|date=October 12, 2016|newspaper=The Libertarian Republic|language=en-US|access-date=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2017 column for ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', Turley was critical of [[military intervention]] in the Middle East and questioned its constitutionality. He also mentioned that he supported the Supreme Court nomination of [[Neil Gorsuch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/defense/326359-is-americas-military-effort-in-the-middle-east-constitutional|title=Is America's military effort in the Middle East constitutional?|first=Anjelica|last=Tan|date=March 29, 2017|website=TheHill|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Testimony before Congress===\nThe conceptual thread running through many of the issues taken on by Turley, is that they involve claims of [[executive privilege]]. For example, he said, \"the president's claim of executive authority based on Article II would put our system on a slippery slope.\"<ref name=privil>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2006/jan/17/20060117-101314-5569r/ Legal scholars split on wiretaps], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', January 17, 2006</ref> He has argued against national security exceptions to fundamental [[constitutional right]]s.<ref name=exviews/><ref name=congress>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2007-01-17-turley-edit_x.htm Can Congress stop the war?], ''[[USA Today]]'', January 17, 2007</ref>\n\nHe is a frequent witness before the House and Senate on constitutional and statutory issues,<ref name=porteo/><ref name=future>[http://www.fff.org/conference2008/speakers/index.htm Restoring the Republic 2008: Foreign Policy & Civil Liberties] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020142944/http://www.fff.org/conference2008/speakers/index.htm |date=October 20, 2011 }}, The Future of Freedom Foundation, June 6, 2008</ref> as well as, tort reform legislation.<ref name=turley/>\n\nTurley has testified regularly during national controversies. He testified at the confirmation hearings of Associate Justice [[Neil Gorsuch]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2017/03/23/turley-testifies-in-senate-gorsuch-confirmation-hearing/|title=TURLEY TESTIFIES IN SENATE GORSUCH CONFIRMATION HEARING|date=March 23, 2017|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2015/01/29/turley-testimony-in-senate-confirmation-hearing-of-loretta-lynch/|title=Turley Testimony In Senate Confirmation Hearing Of Loretta Lynch|date=January 29, 2015|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> and Attorney General [[William Barr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonathanturley.org/2019/01/16/turley-testifies-in-barr-confirmation-hearing/|title=TURLEY TESTIFIES IN BARR CONFIRMATION HEARING|date=January 16, 2019|website=JONATHAN TURLEY|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> He also testified during the [[Impeachment of Bill Clinton|Clinton impeachment]] hearings.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nTurley also has testified in Congress against President Bush's [[NSA warrantless surveillance controversy|warrantless domestic surveillance program]] and was lead counsel in a case challenging it. In regard to warrantless wiretaps he noted that, \"[[Anna Diggs Taylor|Judge Anna Diggs Taylor]] chastised the government for a flagrant abuse of the Constitution and, in a direct message to the president, observed that ''there are no hereditary kings in America.''\"<ref name=snoop>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-08-20/news/0608200377_1_surveillance-program-national-security-agency-surveillance-controversial-monitoring-program NSA ruling much like a pig in parlor], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', August 20, 2006</ref>\n\nWhen Congressional Democrats asked the justice department to investigate the CIA's [[2005 CIA interrogation tapes destruction|destruction of terrorist interrogation tapes]] Turley said, \"these are very serious allegations, that raise as many as six identifiable crimes ranging from contempt of Congress, to contempt of Justice, to perjury, to false statements.\"<ref name=tapes>[http://www.voanews.com/english/news/a-13-2007-12-08-voa36.html CIA, US Justice Dept. to Investigate Destruction of Interrogation Tapes], ''[[Voice of America News]]'', December 8, 2007</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, in an interview by [[Keith Olbermann]] of [[MSNBC]], he expressed strong disapproval of the [[Military Commissions Act of 2006]].<ref name=yawn>[https://www.nbcnews.com/id/15318240 National yawn as our rights evaporate], New law redefines habeas corpus law professor explains, ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'', October 17, 2006</ref>\n\nWhen the U.S. Senate was about to vote on [[Michael Mukasey]] for U.S. attorney general, Turley said, \"The attorney general nominee's evasive remarks on '[[water-boarding]]' should disqualify him from the job.\"<ref name=water>[https://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/commentary/la-oe-turley24oct24,0,1182359.story?coll=la-news-comment-opinions Mukasey's confirmation: a vote about torture], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', October 24, 2007</ref> On the treatment of terrorism suspect [[Jos\u00e9 Padilla (prisoner)|Jos\u00e9 Padilla]], Turley says, \"The treatment of Padilla ranks as one of the most serious abuses after 9/11... This is a case that would have shocked the Framers. This is precisely what many of the drafters of the Constitution had in mind when they tried to create a system of checks and balances.\" Turley considers the case of great import on the grounds that \"Padilla's treatment by the military could happen to others.\"<ref name=padilla>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2007/0904/p02s01-usju.html In Padilla interrogation, no checks or balances], ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', September 4, 2007</ref>\n\nTurley, in his capacity as a constitutional scholar,<ref name=scholar>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061130111243/http://www.rollingstone.com/politics/story/12055360/cover_story_time_to_go_inside_the_worst_congress_ever/6 The Worst Congress Ever], ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', October 17, 2006</ref> testified in favor of the Clinton impeachment.<ref name=peach/><ref name=peach2>[http://jonathanturley.org/2007/08/20/clinton-impeachment-testimony-house-judiciary-committee/ Clinton Impeachment Testimony] [[House Judiciary Committee]], August 20, 2007</ref> He was quoted extensively by congressman [[James E. Rogan|James Rogan]] during the [[impeachment of Bill Clinton]].<ref name=winsky>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/articleiv121298.htm The Impeachment Hearings, Debate on Article IV], ''[[Federal News Service]]'', December 12, 1998</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2019, Turley testified before the House Judiciary Committee regarding the constitutional grounds for presidential impeachment in the [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]], arguing against a Trump impeachment.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=biturley /><ref name=esquireturley /><ref name=nwturley /> In his testimony, Professor Turley objected to the effort to craft articles of impeachment around four criminal allegations\" bribery, extortion, obstruction of justice, and campaign finance violations.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://int.nyt.com/data/documenthelper/6547-jonathan-turley-s-opening-stat/739d3374f20a9ed69157/optimized/full.pdf |title=Opening statement |publisher=int.nyt.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  He argued that the evidence did not meet the standard definitions of those crimes and, against the testimony of the three Democratic witnesses, such legal definitions have always been used as a measure for impeachment deliberations.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>  Turley objected to the lower of the impeachment standards to \"fit a paucity of evidence and an abundance of anger.\" <ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.jurist.org/news/2019/12/house-judiciary-committee-holds-first-impeachment-hearing/|title= House Judiciary Committee holds first impeachment hearing|last=Bloomberg |first=Anna |date=209 |website= www.jurist.org|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> The Committee ultimately rejected all four of those articles and adopted the two that Professor Turley argued could be legitimate if proven: abuse of power and obstruction of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/judiciary/476088-testifying-for-republicans-should-not-be-a-sin-for-academics |title=Turley: Testifying for Republicans should not be a sin for academics |publisher=TheHill |date=2019-12-28 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  Where the Committee departed from the testimony was the rejection of Professor Turley call for more time to develop a more complete record rather than fulfill a promise to impeach by Christmas\u2014an issue that was rekindled by the delay in the submission of the articles to the Senate as new evidence emerged in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/judiciary/476745-democratic-impeachment-case-collapses-under-weight-of-time |title=Democratic impeachment case collapses under weight of time |publisher=TheHill |date=2020-01-04 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref> It was observed that the bases he expressed regarding his prior position that President [[Bill Clinton]] should be impeached diametrically contradicted the opinions he shared regarding the impeachment of President [[Donald Trump]], twenty one years later.<ref name=biturley /><ref name=esquireturley /><ref name=nwturley /> Those 2019 reports contrasted his extensive quotes from the separate processes.<ref name=biturley>[https://www.businessinsider.com/republican-witness-jonathan-turley-contradicted-impeachment-testimony-2019-12 The GOP's only impeachment witness on Wednesday contradicted his own previous testimony], ''[[Business Insider]]'', Sonam Sheth,December 4, 2019. Retrieved December 5, 2019.</ref><ref name=esquireturley>[https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a30122007/jonathan-turley-impeachment-hearing-trump-ukraine/ Jonathan Turley Is Exhibit A That the Clinton Debacle Never Really Ended], ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', Charles Pierce, December 4, 2019. Retrieved December 5, 2019.</ref><ref name=nwturley>[https://www.newsweek.com/clinton-trump-impeachment-constitutional-scholars-1475578  Trump impeachment hearings: Legal scholars' testimony in both Trump, Clinton cases stress 'Abuse of power'], ''[[Newsweek]]'', James Crowley, December 4, 2019. Retrieved December 5, 2019.</ref> Turley sought to clarify his positions regarding the two impeachments the next day in an op-ed.<ref name=\"thehill1\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/judiciary/473171-turley-democrats-offering-passion-over-proof-in-trump-impeachment |title=Turley: Democrats offering passion over proof in Trump impeachment |publisher=TheHill |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  Turley noted that in both hearings he stressed that a president could be impeached for non-criminal acts, including abuse of power, and House Judiciary Chairman Jerry Nadler ended the Trump impeachment hearings by quoting him to that effect. He has noted that the only disagreement was the sufficiency of the record and his calling on House to issue subpoenas for key witnesses like former national security adviser John Bolton.<ref name=\"thehill1\"/> The push for additional time was due in part to Turley's concern that the House was going to impeach a president for going to the courts rather than yielding to congressional demands for witnesses and documents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/05/784994918/jonathan-turley-on-his-impeachment-testimony |title=Jonathan Turley On His Impeachment Testimony |publisher=NPR |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-01-18}}</ref>  Given the short period of investigation, Turley objected that such a move would effectively make seeking judicial review as high crime and misdemeanor. He noted that both Presidents Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton were able to go all the way to the Supreme Court on their challenges before impeachment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-12-09/opinion-trump-impeachment-hearings-democrats |title=Opinion on the hearing |last= |first= |date= December 9, 2019|website=www.latimes.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> While Turley told the Committee that such judicial opinions were not required to impeach on obstruction, the abbreviated period of investigation undermined the foundation of that article.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-12-18/house-impeachment-vote-impulse-holiday-shopping |title= House impeachment vote |date= December 18, 2019|website=www.latimes.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> Turley was cited by both the White House and House managers in their arguments before the United States Senate in the Trump impeachment trial.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/WTXLABC27HD/videos/784565198676296/</ref>  During the trial, Turley opposed the White House argument that impeachment requires a criminal allegation.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51200828</ref> Turley wrote in the Washington Post that \"If some of the president\u2019s critics are adopting a far too broad understanding of impeachable offenses, the White House is adopting a far too narrow one.\"<ref>https://washingtonpost.com//opinions/2020/01/21/where-trump-defense-goes-too-far/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{update|section|date=January 2020}}\nTurley was ranked as 38th in the top 100 most cited \"public intellectuals\" (and second most cited law professor) in a 2001 study by Judge Richard Posner of intellectuals referenced in the media and public debates.<ref name=posner>''Public intellectuals : a study of decline'', by Richard A. Posner, Harvard University Press, 2001, {{ISBN|0-674-00633-X}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Turley was given the Columnist of the Year award for Single-Issue Advocacy for his columns on civil liberties by the [[Aspen Institute]]<ref name=turley/> and ''[[The Week]]'' magazine.<ref name=civlib>[https://theweek.com/article/index/201877/history-of-the-opinion-awards History of the Opinion Awards], ''[[The Week Magazine]]'', April 14, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he was awarded an honorary doctorate of law from [[John Marshall Law School (Atlanta)|John Marshall Law School]] in recognition of his career as an advocate of civil liberties and constitutional rights.<ref name=marshall>[http://www.jmls.edu/in_the_loop/previous/2008/01202008/index.shtml The John Marshall Law School] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927220519/http://www.jmls.edu/in_the_loop/previous/2008/01202008/index.shtml |date=September 27, 2011 }}, January 20, 2008</ref>\n\nHe was ranked among the nation's top 500 lawyers in 2008.<ref name=top500>[http://www.lawdragon.com/index.php/newdragon/leading_08/?sort=name&at=400&tot=100 The Lawdragon 500 for 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722223304/http://www.lawdragon.com/index.php/newdragon/leading_08/?sort=name&at=400&tot=100 |date=July 22, 2011 }}, October 16, 2008</ref> Turley was found to be the second most cited law professor in the country as well as being ranked as one of the top ten military lawyers.<ref name=turley/>\n\nIn 2008 his blog was ranked as the top law professor blog and legal theory blog by the ''[[ABA Journal|American Bar Association Journal]]'' survey of the top 100 blogs.<ref name=best>[http://www.abajournal.com/magazine/article/blawg_100_2008 The Blawg 100], [[ABA Journal]], December 2, 2008</ref><ref name=best2>[http://jonathanturley.org/2008/12/27/the-turley-blog-leads-in-vote-on-best-law-professor-and-legal-theory-blogs/ The Turley Blog Leads in Vote on Best Law Professor and Legal Theory Blogs], Jonathan Turley blog, December 27, 2008</ref> His work with older prisoners has been honored in various states, including his selection as the 2011 recipient of the Dr. Mary Ann Quaranta Elder Justice Award at Fordham University.<ref name=\"auto\"/> &nbsp;He has received other awards including the James Madison award and was declared one of four university fellows at the Utah Valley University in 2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Prominent cases==\nTurley has served as counsel in notable cases; representing whistleblowers, military personnel, and a wide range of other clients in national security, environmental, and constitutional law cases. His  cases as lead counsel have secured decisions striking down both a federal and a state law,<ref name=\"auto\"/> among them:\n\n*Lead counsel in [[United States House of Representatives v. Price]], the 2014 constitutional challenge of President Obama's changes to the Affordable Care Act\n*Lead counsel in ''[[Brown v. Buhman]]'', for the Brown family from the TLC reality series ''[[Sister Wives]]'', in their challenge of Utah's criminalization of polygamy\n*Lead counsel for five former United States Attorneys General in litigation during the Clinton Impeachment in federal court\n*Lead counsel to 'Five Wives Vodka\" in successful challenge of ban on sales in Idaho due to a finding that the product was insulting to Mormons\n*Lead counsel representing Dr. [[Sami Al-Arian]] in securing this release for civil contempt and later, in defense of criminal contempt charges (which were dropped after years of litigation)\n*Larry Hanauer, a House Intelligence Committee staff member falsely accused of leaking classified information to ''The New York Times'' <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/22/washington/22intel.html House Staff Member Cleared in Inquiry on Leak of Iraq Intelligence Estimate], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 22, 2006</ref>\n*David Faulk, a whistleblower who revealed abuses at NSA's [[Fort Gordon]] surveillance programs <ref>[http://legaltimes.typepad.com/blt/2008/10/jonathan-turley.html Jonathan Turley to Advise NSA Whitsle-blower], Legal Times and [[The National Law Journal]], October 10, 2008</ref>\n*Dr. Eric Foretich,<ref name=future/> in overturning the [[Elizabeth Morgan Act]] in 2003 <ref name=morgan>[http://jonathanturley.org/2007/11/20/elizabeth-morgan-act-and-legislating-family-values/ Elizabeth Morgan Act and Legislating Family Values] November 20, 2007</ref>\n*[[Thomas Porteous|Former Judge Thomas Porteous]]'s impeachment trial defense <ref name=porteo>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/dec/7/senate-takes-impeachment-louisiana-judge/ Senate takes up impeachment of Louisiana judge], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', December 7, 2010</ref> Turley characterized Porteus' chronic bribe-taking as merely being a \"moocher\", convicted on four articles of impeachment, removed as judge by a Senate vote of 94-2 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=111&session=2&vote=00265|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 111th Congress - 2nd Session|website=www.senate.gov}}</ref><ref name=latimes>{{cite web\n|author = Michael A. Memoli\n| title = Senate convicts Louisiana federal judge in impeachment trial\n| publisher = Los Angeles Times\n| date = 2010-12-09\n| url = https://articles.latimes.com/2010/dec/09/news/la-pn-senate-impeachment-20101209\n| format =\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05\n| quote = The Senate also voted to bar him from ever holding public office in the future... The vote on the first count was unanimous, 96-0. On subsequent counts, the votes were 69-27, 88-8, and 90-6. Impeachment required a vote of two-thirds of the Senate.}}</ref> \n*Defendants in terrorism cases, including [[Ali al-Tamimi]] (the alleged head of the Virginia Jihad/Paintball conspiracy)-<ref name=sami>[http://www.freesamialarian.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=9:dr-al-arians-attorneys&Itemid=6&layout=default Dr. Al-Arian's Lawyers in Virginia], Free Sami Al-Arian website</ref>\n*[[Area 51]] workers at a secret air base in Nevada.<ref name=area51>[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1998/aug/07/lawyer-views-high-court-appeal-of-area-51-lawsuit-/ Lawyer views high court appeal of Area 51 lawsuit a longshot], ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', August 7, 1998</ref><ref name=glimpse>[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2000/apr/18/at-last-a-glimpse-of-area-51/ At last, a glimpse of Area 51], ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', April 18, 2000</ref>\n*Lead counsel in the litigation over the mass arrests at the [[Washington A16, 2000|World Bank/IMF protests in Washington]].<ref>[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/crime-scene/del-quentin-wilber/lawyers-fees-top-2-million-in.html Pershing Park lawyers fees top $2M], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', March 4, 2011</ref>\n*Turley represented the [[Rocky Flats Plant|Rocky Flats]] grand jury in Colorado <ref name=rocky>[http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_9164267 Some Flats data public], ''[[The Denver Post]]'', May 6, 2008</ref>\n* Turley testified on December 4, 2019, regarding the impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump, regarding constitutional issues not supporting the impeachment of Trump.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nTurley married his wife, Leslie, on [[New Year's Eve]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |last=Turley |first=Jonathan |date=December 31, 2013 |title=Happy New Year's Eve!!! |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2013/12/31/happy-new-years-eve-3/ |website=Jonathan Turley |access-date=October 29, 2016}}</ref>{{third party inline|date=January 2020}} He and his wife live in [[Washington, D.C.]],{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} and have four children.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} They keep a [[Goldendoodle]] named \"Luna\" as a pet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-impeachment-inquirty-jonathan-turley-goldendoodle-mad-2019-12|title=A Republican legal expert says even his goldendoodle Luna is mad about impeachment, so we shouldn't pursue it|last=McLaughlin|first=Kelly|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://jonathanturley.org/}}\n* [https://www.law.gwu.edu/jonathan-turley?id=1738 Jonathan Turley] at [[George Washington University Law School]]\n** [https://www.law.gwu.edu/turley-jonathan and bibliography]\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turley, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:American legal writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:Anti-bullying activists]]\n[[Category:George Washington University faculty]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University Pritzker School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Scholars of constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Tulane University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tulane University Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing bot mistake (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Turley"}
{"title_page": "Jessy Mendiola", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Short description|Filipino actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Philippine name|Mendiola|Tawile}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jessy Mendiola\n| image              = Jessy Mendiola 06-19-14.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Mendiola on July 19, 2014\n| birth_name         = Jessica Mendiola Tawile\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1992|12|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]\n| residence          = \n| alma_mater         = Kester Grant College\n| occupation         = Actress, Model \n| years_active       = 2004\u2013present\n| agent              = [[Star Magic]] (2007\u2013present) <br/> [[Viva Entertainment|Viva Artists Agency]] (2019\u2013present)\n| known_for          = ''[[Maria Mercedes (Philippine TV series)|Maria Mercedes]]'' <br/>''[[Maalaala Mo Kaya]]''<br/>''[[Budoy]]''\n| home_town          = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Jessica Mendiola Tawile''' (born December 3, 1992)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Villar|first1=Ferdie|title=Will Sam Milby really pursue Jessy Mendiola's heart?|url=http://asianjournal.com/lifestyle/will-sam-milby-really-pursue-jessy-mendiolas-heart/|accessdate=March 15, 2017|work=Asian Journal|date=September 12, 2013}}</ref> is a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] actress. She played the titular character in the [[Maria Mercedes (Philippine telenovela)|2013 remake]] of the 1992 Mexican telenovela ''[[Mar\u00eda Mercedes (telenovela)|Maria Mercedes]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMendiola was born in [[Dubai]], where her father used to work.<ref name=\"Malaya\"/> She is the second of three siblings of a Filipina mother and a [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] - British father.<ref name=\"Jessie Mendiola on the buzz\"/>{{dead link|date=January 2019}}  She was three years old when her mother moved and brought her and her elder sister Pamela to the [[Philippines]]. Her mother left her father due to his infidelity. Jessy's younger sister Megan was born in Mexico, where her parents reconciled but eventually separated again for unknown reasons. She remains in contact with her father, who works overseas as a marine anthropologist.<ref name=\"Journal\"/> She studied [[mass communication]] at [[Far Eastern University]].\n\n==Career==\nJessy Mendiola was one of the 18 new talents launched by [[ABS-CBN]] under [[Star Magic]] Batch 15.<ref name='Star Magic Batch 15'/> She, along with [[Megan Young]], [[Alfonso Martinez (actor)|Alfonso Martinez]], [[Carlo Guevarra]] and her Star Magic batchmates, joined the cast of ''[[Star Magic Presents]]: [[Abt Ur Luv]]'', when it was revamped to ''[[Abt Ur Luv|Abt Ur Luv Ur Lyf 2]]'' in 2007. She also had a minor role in ''[[Sineserye Presents]]: [[Natutulog Ba Ang Diyos?]]''.\n\nIn 2008, she was cast as Chappy Girl in the TV series ''[[Volta (TV series)|Volta]]'', which was adapted from the [[Star Cinema]] [[Volta (film)|film of the same name]].\n\nIn 2010, she had a guest appearance in ''[[George and Cecil]]'', playing the love interest of [[Dino Imperial]]'s Jun. Mendiola revealed that she was pulled out of Habang May Buhay and was cast as Christina in the TV series ''[[Kung Tayo'y Magkakalayo]]'' instead.<ref name=\"Jessy Mendiola on her idol\"/> Mendiola was supposed to appear in ''[[Habang May Buhay]]'' and was featured in the 2008 trailer of the show which was originally titled as Humingi Ako Sa Langit. The TV series, which was supposed to air in 2008, was cancelled, reshot and recast.<ref name='Huming Ako Sa Langit trailer'/> Due to good feedback, her one-week guest appearance in Kung Tayo'y Magkakalayo was extended. She was later cast in ''[[Your Song (TV series)|Your Song Presents:]] [[Gimik 2010]]'',<ref name=\"Gimik 2010\"/><ref name=\"Gimik\"/> playing the role of the reformed rebel teenager Jessy. Mendiola was supposed to appear in ''[[Kokey @ Ako]]'', opposite [[Enrique Gil]], but their characters were written off in favor of [[Melai Cantiveros]] and [[Jason Francisco]].<ref name=\"Enrique\"/> She eventually returned as a recurring character in the last few episodes of Kung Tayo'y Magkakalayo.<ref name=\"Mendiola Prefers to Take it Slow\"/>\n\nShe portrayed lead roles in ''[[Maalaala Mo Kaya]]: \"Marriage Contract\"''<ref name='Marriage Contract'/> and in ''[[Wansapanataym]]: \"Kakambal Ko'y Manika\"''. Her first biggest break was playing the title role in the afternoon TV show, ''[[Sabel (TV series)|Sabel]]''.<ref name='Launching Project'/><ref name=\"Jessy is Sabel\"/>\n\nIn 2011, when Sabel ended, Mendiola joined ''[[ASAP (variety show)|ASAP Rocks]]''. She along with [[Empress Schuck]], [[Enchong Dee]] and [[Sam Concepcion]] are referred to as ASAP's 'Dance Quad'.<ref name=\"Showstopping Performance\"/><ref name=\"Reunion\"/>  Earlier, she portrayed Isabel Valderama in ''[[Agimat: Ang Mga Alamat ni Ramon Revilla|Agimat: Ang Mga Alamat ni Ramon Revilla Presents:]] [[Bianong Bulag]]''. In April, she became a guest judge for ''[[It's Showtime (TV program)|It's Showtime]]'' and appeared as Risa in the Maalaala Mo Kaya episode, \"Medalyon\".<ref name=\"Bolder\"/><ref name=\"Obsession\"/> She also played the role of Jacqueline Marasigan in the primetime TV show, ''[[Budoy]]'', opposite [[Gerald Anderson]] and [[Enrique Gil]].<ref name=\"Gerald Anderson\"/>\n\nIn 2012, she starred in the film ''[[The Reunion (2012 film)|The Reunion]]'', with [[Enchong Dee]], [[Enrique Gil]] and [[Xian Lim]]. She also starred in the afternoon TV show ''[[Precious Hearts Romances Presents]]: [[Paraiso (TV series)|Paraiso]]'', with [[Matteo Guidicelli]], [[Matt Evans]] and [[Jewel Mische]].<ref name=\"PHR: Paraiso\"/>\n\nIn 2013, Mendiola played the titular role in the Philippine remake of ''[[Maria Mercedes (Philippine TV series)|Maria Mercedes]]''.<ref name='Jessy is Maria Mercedes'/> In October, she flew to Korea for a ceremonial appointment by Korean Tourism Organization as the Honorary Ambassador for Korean Tourism.<ref name=\"Honorary Tourism Ambassador\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Mendiola played another lead role in the comedy drama ''[[Must Date the Playboy]]'', alongside [[Kim Chiu]], [[Xian Lim]] and [[Matt Evans]]. and in the romantic family drama ''[[You're My Home (TV series)|You're My Home]]'', alongside [[Dawn Zulueta]], [[Richard Gomez]] and [[JC de Vera]].<ref name='First details'/>\n\nIn 2016, Mendiola was recognized as the No. 1 Sexiest Woman in the Philippines by the men's magazine [[FHM Philippines]].<ref name=\"Sexiest Woman of the Philippines 2016\"/> She landed fourth place in the same list of sexiest women in the Philippines a year after.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/06/29/17/nadine-lustre-tops-fhms-100-sexiest-poll |title=Nadine Lustre Tops FHMS 100 Sexiest Poll |date=June 29, 2017 |work=ABS-CBN News |publisher=ABS-CBN Corporation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629180100/http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/06/29/17/nadine-lustre-tops-fhms-100-sexiest-poll |archive-date=June 29, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=July 14, 2017  }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" <!-- Do not center -->\n|- <!-- Never add unnecessary background colors -->\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes <!-- Do not replace with or add a Network/Channel column. Network rivalry is outside of Wikipedia. Do not replace with an Episode column, Notes column is not limited to episode titles. -->\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Source <!-- Use third party sources other than the actor's IMDB page -->\n|- <!-- Do not add rowspan -->\n| 2004 \n| ''[[Hanggang Kailan]]'' \n| Gina \n| \n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Star Magic Presents]]: [[Abt Ur Luv| Abt Ur Luv Ur Lyf 2]]'' \n| Lheny \n|\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Sineserye Presents]]: [[Natutulog Ba Ang Diyos?]]''\n| Michelle\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2008 \n| ''[[Your Song (TV series)|Your Song Presents]]: Bakit Labis Kitang Mahal'' \n| Ki