elgium exhumes its colonial demons|last1=Osborn|first1=Andrew}}\n* {{cite journal|url=https://edoc.hu-berlin.de/docviews/abstract.php?id=42990|last=G\u00fclstorff|first=Torben|year=2016|place=Berlin|title=Trade follows Hallstein? Deutsche Aktivit\u00e4ten im zentralafrikanischen Raum des Second Scramble.|doi=10.18452/17628}}\n\n{{Africa topics}}\n{{Great Power diplomacy}}\n{{World War I}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scramble For Africa}}\n[[Category:19th century in Africa]]\n[[Category:19th century in international relations]]\n[[Category:20th century in international relations]]\n[[Category:European colonisation in Africa]]\n[[Category:Geopolitical rivalry]]\n[[Category:Partition (politics)]]\n[[Category:Political geography]]\n[[Category:History of Africa]]\n[[Category:History of international relations]]\n[[Category:New Imperialism]]\n[[Category:David Livingstone]]\n[[Category:20th century in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "2601:245:c480:9cb0:7526:8252:6da6:b2c8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eStrategic rivalry)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scramble_for_Africa"}
{"title_page": "FaceBase", "text_new": "{{notability|date=November 2010}}\n\n'''FaceBase''' is an [[NIH]]-supported initiative that began in September 2009.  Funded by the [[National Institute of Dental and Craniofacial Research]], the FaceBase Consortium is a five-year initiative that systematically compiles the biological instructions to construct the middle region of the human face and precisely define the genetics underlying its common [[developmental disorders]] such as [[cleft lip and palate]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nih.gov/news/health/oct2009/nidcr-05.htm |title=NIDCR Launches the FaceBase Consortium |date=5 October 2009 |author=National Institute of Health |publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702094519/http://www.nih.gov/news/health/oct2009/nidcr-05.htm |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref> A range of genetic and environmental factors are thought to contribute to facial clefting<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Dixon | first1 = M. J. \n| last2 = Marazita | first2 = M. L. \n| last3 = Beaty | first3 = T. H. \n| last4 = Murray | first4 = J. C. \n| title = Cleft lip and palate: Understanding genetic and environmental influences \n| doi = 10.1038/nrg2933 \n| journal = Nature Reviews Genetics \n| volume = 12 \n| issue = 3 \n| pages = 167\u2013178 \n| year = 2011 \n| pmid = 21331089 \n| pmc =3086810 \n}}</ref> and FaceBase is designed to enhance investigations into these causes and their outcomes.\n\n==FaceBase Biorepository==\nThe FaceBase Biorepository is a collection or bank of DNA samples and information from families around the world to be used in research studies. Individuals with birth defects that involve the head, face, and eye can participate along with their family members. DNA is collected through blood or saliva and combined with information about the subject's family history and pregnancy history. The goal of the biorepository is to collect samples and data from 5,000 people to drive research studies on the genetic and environmental factors that contribute to craniofacial birth defects. <ref>FaceBase. (2012). ''Biorepository.'' Retrieved from https://www.facebase.org/node/252 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801042420/https://www.facebase.org/node/252 |date=2012-08-01 }}.</ref>\n\n==Gene Wiki==\nSo far, a number of genes have been found to play a role in craniofacial development and the FaceBase project is continuing to research these genes to better understand craniofacial birth defects such as cleft lip and palate. These genes include [[AXIN2]], [[BMP4]], [[FGFR1]], [[FGFR2]], [[FOXE1]], [[IRF6]], [[MAFB (gene)]], [[MMP3]], [[MSX1]], MSX2 ([[Msh homeobox 2]]), MSX3, [[PAX7]], [[PDGFC]], [[PTCH1]], [[SATB2]], [[SOX9]], SUMO1 ([[Small ubiquitin-related modifier 1]]), [[TBX22]], TCOF ([[Treacle protein]]), [[TFAP2A]], [[VAX1]], [[TP63]], [[ARHGAP29]], NOG, [[NTN1]], WNT genes, and locus 8q24. <ref>FaceBase. (2012). ''Gene Wiki''. Retrieved from https://www.facebase.org/resources/gene-wiki {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815113927/https://www.facebase.org/resources/gene-wiki |date=2012-08-15 }}.</ref>\n\n==FaceBase Hub==\nA key part of the initiative is the Hub, which intends to provide easily accessible [[craniofacial]] research data.<ref name=Hocheisser2011>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hochheiser | first1 = H. | last2 = Aronow | first2 = B. J. | last3 = Artinger | first3 = K. | last4 = Beaty | first4 = T. H. | last5 = Brinkley | first5 = J. F. | last6 = Chai | first6 = Y. | last7 = Clouthier | first7 = D. | last8 = Cunningham | first8 = M. L. | last9 = Dixon | first9 = M. | last10 = Donahue | first10 = L. R. | last11 = Fraser | first11 = S. E. | last12 = Hallgrimsson | first12 = B. | last13 = Iwata | first13 = J. | last14 = Klein | first14 = O. | last15 = Marazita | first15 = M. L. | last16 = Murray | first16 = J. C. | last17 = Murray | first17 = S. | last18 = De Villena | first18 = F. P. M. | last19 = Postlethwait | first19 = J. | last20 = Potter | first20 = S. | last21 = Shapiro | first21 = L. | last22 = Spritz | first22 = R. | last23 = Visel | first23 = A. | last24 = Weinberg | first24 = S. M. | last25 = Trainor | first25 = P. A. | title = The FaceBase Consortium: A comprehensive program to facilitate craniofacial research | journal = Developmental Biology | volume = 355 | issue = 2 | pages = 175\u2013182 | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2011.02.033 | pmc = 3440302 | pmid=21458441}}</ref> The FaceBase Hub aims to allow scientists to more rapidly and effectively generate hypotheses and accelerate the pace of their research.<ref>{{Cite journal\n | last1 = Hochheiser | first1 = H.\n | last2 = Aronow | first2 = B. J.\n | last3 = Artinger | first3 = K.\n | last4 = Beaty | first4 = T. H.\n | last5 = Brinkley | first5 = J. F.\n | last6 = Chai | first6 = Y.\n | last7 = Clouthier | first7 = D.\n | last8 = Cunningham | first8 = M. L.\n | last9 = Dixon | first9 = M.\n | last10 = Donahue | first10 = L. R.\n | last11 = Fraser | first11 = S. E.\n | last12 = Hallgrimsson | first12 = B.\n | last13 = Iwata | first13 = J.\n | last14 = Klein | first14 = O.\n | last15 = Marazita | first15 = M. L.\n | last16 = Murray | first16 = J. C.\n | last17 = Murray | first17 = S.\n | last18 = De Villena | first18 = F. P. M.\n | last19 = Postlethwait | first19 = J.\n | last20 = Potter | first20 = S.\n | last21 = Shapiro | first21 = L.\n | last22 = Spritz | first22 = R.\n | last23 = Visel | first23 = A.\n | last24 = Weinberg | first24 = S. M.\n | last25 = Trainor | first25 = P. A.\n | title = The FaceBase Consortium: A comprehensive program to facilitate craniofacial research\n | journal = Developmental Biology\n | volume = 355\n | issue = 2\n | pages = 175\u2013182\n | year = 2011\n | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2011.02.033\n | pmc = 3440302 | pmid=21458441\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebase.org/ Official website]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.dentistryiq.com/index/display/article-display.articles.dentisryiq.clinical.2010.01.facebase_-a_new_research.html|title=FaceBase: a new research consortium to synthesize research results in craniofacial and dental biology|publisher=Dentistry IQ}}\n\n[[Category:Dentistry]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[NameBase]]\n*[[Facebook]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=November 2010}}\n\n'''FaceBase''' is an [[NIH]]-supported initiative that began in September 2009.  Funded by the [[National Institute of Dental and Craniofacial Research]], the FaceBase Consortium is a five-year initiative that systematically compiles the biological instructions to construct the middle region of the human face and precisely define the genetics underlying its common [[developmental disorders]] such as [[cleft lip and palate]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nih.gov/news/health/oct2009/nidcr-05.htm |title=NIDCR Launches the FaceBase Consortium |date=5 October 2009 |author=National Institute of Health |publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702094519/http://www.nih.gov/news/health/oct2009/nidcr-05.htm |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref> A range of genetic and environmental factors are thought to contribute to facial clefting<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Dixon | first1 = M. J. \n| last2 = Marazita | first2 = M. L. \n| last3 = Beaty | first3 = T. H. \n| last4 = Murray | first4 = J. C. \n| title = Cleft lip and palate: Understanding genetic and environmental influences \n| doi = 10.1038/nrg2933 \n| journal = Nature Reviews Genetics \n| volume = 12 \n| issue = 3 \n| pages = 167\u2013178 \n| year = 2011 \n| pmid = 21331089 \n| pmc =3086810 \n}}</ref> and FaceBase is designed to enhance investigations into these causes and their outcomes.\n\n==FaceBase Biorepository==\nThe FaceBase Biorepository is a collection or bank of DNA samples and information from families around the world to be used in research studies. Individuals with birth defects that involve the head, face, and eye can participate along with their family members. DNA is collected through blood or saliva and combined with information about the subject's family history and pregnancy history. The goal of the biorepository is to collect samples and data from 5,000 people to drive research studies on the genetic and environmental factors that contribute to craniofacial birth defects. <ref>FaceBase. (2012). ''Biorepository.'' Retrieved from https://www.facebase.org/node/252 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801042420/https://www.facebase.org/node/252 |date=2012-08-01 }}.</ref>\n\n==Gene Wiki==\nSo far, a number of genes have been found to play a role in craniofacial development and the FaceBase project is continuing to research these genes to better understand craniofacial birth defects such as cleft lip and palate. These genes include [[AXIN2]], [[BMP4]], [[FGFR1]], [[FGFR2]], [[FOXE1]], [[IRF6]], [[MAFB (gene)]], [[MMP3]], [[MSX1]], MSX2 ([[Msh homeobox 2]]), MSX3, [[PAX7]], [[PDGFC]], [[PTCH1]], [[SATB2]], [[SOX9]], SUMO1 ([[Small ubiquitin-related modifier 1]]), [[TBX22]], TCOF ([[Treacle protein]]), [[TFAP2A]], [[VAX1]], [[TP63]], [[ARHGAP29]], NOG, [[NTN1]], WNT genes, and locus 8q24. <ref>FaceBase. (2012). ''Gene Wiki''. Retrieved from https://www.facebase.org/resources/gene-wiki {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815113927/https://www.facebase.org/resources/gene-wiki |date=2012-08-15 }}.</ref>\n\n==FaceBase Hub==\nA key part of the initiative is the Hub, which intends to provide easily accessible [[craniofacial]] research data.<ref name=Hocheisser2011>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hochheiser | first1 = H. | last2 = Aronow | first2 = B. J. | last3 = Artinger | first3 = K. | last4 = Beaty | first4 = T. H. | last5 = Brinkley | first5 = J. F. | last6 = Chai | first6 = Y. | last7 = Clouthier | first7 = D. | last8 = Cunningham | first8 = M. L. | last9 = Dixon | first9 = M. | last10 = Donahue | first10 = L. R. | last11 = Fraser | first11 = S. E. | last12 = Hallgrimsson | first12 = B. | last13 = Iwata | first13 = J. | last14 = Klein | first14 = O. | last15 = Marazita | first15 = M. L. | last16 = Murray | first16 = J. C. | last17 = Murray | first17 = S. | last18 = De Villena | first18 = F. P. M. | last19 = Postlethwait | first19 = J. | last20 = Potter | first20 = S. | last21 = Shapiro | first21 = L. | last22 = Spritz | first22 = R. | last23 = Visel | first23 = A. | last24 = Weinberg | first24 = S. M. | last25 = Trainor | first25 = P. A. | title = The FaceBase Consortium: A comprehensive program to facilitate craniofacial research | journal = Developmental Biology | volume = 355 | issue = 2 | pages = 175\u2013182 | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2011.02.033 | pmc = 3440302 | pmid=21458441}}</ref> The FaceBase Hub aims to allow scientists to more rapidly and effectively generate hypotheses and accelerate the pace of their research.<ref>{{Cite journal\n | last1 = Hochheiser | first1 = H.\n | last2 = Aronow | first2 = B. J.\n | last3 = Artinger | first3 = K.\n | last4 = Beaty | first4 = T. H.\n | last5 = Brinkley | first5 = J. F.\n | last6 = Chai | first6 = Y.\n | last7 = Clouthier | first7 = D.\n | last8 = Cunningham | first8 = M. L.\n | last9 = Dixon | first9 = M.\n | last10 = Donahue | first10 = L. R.\n | last11 = Fraser | first11 = S. E.\n | last12 = Hallgrimsson | first12 = B.\n | last13 = Iwata | first13 = J.\n | last14 = Klein | first14 = O.\n | last15 = Marazita | first15 = M. L.\n | last16 = Murray | first16 = J. C.\n | last17 = Murray | first17 = S.\n | last18 = De Villena | first18 = F. P. M.\n | last19 = Postlethwait | first19 = J.\n | last20 = Potter | first20 = S.\n | last21 = Shapiro | first21 = L.\n | last22 = Spritz | first22 = R.\n | last23 = Visel | first23 = A.\n | last24 = Weinberg | first24 = S. M.\n | last25 = Trainor | first25 = P. A.\n | title = The FaceBase Consortium: A comprehensive program to facilitate craniofacial research\n | journal = Developmental Biology\n | volume = 355\n | issue = 2\n | pages = 175\u2013182\n | year = 2011\n | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2011.02.033\n | pmc = 3440302 | pmid=21458441\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebase.org/ Official website]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.dentistryiq.com/index/display/article-display.articles.dentisryiq.clinical.2010.01.facebase_-a_new_research.html|title=FaceBase: a new research consortium to synthesize research results in craniofacial and dental biology|publisher=Dentistry IQ}}\n\n[[Category:Dentistry]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[namebase]]\n*[[facebook]]\n", "name_user": "Cryptopocalypse", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Capitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FaceBase"}
{"title_page": "FC Barcelona B", "text_new": "{{About|the football team|the basketball team|FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Barcelona B\n| image = \n| fullname = Futbol Club Barcelona \"B\"\n| nickname = Bar\u00e7a B<br>La Mas\u00eda\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1970|6|12}}<br />as ''FC Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic''\n| ground = [[Estadi Johan Cruyff]], [[Sant Joan Desp\u00ed]],<br /> [[Catalonia]], [[Spain]]\n| capacity = 6,000\n| chairman = [[Josep Maria Bartomeu]]\n| chrtitle = President\n| manager = [[Francisco Javier Garc\u00eda Pimienta|Xavi Garc\u00eda Pimienta]]\n| mgrtitle = Head coach\n| league = [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], 8th\n| current = 2018\u201319 FC Barcelona B season\n| website = http://www.fcbarcelona.com\n| pattern_la1 = _fcbarcelona1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _fcbarcelona1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _fcbarcelona1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = _barcelona1920h\n| leftarm1 = 000080\n| body1 = 000080\n| rightarm1 = 000080\n| shorts1 = 000080\n| socks1 = 000080\n| pattern_la2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| leftarm2 = FFDD00\n| body2 = FFDD00\n| rightarm2 = FFDD00\n| shorts2 = FFDD00\n| socks2 = FFDD00\n}}\n{{FC Barcelona sections}}\n'''Futbol Club Barcelona B''' is a [[List of football clubs in Spain|Spanish football team]] based in [[Barcelona]], in the autonomous community of [[Catalonia]].\n\nFounded in 1970 as '''FC Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic''', it is the [[reserve team]] of [[FC Barcelona]], and currently plays in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], holding home matches at the [[Estadi Johan Cruyff]].\n\nReserve teams in [[Spanish football league system|Spain]] play in the same league system as the senior team, rather than in a reserve team league. They must play at least one level below their main side, and thus Barcelona B are ineligible for promotion to [[La Liga]]. They also cannot play in the [[Copa del Rey]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Espanya Industrial===\n{{Main|CD Condal}}\nFounded on 1 August 1934 as ''Societat Esportiva Industrial Espanya'', the club was originally the sports team of the factory with the same name, and its shirt featured blue and white vertical stripes. The company was owned by the family of Josep Antoni de Albert, who was briefly president of [[FC Barcelona]] in 1943; during Albert's presidency the club, now known as ''Club Deportivo Espanya Industrial'', became Barcelona's [[reserve team]] and began to play home games at [[Camp de Les Corts]].\n\nInitially, Industrial played in the local regional leagues but, in 1950, it was promoted to [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]], reaching [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] two years later. In [[1952\u201353 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1953]] the club finished as runners-up in both the league and the promotion play-off but, being a nursery club of Barcelona, it was unable to move up a division.\n\n===CD Condal===\n{{Main|CD Condal}}\nAfter winning another promotion play-off in 1956, Espanya Industrial became independent of FC Barcelona and was renamed Club Deportivo Condal. The club wore blue shirts with two white diagonals stripes.\n\nCondal competed once in [[La Liga]], in the [[1956\u201357 La Liga|1956\u201357 season]], being relegated as 16th and last. In 1968 the club rejoined the Barcelona family as its reserve team, and adopted the ''blaugrana'' colours.\n\n===Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic/Barcelona B===\n[[Image:Barcelona Atl\u00e9tico.png|thumb|150px|Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic crest]]\nIn 1970, Barcelona president Agust\u00ed Montal decided to [[Mergers and acquisitions|merge]] Condal with another junior club, Atl\u00e8tic Catalunya, and formed Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic. Atl\u00e8tic was founded in 1965 as a result of the merger of two other teams: UE Catalunya de Les Corts (founded in 1918 as Catalunya Sporting Club) and CD Fabra Coats (1926).\n\nUnder the new denomination the B-team played a total of ten seasons in the second level. At the end of [[1988\u201389 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1988\u201389]] the side returned to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] \u2013 the new third level created in 1977 \u2013 after ranking 17th.\n\nIn 1990 the team was renamed Barcelona B, but club president [[Joan Laporta]] changed the name back to Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic in 2008. Two years later, his successor [[Sandro Rosell]] returned to the previous denomination.<ref>[http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20100703/53957128068/noticia/el-barsa-atletic-volvera-a-llamarse-barsa-b.html El Bar\u00e7a Atl\u00e8tic volver\u00e1 a llamarse Bar\u00e7a B (Bar\u00e7a Atl\u00e8tic to be called Bar\u00e7a B again)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818170347/http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20100703/53957128068/noticia/el-barsa-atletic-volvera-a-llamarse-barsa-b.html |date=2010-08-18 }}; [[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]], 3 July 2010 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nFormer club player [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] (he also played for [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]) succeeded [[Pep Guardiola]] as team manager in the summer of 2008, as the latter was appointed main squad coach.<ref>[http://deportes.elpais.com/deportes/2008/05/26/actualidad/1211786516_850215.html Luis Enrique, nuevo entrenador del Barcelona B (Luis Enrique, new Barcelona B coach)]; [[El Pa\u00eds]], 26 May 2008 {{in lang|es}}</ref> In [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2009\u201310]] the club finished second in Group III and returned to division two after an absence of 11 years; this was followed by a third-place in [[2010\u201311 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]], but the team was not eligible for promotion.\n\n==Season to season==\n{| \n|valign=\"top\" width=0%|\n{|  class=\"wikitable\" \n|- style=\"background:#f0f6fa;\"\n!Season\n!Tier\n!Division\n!Place\n|-style=\"background:#FF7F00;\"\n|