P|name=[[Mika M\u00e1rmol]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=37|pos=FW|nat=ESP|name=[[Gerard Fern\u00e1ndez Castellano|Gerard Fern\u00e1ndez]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=38|pos=DF|nat=NED|name=[[Xavier Mbuyamba]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=40|pos=DF|nat=ESP|name=[[Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ednez (Spanish footballer)|Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ednez]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=41|pos=GK|nat=ESP|name=[[Ramon Vila (goalkeeper|Ramon Vila]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Current technical staff===\n{{Fb cs header}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=Head coach |s=[[Francisco Javier Garc\u00eda Pimienta|Xavi Garc\u00eda Pimienta]]}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=Assistant coach |s=Pau Mart\u00ed}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=Assistant coach |s=Albert Peris}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=Fitness coach |s=Marc Guitart}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=Goalkeeping coach |s=[[Carles Busquets]]}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=Technical assistant |s=Albert Peris}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg= |p=[[FC Barcelona (youth)|Juvenil A]] coach |s=Franc Artiga}}\n{{Fb cs footer|u=21 May 2018 |s=[https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/barca-b/staff/players FC Barcelona B]|date=31 January 2017}}\n\n==Former players==\n{{See also|Category:FC Barcelona B players}}\n\n==Former coaches==\n{|\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top\"\n||\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Josep Seguer]] (1970\u201372)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Luis Aloy Vidal|Luis Aloy]] (1972\u201376)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Laureano Ruiz]] (1976\u201378)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Antoni Torres]] (1978\u201379, 1980\u201383)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Joan Segarra]] (1979\u201380)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jaume Oliv\u00e9]] (1980)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Romero (manager)|Jos\u00e9 Luis Romero]] (1983\u201384)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Joan Mart\u00ednez Vilaseca]] (1984\u201387)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Llu\u00eds Pujol]] (1987\u201389)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Quique Costas]] (1989\u201396, 2001\u201303, 2005\u201307)\n||\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Juande Ramos]] (1996\u201397)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Josep Maria Gonzalvo]] (1997\u201301)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pere Gratac\u00f3s]] (2003\u201305)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pep Guardiola]] (2007\u201308)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] (2008\u201311)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Eusebio Sacrist\u00e1n]] (2011\u201315)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jordi Vinyals]] (2015)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Gerard L\u00f3pez]] (2015\u20132018)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Francisco Javier Garc\u00eda Pimienta|Xavi Garc\u00eda Pimienta]] (2018\u2013)\n|}\n\n==Top scorers==\n\n===All competitions===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=text-align:center\n!Ranking\n!Nationality\n!Name\n!Years\n!Goals\n|-\n|1||align=left|{{ESP}}||[[Jonathan Soriano]]||2009\u20132012||55\n|-\n|2||align=left|{{NGA}}||[[Haruna Babangida]]||1998\u20132004||46\n|-\n|3||align=left|{{ESP}}||[[Sergio Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1983)|Sergio Garc\u00eda]]||2002\u20132004||34\n|-\n|4||align=left|{{ESP}}||[[Mario Rosas]]||1997\u20132000||30\n|-\n|5|| align=\"left\" |{{ESP}}||[[Joan Verd\u00fa]]||2002\u20132006||30\n|-\n|6||align=left|{{ESP}}||[[Nolito]]||2008\u20132011||29\n|-\n|7|| align=\"left\" |{{ESP}}||[[Roberto Trashorras]]||1999\u20132003||29\n|-\n|8|| align=\"left\" |{{CMR}}||[[Jean Marie Dongou]]||2011\u20132016||29\n|-\n|9||align=left|{{ESP}}||[[Thomas Christiansen]]||1991\u20131996||28\n|-\n|10|| align=\"left\" |{{ESP}}||[[Jon Bakero Escudero]]||1992\u20131997||28\n|}\n\n==Stadium==\n{{Main|Estadi Johan Cruyff}}\n[[File:Barcelona-Mini Estadi.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The Mini Estadi, home stadium until 2019]]\nOn 23 September 1982 the [[Mini Estadi]] was inaugurated by Barcelona president [[Josep Llu\u00eds N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]. Next to the ground there are two training pitches, pitch 3 and 4, which have artificial turf \u2013 the latter has a regulation size of 100 x 70 metres and has seating for 1,000 spectators.\n\nMini Estadi has also hosted games for the [[Andorra national football team]], and the [[Barcelona Dragons]] of [[American football]].\n\nAs a part of the Espai Bar\u00e7a project, the Mini Estadi was demolished and the [[Estadi Johan Cruyff]] was opened to take its place starting in the 2019\u201320 season. Also, as part of this project the [[Camp Nou]] will undergo renovation.<ref>https://www.fcbarcelona.es/club/instalaciones/ficha/que-es-l-espai-barca</ref>\n\n==La Masia==\nInaugurated on 26 September 1966, [[La Masia]] is the name given to Barcelona's training facilities located near the Camp Nou in the [[Les Corts (district)|Les Corts]] district of Barcelona. It is an ancient country residence built in 1702 and once Camp Nou was inaugurated in 1957, the building was remodelled and extended for use as the club's social headquarters.\n\nIn 1979, La Masia became the residence of young players from outside of the city. In the following decades the academy forged several players that would later appear for both the main squad and the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]], [[Guillermo Amor]], [[Albert Ferrer]], [[Iv\u00e1n de la Pe\u00f1a]], [[Carles Puyol]], [[Gerard L\u00f3pez]], [[Xavi]], [[V\u00edctor Vald\u00e9s]], and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] being amongst the most prominent.<ref>[http://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/facilites-and-services/masia La Masia history]; Barcelona's official website</ref><ref>[http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/la-masia-the-footballing-factory-par-excellence/ La Masia \u2013 A footballing factory par excellence]; Total Bar\u00e7a, 22 April 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/els-jugadors-formats-a-la-masia-superen-el-millor-registre-golejador-en-la-historia-del-club La Masia graduates have scored more goals this season than in any other season in the Club's history]; Barcelona's official website, 18 March 2012</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/barca-b Team profile at official website]\n*[http://www.futbolme.com/com/index_equipo.asp?id_equipo=330 Futbolme team profile] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/e/e71.html BDFutbol team profile]\n\n{{FC Barcelona}}\n{{Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B Group 3}}\n{{Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barcelona B}}\n[[Category:FC Barcelona B| ]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona|*B]]\n[[Category:Spanish reserve football teams]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the football team|the basketball team|FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Barcelona B\n| image = \n| fullname = Futbol Club Barcelona \"B\"\n| nickname = Bar\u00e7a B<br>La Mas\u00eda\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1970|6|12}}<br />as ''FC Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic''\n| ground = [[Estadi Johan Cruyff]], [[Sant Joan Desp\u00ed]],<br /> [[Catalonia]], [[Spain]]\n| capacity = 6,000\n| chairman = [[Josep Maria Bartomeu]]\n| chrtitle = President\n| manager = [[Francisco Javier Garc\u00eda Pimienta|Xavi Garc\u00eda Pimienta]]\n| mgrtitle = Head coach\n| league = [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], 8th\n| current = 2018\u201319 FC Barcelona B season\n| website = http://www.fcbarcelona.com\n| pattern_la1 = _fcbarcelona1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _fcbarcelona1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _fcbarcelona1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = _barcelona1920h\n| leftarm1 = 000080\n| body1 = 000080\n| rightarm1 = 000080\n| shorts1 = 000080\n| socks1 = 000080\n| pattern_la2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = _fcbarcelona1920a\n| leftarm2 = FFDD00\n| body2 = FFDD00\n| rightarm2 = FFDD00\n| shorts2 = FFDD00\n| socks2 = FFDD00\n}}\n{{FC Barcelona sections}}\n'''Futbol Club Barcelona B''' is a [[List of football clubs in Spain|Spanish football team]] based in [[Barcelona]], in the autonomous community of [[Catalonia]].\n\nFounded in 1970 as '''FC Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic''', it is the [[reserve team]] of [[FC Barcelona]], and currently plays in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], holding home matches at the [[Estadi Johan Cruyff]].\n\nReserve teams in [[Spanish football league system|Spain]] play in the same league system as the senior team, rather than in a reserve team league. They must play at least one level below their main side, and thus Barcelona B are ineligible for promotion to [[La Liga]]. They also cannot play in the [[Copa del Rey]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Espanya Industrial===\n{{Main|CD Condal}}\nFounded on 1 August 1934 as ''Societat Esportiva Industrial Espanya'', the club was originally the sports team of the factory with the same name, and its shirt featured blue and white vertical stripes. The company was owned by the family of Josep Antoni de Albert, who was briefly president of [[FC Barcelona]] in 1943; during Albert's presidency the club, now known as ''Club Deportivo Espanya Industrial'', became Barcelona's [[reserve team]] and began to play home games at [[Camp de Les Corts]].\n\nInitially, Industrial played in the local regional leagues but, in 1950, it was promoted to [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]], reaching [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] two years later. In [[1952\u201353 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1953]] the club finished as runners-up in both the league and the promotion play-off but, being a nursery club of Barcelona, it was unable to move up a division.\n\n===CD Condal===\n{{Main|CD Condal}}\nAfter winning another promotion play-off in 1956, Espanya Industrial became independent of FC Barcelona and was renamed Club Deportivo Condal. The club wore blue shirts with two white diagonals stripes.\n\nCondal competed once in [[La Liga]], in the [[1956\u201357 La Liga|1956\u201357 season]], being relegated as 16th and last. In 1968 the club rejoined the Barcelona family as its reserve team, and adopted the ''blaugrana'' colours.\n\n===Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic/Barcelona B===\n[[Image:Barcelona Atl\u00e9tico.png|thumb|150px|Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic crest]]\nIn 1970, Barcelona president Agust\u00ed Montal decided to [[Mergers and acquisitions|merge]] Condal with another junior club, Atl\u00e8tic Catalunya, and formed Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic. Atl\u00e8tic was founded in 1965 as a result of the merger of two other teams: UE Catalunya de Les Corts (founded in 1918 as Catalunya Sporting Club) and CD Fabra Coats (1926).\n\nUnder the new denomination the B-team played a total of ten seasons in the second level. At the end of [[1988\u201389 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1988\u201389]] the side returned to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] \u2013 the new third level created in 1977 \u2013 after ranking 17th.\n\nIn 1990 the team was renamed Barcelona B, but club president [[Joan Laporta]] changed the name back to Barcelona Atl\u00e8tic in 2008. Two years later, his successor [[Sandro Rosell]] returned to the previous denomination.<ref>[http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20100703/53957128068/noticia/el-barsa-atletic-volvera-a-llamarse-barsa-b.html El Bar\u00e7a Atl\u00e8tic volver\u00e1 a llamarse Bar\u00e7a B (Bar\u00e7a Atl\u00e8tic to be called Bar\u00e7a B again)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818170347/http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20100703/53957128068/noticia/el-barsa-atletic-volvera-a-llamarse-barsa-b.html |date=2010-08-18 }}; [[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]], 3 July 2010 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nFormer club player [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] (he also played for [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]) succeeded [[Pep Guardiola]] as team manager in the summer of 2008, as the latter was appointed main squad coach.<ref>[http://deportes.elpais.com/deportes/2008/05/26/actualidad/1211786516_850215.html Luis Enrique, nuevo entrenador del Barcelona B (Luis Enrique, new Barcelona B coach)]; [[El Pa\u00eds]], 26 May 2008 {{in lang|es}}</ref> In [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2009\u201310]] the club finished second in Group III and returned to division two after an absence of 11 years; this was followed by a third-place in [[2010\u201311 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]], but the team was not eligible for promotion.\n\n==Season to season==\n{| \n|valign=\"top\" width=0%|\n{|  class=\"wikitable\" \n|- style=\"background:#f0f6fa;\"\n!Season\n!Tier\n!Division\n!Place\n|-style=\"background:#FF7F00;\"\n| 1970\u201371\n| 3\n| [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|3\u00aa]] \n| 4th\n|-style=\"background:#FF7F00;\"\n| 1971\u201372\n| 3\n| [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|3\u00aa]] \n| 1st\n\n|-style=\"background:#CECE1B;\"\n| 1972\u201373\n| 4\n| Regional\n| 1st\n|-style=\"background:#FF7F00;\"\n| 1973\u201374\n| 3\n| [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|3\u00aa]] \n| 1st\n|-style=\"background:silver;\"\n| [[1974\u201375 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1974\u201375]]\n| 2\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2\u00aa]]\n| 10th\n|-style=\"background:silver;\"\n| [[1975\u201376 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1975\u201376]]\n| 2\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2\u00aa]]\n| 6th\n|-style=\"background:silver;\"\n| [[1976\u201377 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1976\u201377]]\n| 2\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2\u00aa]]\n| 20th\n|-style=\"background:#BF8D5B;\"\n| [[1977\u201378 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1977\u201378]]\n| 3\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2\u00aa B]]\n| 5th\n|-style=\"background:#BF8D5B;\"\n| [[1978\u201379 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1978\u201379]]\n| 3\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2\u00aa B]]\n| 4th\n|-style=\"background:#BF8D5B;\"\n| [[1979\u201380 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1979\u201380]]\n| 3\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2\u00aa B]]\n| 14th\n|-style=\"background:#BF8D5B;\"\n| [[1980\u201381 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1980\u201381]]\n| 3\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2\u00aa B]]\n| 3rd\n|-style=\"background:#BF8D5B;\"\n| [[1981\u201382 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1981\u201382]]\n| 3\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2\u00aa B]]\n| 1st\n|-style=\"background:silver;\"\n| [[1982\u201383 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1982\u201383]]\n| 2\n| [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2\u00aa]]\n| 11th